<FIRST>u a AM-MexicanDebt     07-14 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexican Debt,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush to Give Mexico $1 Billion Bridge Loan, Reports Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is preparing to grant
Mexico a temporary loan of $1 billion to $2 billion to help bring an
agreement with U.S. banks on debt restructuring to a close,
according to published reports.
   The New York Times reported in Friday editions that the loan is
contingent on an agreement between Mexico and its creditors to
reduce and rearrange $54 billion in existing loans.
   Other countries and perhaps commercial sources may also
contribute to the temporary loan, the Times said.
   In its Friday editions, The Washington Post said that Mexico and
the banks had reached a tentative deal.
   A senior government official in Washington told The Associated
Press that he could not confirm the reports because the officials
involved were with President Bush in Paris for the seven-nation
economic summit conference.
   He said, however, that he did not believe Mexico had reached a
deal. On Saturday, the negotiators for the two parties said that
they were near an agreement.
   ``There would have been great pleasure'' if Mexico and the banks
could have agreed on a deal before the Paris summit, but when it
became clear the negotiations would span the summit ``we weren't
particularly uptight about it,'' said the official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The Mexican government has said it wants to reach an agreement
before accepting new loans.
</TEXT>
