<DOCNO> AP890714-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 0039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-CruiseMissiles     07-14 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cruise Missiles,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet General Advances New Cruise Missile Idea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet military would be willing to give up
sea-launched nuclear cruise missiles if the United States would too,
a senior Soviet general is quoted as saying.
   In a report of an interview in Moscow, The Washington Post in
Friday editions quotes Col. Gen. Nikolai Chervov, chief of the arms
control section of the Soviet General Staff, as saying, ``If I were
determining policy, then I'd accept it.''
   The general said it was a ``progressive suggestion'' to eliminate
nuclear cruise missiles.
   The Soviets, he said, would prefer to give up all cruise missiles
at sea, but faced with the U.S. Navy's strong desire to keep
conventionally armed missiles ``we are coming to this,'' Chervov
said.
   ``How the Soviet Union decides, we'll see.''
   Chervov was reported as telling his interviewers Soviet military
spending in 1987 and 1988 was 10 billion rubles, $16 billion at
official exchange rates, below original plans, and would fall by a
similar amount in each of the next two three-year periods. This
would mean a 25 percent cut by 1995, he said.
</TEXT>
