   It's a stand that would bring cheers from
anyone with a pile of parking tickets.
   Police Chief Thomas O'Loughlin is running out of the tickets, and
selectmen in this wealthy Boston suburb won't authorize the
expenditure of $1,500 to buy 5,000 more.
   ``There's going to be some problems,'' O'Loughlin said Thursday.
He has 50 tickets left, enough to last about 10 days.
   Lewis Russell, the selectmen's chairman, said if the ticket
purchase is ``that important, he will buy (the tickets). Something
else in his budget will have to be reduced instead.''
   Town officials planned to meet today to further discuss the issue.
   The police chief doesn't think voters would mind paying the
$1,500 for the new tickets. He said as much as they hate getting
ticketed, they hate being blocked by illegally parked cars more. The
return on the investment also is attractive, he said.
   Parking fines are $5 to $10, and the new tickets would generate
about $37,500, he said.
   Once the tickets run out, O'Loughlin said he'll tell officers to
tow vehicles parked in tow zones.
   But car owners who don't feed parking meters will get a free ride.
