<FIRST>r a PM-BadChecks     07-14 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bad Checks,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merchant Sheds Light on Bad Check Writers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Corder says people who write bad
checks for items at his convenience store now will pay: He's
displaying their names on a large sign out front.
   ``If you saw the stack of bad checks I got in here, you'd know
why I was doing this,'' said Corder, whose convenience store is
about four miles south of South Congaree, a small town west of
Columbia. ``The sheriff's deputies can only do so much, and it's
time I did something.''
   The names of those who write checks that bounce are on a large
yellow marquee with flashing lights in front of Corder's Open Air
Market.
   ``I had three bad checks from the same guy on three consecutive
days. Now that made me mad,'' Corder said.
   Corder said he has about 30 bad checks totaling about $1,000, but
there's only room on the sign for four names. So he's putting up
another sign.
   He said he telephones and sends a registered letter requesting
payment from people who write bad checks. If they don't respond, he
puts their name up 18 days after the bad check arrives back from the
bank.
   People can get their names off the sign by paying him the money
owed, Corder said.
   ``It's armed robbery, that's what it is,'' he said. ``They rob
with a pen, not a pistol.''
</TEXT>
