<DOCNO> AP890714-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 0721EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     07-14 0940</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,920</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA Sees More Hogs Go to Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hog producers are cutting back on their
breeding stock but are sending enough animals to market that 1989
pork output should be up from last year, says the Agriculture
Department.
   ``Hog producers have experienced a steep drop in returns over the
past year but have made only a modest cutback in hog numbers,'' the
department's Economic Research Service said Thursday.
   On June 1, the number of hogs kept for breeding was 3 percent
below a year ago, while market hogs _ those destined for slaughter _
were down only 1 percent. And the report said producers expect to
have ``about the same number'' of sows farrow this summer and next
fall as they did last year.
   Commercial output of pork for all of 1989 was estimated at 15.9
billion pounds, up 2 percent from last year and the most since 1980.
Market prices of hogs going to slaughter are expected to average $40
to $43 per 100 pounds, compared with $43 in 1988.
   The all-cut retail price of pork may be around $1.80 per pound in
1989, down 3 to 5 cents per pound from last year's average, the
report said.
   Beef production was projected at 22.8 billion pounds this year,
down 3 percent from 1988 production. Last month the agency forecast
a 2 percent reduction in beef output.
   Prices of Choice-grade steers are expected to average $71 to $74
per 100 pounds, compared with $70 in 1988. Feeder steers may average
about the same as last year's $84 per hundredweight, the report said.
   ``The relatively high feeder cattle prices should provide an
incentive for cow-calf producers to retain heifers to rebuild their
(breeding) herds,'' the report said.
   As a result of smaller beef supplies, average retail prices were
forecast to rise 10 to 15 cents per pound, on an all-cut average,
from the 1988 level of $2.55 per pound.
   Relatively high returns are encouraging broiler producers to
expand production by about 6 percent this year to 17.1 billion
pounds, the report said. Last month's forecast was a 1989 increase
of about 5 percent.
   Wholesale prices were forecast at 60 to 63 cents this year, up
from an average of 56 cents in 1988.
   Turkey output is expected to increase about 4 percent this year
after a 6 percent increase in 1988. The June forecast indicated a 3
percent increase. Wholesale turkey hen prices were indicated at 68
to 71 cents per pound, compared with 61 cents last year.
   Egg production may decline about 2 percent this year, following a
slight drop in 1988, the report said. Prices paid to producers were
forecast at 73 to 76 cents per dozen, up from 62 cents last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When city people move to the suburbs, they
sometimes are bothered by pesky flies from a nearby farm. And that
could lead to bad feelings and even lawsuits, says the Agriculture
Department.
   ``We've seen instances all over the country where urban
encroachment in agricultural areas has caused problems for
homeowners and agricultural producers,'' says Ralph A. Bram of the
department's Agricultural Research Service.
   Cities are sprawling into the countryside at the estimated rate
of 900,000 to 1.5 million acres a year, he said Thursday in an
agency report. And to newcomers flies and barnyard odors are not
part of their idyllic country dream.
   Some flies can travel great distances from manure piles or other
barnyard breeding places to find targets. One kind _ the stable fly
_ can migrate up to 135 miles.
   Bram is the national program leader for insects affecting humans
at the agency's research facility in Beltsville, Md.
   ``We have to learn how to increase non-chemical fly control and
how to make the same chemicals we have work better,'' he said. ``It
goes beyond relying on screen doors, sprays and swatters.''
   Possible tactics include several non-chemical baits in traps to
lure flies; natural predators such as wasps that prey flies while in
their pupa stage of development; and natural organisms such as fungi
and bacteria that attack flies in cattle feedlots.
   The USDA attack is directed at four main kinds of flies:
   _Stable flies, which have biting mouth parts and feed on blood.
   _House flies, which secrete digestive enzymes onto their food,
then suck up both enzymes and food.
   _Horn flies, which bother only livestock on pastures and
rangeland.
   _Face flies, also pests of livestock, but an annoyance to
homeowners in the fall.
   Stable flies and house flies from farms are the major problem
species for homeowners, said Gustave D. Thomas, an entomologist and
research leader at the agency's Midwest Livestock Insects Research
laboratory, Lincoln, Neb.
   ``In the United States, the stable fly is estimated to cost $400
million annually in damage to cattle,'' he said. ``It's hard to put
a dollar value on the damage caused by the house fly. But worldwide,
this fly may rank in the top 10 insect problems because it can
transmit a lot of diseases.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World oilseed production in 1989-90 is expected
to be at a record level of around 215.4 million metric tons, up 8
percent from last year, says the Agriculture Department.
   The U.S. share is expected to be about 60.7 million tons, up 21
percent from last year. Most will be soybeans from the 1989 crop,
currently projected at 53.1 million tons, or 1.95 billion bushels.
   Last year's U.S. soybean harvest was 41.9 million tons, or 1.54
billion bushels. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to
36.7 bushels of soybeans.
</TEXT>
