<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 0350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ForestDeals     07-14 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Forest Deals,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Deals Blow to Companies Cutting Alaskan Forest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alaska's governor and House representative say
legislation to cancel sweetheart deals two companies have to cut
timber in Alaska's huge Tongass National Forest Forest is a case of
environmentalists going too far.
   The bill, approved Thursday by a 356-60 vote, would terminate
50-year contracts with the Louisiana Pacific-Ketchikan and the
Alaska Pulp Co., a Japanese firm, in the southeastern Alaskan forest.
   Proponents claim the companies have abused their special
relationship and stifled competition from other companies while
getting trees at bargain-basement prices.
   Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., called the timber contracts a
``raid on taxpayers.''
   ``The federal government has spent $362 million on Tongass timber
subsidies since 1982,'' said Miller. ``But because the government
has assessed the value of the trees at rates set in 1956, the U.S.
Treasury has received only $3.9 million on its $362 million
investment.''
   The size of West Virginia and Delaware combined, the forest is
treasured by environmentalists as a habitat for grizzly bear and
bald eagles and contains the largest spawning area for salmon.
   It's also one of two remaining sections of a rain forest that
once extended northward from northern California and is considered
an important protection against global warming.
   But Alaskan officials say the vote ignored the state's interests.
   ``Today's House action is an unfortunate case of congressmen from
outside Alaska voting on the livelihoods of Alaskans,'' Gov. Steve
Cowper said. ``Alaskans deserve better and I suspect we'll get it
when this measure reaches the Senate.''
   Republican Rep. Don Young, Alaska's lone representative in the
House, said the vote demonstrated the power of environmentalists who
ignore the need of Alaskans to find jobs. He claims 6,000 jobs would
be lost if the lumber companies go out of business.
   ``I'm terribly disappointed,'' he said.
   Proponents say competition would be enhanced, however.
   ``If we cancel these contracts, it doesn't drive the timber
industry out of Alaska,'' said Robert Mrazek, D-N.Y., co-sponsor of
the bill. ``It simply puts these companies on the same footing as
other companies.''
   Young, Cowper and many members of Congress, including Agriculture
Committee Chairman Kika de la Garza, D-Texas, favor a version that
would have called for renegotiation rather than cancellation of the
timber contracts. The Agriculture Committee oversees the Forest
Service.
   But that version was rejected 269-144 on Thursday.
   Young said if the bill is not changed in the Senate, it will be
vetoed by President Bush.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter has already said he would
recommend a veto of legislation that called for termination of the
contracts.
   The House Interior Committee, whose chairman Rep. Morris Udall,
D-Ariz., vowed nine years ago to end the 50-year contracts, is also
trying to attach the bill to deficit-reducing legislation which
staff members believe would have better chance of becoming law.
   By repealing a $40 million annual appropriation that aided the
lumber companies, the Tongass Timber Reform Act would save the
federal government almost $200 million over five years, after
subtracting added expenses the bill creates.
   The legislation also would designate 23 areas as wilderness,
barring timber harvesting and development on 1.8 million acres; and
ban logging within 100 feet of salmon streams.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
