<FIRST>r a PM-Lites SUB a0426 07-14 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites, SUB, a0426,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st item to UPDATE with Presley estate officials changing
minds and saying Elvis likeness may be used in parade.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rosy likeness of rock 'n' roll king Elvis
Presley will appear on Mississippi's entry in the Tournament of
Roses Parade on New Year's day after all.
   Barry Ward, a Memphis, Tenn., attorney representing Presley's
estate, said Thursday that an earlier decision against allowing use
of the likeness had been reversed. The Mississippi parade entry is
planned as a tribute to the Magnolia State's musicians.
   ``The estate does not like, normally, to have Elvis associated
with any other artists,'' Ward said. ``The other artists that are
going to be featured on the float are outstanding in their field,
even though it was a different field from Elvis'.''
   With the floral bust of the Tupelo-born rocker will be likenesses
of bluesman B.B. King, opera diva Leontyne Price and country singer
Tammy Wynette.
   Ward said the original decision was reconsidered because of the
float's importance to Mississippi and Mississippians.
   ``We're celebrating around the office,'' said Pat Frascogna,
chairwoman of the Mississippi float committee. ``I've never seen
anything change so fast in my life. We were dismayed at their
earlier decision.''
   Her organization, the non-profit Mississippi Tournament of Roses
Association, will launch the float in the 1990 parade.
   The reversal ended a frantic search for an Elvis replacement.
Choices included Louisiana native Jerry Lee Lewis, who now lives in
Mississippi, and Jimmy Buffet, Conway Twitty, Charlie Pride, Jimmie
Rodgers and Bobbie Gentry.
   The $102,500 float was already under construction in Pasadena,
Calif., where the parade is held.
   The Presley estate's initial refusal outraged some Mississippians
and sparked a Jackson radio station's letter-writing campaign
intended to shame estate representatives into changing their minds.
</TEXT>
