<FIRST>r w PM-HUD-Houston     07-14 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD-Houston,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer, Late With Payments to HUD, Barred From Doing Government Business</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-HUD Probe, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Houston-area lawyer is barred from doing
business with the federal government because he was slow in turning
over some $1.5 million from sales of property owned by the
Department of Housing and Urban Development.
   ``We have not kept any money,'' Larry E. Thomas, who had worked
as a private closing agent for HUD, said Thursday.
   A HUD official, Wayne Sevier, in the department's Fort Worth
office, confirmed that ``practically all of the money has been
recovered.''
   The department, which estimates it has lost about $20 million
from closing agents who sold HUD property and kept the money, sent
Thomas a letter two weeks ago telling him he can't do any more work
for the government.
   The ban applies to all agencies of the executive branch of
government, the letter said.
   In recent years, HUD hired private contractors, including Thomas,
to handle the paperwork for closing the sales of property the
department took over through foreclosure. Once the sale is closed,
the agents are to turn over the money to the federal Treasury by
wire within a few days.
   Thomas, speaking in a telephone interview from Missouri City,
Texas, acknowledged he had been late in giving the money to the
department _ sometimes by months _ but said it was due to one
paperwork problem or another.
   ``Whether it's `late' or whether he didn't plan to do it, who
knows?'' said Sevier. ``Anyway, it's been turned over to our
inspector general and possibly to Justice (the Justice Department)
for action.''
   Thomas said he did not profit by hanging onto the money because
it had been kept in an account that did not bear interest.
   ``The only reason that there would be any delay would be because
of the incorrect reporting of the taxes that we might receive from
the tax people that we use here, or in-house missed communications
over at the department, getting them signed in the right amount of
time,'' Thomas said.
   Thomas said he was not surprised to be slapped with a ban on
doing contract work for the government because of all the attention
that has been focused on closing agents and other scandals at HUD.
   One former closing agent, Marilyn Harrell of Maryland, has become
the most widely known because of her nickname, ``Robin HUD,'' given
because she said she used some of her stolen money to help buy
houses and cars for the poor. In all, she admits stealing more than
$5 million.
</TEXT>
