<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 0423EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TaxBill     07-14 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tax Bill,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Interest Writeoff Could be Dropped a Year Early</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Should stand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House tax-writers want millions of people who
deduct consumer interest to give up the writeoff a year earlier so
bankers and corporate executives may keep a special tax benefit of
their own.
   That unusual tradeoff has been written by the House Ways and
Means Committee into a bill designed to raise $5.3 billion in new
revenue for deficit reduction during the budget year that begins
Oct. 1.
   The committee also signaled Thursday that it is likely to
recommend significant changes in the surtax that finances
catastrophic health insurance for older Americans. Aides said there
also is considerable sentiment to make some cut in the capital gains
tax, although not necessarily as President Bush has recommended.
   But on a 25-11 vote, the committee rejected a plan by Rep. Bill
Archer, R-Texas, to tackle the catastrophic and capital gains issues
together. His amendment would have delayed for one year the Medicare
surtax on older Americans and used a lower capital gains tax to pay
for the bulk of the insurance program.
   Committee aides said the panel is likely to make some change in
the catastrophic insurance tax next week. Congress has been flooded
with mail from older Americans with higher incomes who now must pay
a surtax of up to $800 this year for federal insurance against costs
of catastrophic illness.
   It is far from certain, the aides added, that the capital gains
tax will be cut. Many Democrats are opposed because the bulk of the
benefit would go to high-income taxpayers.
   The Bush administration contends a capital gains tax cut, which
affects profits from stocks and other assets, would raise money and
thus could be used to reduce the deficit. Congressional economists
insist it would lose money after the first year.
   By a voice vote, the panel eliminated from the deficit-reduction
package an increase in taxes on snuff and pipe and chewing tobacco.
The three products would have been taxed at $2.67 a pound; snuff now
is taxed at 24 cents; pipe tobacco at 45 cents and chewing tobacco
at 8 cents.
   In place of those increases, the committee agreed to speed up
collection of taxes from dividends received from mutual funds.
   The biggest single revenue-raiser, affecting corporations that
use employee stock-ownership plans to avoid takeover and banks that
lend to ESOPs, was scaled back. It was to finance part of that
scaleback that the committee agreed to a quicker phase-out of the
itemized deduction for consumer interest.
   Only 20 percent of interest on loans for automobiles, education
and credit cards is deductible. Under present law, that is scheduled
to drop next year to 10 percent. Under the committee's action, the
interest deduction would die at the end of this year.
   About 24 million couples and individuals take a deduction for
consumer interest.
   The committee wants to reduce two existing tax benefits connected
with ESOPs, under which workers are given shares of the companies
where they are employed.
   Under the committee's action Thursday, a bank that lends money to
finance an ESOP purchase of stock could continue avoiding tax on
half the interest earned from such loans only if the ESOP owns 30
percent or more of the corporation. The same 30 percent test would
be applied before a corporation could take a tax deduction for
certain dividends paid on ESOP stock.
   A second change would make the new rule effective on July 10.
This change would allow dozens of corporations that are setting up
ESOPs to qualify for treatment under the old rules.
</TEXT>
