<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 0432EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BeerAds     07-14 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Beer Ads,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Wants to Regulate Beer Commercials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beer ads on television should be regulated so
youngsters are not encouraged to drink, an advocacy group says, but
the beer industry contends it's up to parents to keep an eye on
their kids' viewing habits.
   The Center for Science in the Public Interest said Thursday that
in an informal survey it conducted, television ads for beer were
more popular than any other type of commercial among teen-age boys.
   Forty percent of the high-school boys surveyed said one or more
beer ads were their favorites. Of the girls surveyed, 12 percent
listed beer and wine ads as their favorites.
   Michael Jacobson, executive director of the Washington-based
center, said the ads have an impact regardless of beer industry
claims that they don't target youngsters.
   ``Intentions aside, their advertising is sure reaching these
kids, and that's really the issue,'' he said.
   Jim Sanders, president of the Beer Institute, said, ``I don't
believe this particular survey reveals anything more than parental
neglect.''
   Other surveys have shown no correlation between advertising and
increased consumption, Sanders said. The competition within the
industry is for a market that has leveled off, he said.
   Jacobson said the survey showed that advertisements for fast
foods and soft drinks as well as beer are popular with teen-agers.
   ``It's high time that society either restricted such ads or made
sure that messages for a more healthful lifestyle reached kids,'' he
said.
   Boys and girls agreed on what made an ad attractive, he said.
Those characteristics were humor, rock music and the depiction of
athletes or other sports activities.
   In fact, the single favorite ad among boys was for Isuzu cars and
trucks, followed by Budweiser or Bud Light. The single favorite
among girls was McDonald's, followed by Pepsi or Diet Pepsi.
   The students in the survey were questioned this spring at public
and private high schools in Washington, Baltimore and rural
Pennsylvania, the Washington-based center said. The 284 responding
students listed a total of 1,026 ``favorite or most memorable'' ads.
The students' average age was 15.7 years.
</TEXT>
