<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 0438EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Immigration     07-14 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Immigration,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Overhaul of Immigration System Clears Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate sponsors of a planned overhaul of the
nation's immigration system, including a cap of 630,000 immigrants
arriving each year, are predicting a strong chance of approval in
the House.
   ``I'm very hopeful that we'll get legislation. It's early in the
session,'' Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said Thursday after the
Senate approved the measure, 81-17, and sent it to the House.
   The bill was originally designed to cap immigration at 600,000 in
each of the next three years but was expanded to include room for
30,000 new arrivals annually before final passage. The ceiling
represents 136,000 more visas than were issued last year.
   Critics say the bill still could reduce visas for all but the
closest relatives of American citizens and permanent residents of
the United States.
   The House killed a similar measure in 1988, but sponsors are more
hopeful about their chances this year.
   Kennedy and co-sponsor Alan K. Simpson, R-Wyo., said they have
already received encouragement from House leaders.
   ``We've never given them anything like this this early,'' Simpson
said.
   Simpson expressed concerns about changes the bill underwent
before passage, but said it was ``time to face the unfortunate but
hideously cold reality that there are many more people who want to
come here than there is room or intent to accommodate them.''
   Simpson praised provisions that reserved 120,000 of the annual
visas for individuals who do not have family ties in America but who
would be likely to make significant contributions in business,
sciences or other areas.
   The Senate added a provision that would allow entry to spouses
and minor children of those who achieved legal status under the 1986
amnesty program for illegal aliens.
   The thrust of the bill does not relate to illegal aliens, but the
Senate attached a number of riders that focused on the politically
volatile subject.
   The Senate voted 78-21 to raise the ceiling by 30,000 visas
annually after Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., recalled how his father
fled czarist Russia in 1911 and arrived in America ``with no rubles
in his pocket, he had to come steerage.''
   Further efforts at expansion, however, were rejected.
   The Senate did approve an amendment from Sen. Richard C. Shelby,
D-Ala., that would force the Census Bureau to halt its practice of
including illegal aliens in its official count. Proponents were
concerned that states with many aliens would get an unfair edge in
congressional remaps following next year's census.
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said that under the current system
``states like California would gain a (congressional) seat at North
Carolina's expense.''
   Among those entering for reasons other than family ties, 54,000
visas annually are subject to a point system giving credit for those
with special skills who do not have employers ready to sponsor them.
   The Judiciary Committee deleted a provision that would provide
extra points to individuals who speak English. Simpson appealed to
the Senate in vain to restore the point system but lawmakers
rejected the idea, 56-43.
   Meanwhile, the House approved, 358-44, and sent to the Senate
separate legislation to ease immigration of certain Soviet and
Southeast Asian refugees.
   It would temporarily re-establish the legal status of Soviet Jews
and evangelical Christians as well as certain categories of
Vietnamese, Laotians and Cambodians as persecuted without having to
prove it in each individual case. That would aid them in obtaining
standing as refugees.
   The measure is opposed by the Bush administration, which contends
it unnecessarily establishes special preferences for certain
refugees and makes it more difficult to fairly administer the U.S.
refugee program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890714-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 0439EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Budget     07-14 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Expects Favorable Deficit Forecast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Next week's update of the projected federal
deficit for fiscal 1990, once seen on Capitol Hill as ominous, is
now viewed by lawmakers as a harmless exercise that may even make
their budget work easier.
   Many members of Congress say they believe the White House's
Office of Management and Budget is likely to forecast a deficit that
falls below the $110 billion target set in the Gramm-Rudman
balanced-budget law.
   ``My best estimate is that OMB will come in with a set of numbers
indicating we'll easily achieve the $110 billion,'' Sen. Pete V.
Domenici of New Mexico, ranking Republican on the Senate Budget
Committee, said Thursday.
   ``I would not even be surprised if the assumptions would yield
closer to $100 billion than $110 billion,'' he said.
   Domenici, who consults regularly with Bush administration
officials, said his comments were based on an ``informed guess.''
   Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., chairman of the House Budget
Committee, said he believes the deficit will probably be projected
``very close'' to earlier estimates that the Gramm-Rudman target
would be honored.
   ``I'm not expecting any big surprises,'' he said.
   Failure to meet the Gramm-Rudman ceiling can trigger automatic
spending slashes in most domestic and defense federal programs.
Fiscal 1990 begins Oct. 1.
   Domenici, Panetta and others on Capitol Hill said they expect OMB
to concede that next year's economy is likely to be less robust than
the agency projected in February.
   A worsening economy tends to increase interest rates the
government pays to borrowers and diminish the revenues it collects,
driving up the deficit.
   But the lawmakers said that could be more than compensated for by
higher than anticipated revenue collections by the government, as
well as some spending savings.
   Domenici indicated that OMB could claim $10 billion more in
revenue than was expected in February, $3 billion in savings from
the way the savings and loan industry bailout is being handled, and
perhaps $1 billion in savings from changes in defense spending.
   OMB officials wouldn't comment on the forecast.
   In other budget action Thursday:
   _The House Energy and Commerce Committee imposed Federal
Communications Commission fees on amateur radio operators,
nationwide paging services and other radio frequency users, raising
an estimated $50 million.
   The panel also wrote new restrictions on dial-a-porn companies,
and voted to write the Fairness Doctrine into law. The doctrine,
enforced by the FCC until 1987, requires broadcasters to grant equal
time to all sides of issues.
   _The Senate Banking Committee took credit for saving $187 million
by renewing the government's flood-insurance program. The program is
to expire Sept. 30, which would leave about 2 million policyholders
eligible to receive benefits but not required to pay premiums.
   _The Senate Governmental Affairs Committee approved legislation
moving the money-losing Postal Service ``off-budget,'' and changing
the way the service pays health benefits to families of former
employees, pensions and other retirement payments. The package
claims $2.9 billion in savings.
   _The Senate Veterans Affairs Committee extended a fee it charges
for loans and retained restrictions on the loan portfolios it sells,
claiming a savings of $665 million. The House Veterans Affairs
Committee took similar action that it said saved $697 million.
   OMB's deficit projections assume enactment of savings in the
$1.17 trillion budget passed by Congress in May. Congressional
committees are beginning work on the spending, revenue and savings
bills needed to carry out the deficit reduction envisioned in the
budget.
   The congressional budget planned a deficit of $105.4 billion in
fiscal 1990. The spending plan reflected an agreement worked out in
April between President Bush and congressional leaders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890714-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 0440EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China     07-14 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China,0696</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Tightens Laws on Publications, More Executions Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China said today it was imposing tougher rules on
what books and magazines can publish, and there were reports of more
executions and prison terms in a continuation of the government's
drive to stifle popular dissent.
   A foreign source in Chengdu, the capital of central Sichuan
Province, quoted local press reports as saying two men were executed
last Saturday for their actions during deadly riots in that city in
early June.
   The executions, which were not reported in the national press,
brought to 29 the number of people known to have been put to death
for disrupting social order since the June 3-4 military assault on
Beijing in which at least 200 people were killed.
   Meanwhile, the official People's Daily said today that the state
Press and Publications Administration has decided to take tough new
measures to weed out publications it considers unsavory.
   It said publishers in recent years have ``flooded the book market
with low grade and vulgar material which contain violent murders and
obscene pornography which have corrupted people's souls.''
   It added that books and periodicals to be investigated and
removed from bookstalls include those with ``counterrevolutionary
and bourgeois liberalization propaganda.''
   The Chinese government has blamed the June violence on
``counterrevolutionary rebels'' trying to overthrow the socialist
system and has detained or issued arrest warrants for dozens of
students and intellectuals who led the pro-democracy movement.
   Books by scholars now on nationwide wanted lists have been
banned, and Culture Ministry workers have raided private bookstalls
to seize copies.
   The administration said any bookseller or publisher who violates
the regulations will be fined at least five times the profit made.
   The Chengdu source said the two executed men, Zhou Xiangcheng and
Wang Guiyuan, were charged with ``beating, smashing, looting and
burning,'' a catchall of crimes that China uses for rioting. Neither
was a student, he said.
   The Chengdu riots of June 4-5 are believed to be the most violent
that occurred outside the capital. Up to 30 people were killed as
people battled police, and a half-block of the city was destroyed by
fire. More than 100 people were later arrested.
   The source said Chengdu courts also gave another man a death
sentence with a two-year reprieve and sentenced three others to life
imprisonment, one for arson and two for ``hooliganism.'' The
two-year stay of execution means the sentence is converted to life
if the prisoner shows a proper attitude.
   The source said courts in Chengdu the past week have sentenced 20
others to prison terms ranging from five years to life.
   In the first weeks following the violence in Beijing, China's
national media reported the arrests of more than 2,000 people who
took part in protests. The arrests still are believed to be going
on, although the national press rarely reports them now.
   One exception was Thursday, when television news showed an office
worker being given a 10-year prison term for spreading rumors during
an interview with ABC-TV.
   The interview, in which Xiao Bin, 42, of Dalian told ABC that
20,000 people were killed by troops during their attack on Tiananmen
Square, apparently was intercepted by China Central Television when
ABC was sending the unedited tape by satellite.
   China TV broadcast the tape and demanded that people turn the man
in. Two women reported Xiao to police and later received cash
rewards.
   Xinjiang Radio, in China's westernmost province, also reported
Thursday that 10 people had received prison terms ranging from one
year to life for involvement in a May 19 riot in the provincial
capital of Urumqi.
   One man received life imprisonment for ``a serious case of
beating, smashing and looting'' during the riot when, according to
official accounts, 150 policemen and government officials were
injured, 20 of them seriously, and 43 trucks were overturned.
   The Urumqi disturbances focused on protests over a
Chinese-language book, ``Sexual Customs,'' which Moslems claimed
insulted their religion.
   About half of China's 15 million Moslems live in Xinjiang.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
