<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     07-14 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Closes Up Against Yen, Shares Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar closed higher Friday on the Tokyo
Foreign Exchange while share prices fell moderately.
   The dollar closed at 139.50 yen, up 0.45 yen from Thursday's
close of 139.05 yen. After opening higher at 139.60 yen, the dollar
ranged from 139.35 to 139.68 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which lost 70.36 points Thursday, shed another
56.39 points, or 0.16 percent, closing the week at 33,574.77.
   Currency dealers said the morning trading was quiet prior to the
release of several U.S. economic indicators, due out in Washington
later Friday. Statistics to be released include the U.S. producer
price index for June and industrial production and retail sales
figures.
   ``Amid a wait-and-see position prevailing in the market, the yen
weakened as foreign banks adjusted their holdings'' by selling the
yen to buy dollars, said Hirohisa Yumoto, a dealer with the
Mitsubishi Bank.
   On the stock market, the market's main index declined, with many
participants retreating to the sidelines because of uncertainties
over Japanese politics centering on July 23 elections for half the
seats of the 252-member upper house of parliament, dealers said.
   The governing Liberal Democratic Party is expected to suffer a
defeat in the elections because of reaction against an unpopular 3
percent consumption tax imposed April 1, the Recruit Co.
influence-peddling scandal, and sex scandals surrounding Prime
Minister Sousuke Uno.
</TEXT>
