<HEAD>Senate Goes to Work On Drought Relief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators from the South and upper Midwest are
pushing to get aid for weather-damaged crops in their states
included in drought-relief legislation lawmakers are rushing to
finish this summer.
   ``We've got a comprehensive problem that's going to take a
comprehensive approach,'' Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D., told fellow
members of the Senate Agriculture Committee on Thursday. ``The loss
is great ... and the time is short.''
   The Bush administration and Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of
Kansas have been backing off their insistence that drought relief be
limited to winter wheat farmers. But it is uncertain whether enough
money would be available to cover losses of other crops.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter had said he would recommend
that President Bush veto a drought relief package approved by the
House that would cover more than 500 crops and cost more than $900
million.
   The committee is scheduled to vote on a drought-relief bill next
week that lawmakers hope to get approved by Congress before the
August recess.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>House Panel Approves Medicaid Expansion</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee has approved expansions in
the Medicaid health-care program for the poor that would cost the
federal government about $4 billion over five years.
   The expansions would bring into the federal-state program many of
the pregnant women, infants and children who are not now covered and
have no private health insurance.
   The House Energy and Commerce Committee on Thursday also
unanimously approved a non-binding resolution calling for the
Medicare program covering catastrophic illnesses to be made
voluntary, saying Congress cannot ignore outrage among the elderly
over the program.
   ``I think we need to make some changes in the catastrophic care
program because so many people are upset,'' said Rep. Henry Waxman,
D-Calif., chairman of the panel's health subcommittee.
   Rep. Michael Bilirakis, R-Fla., who proposed the resolution,
called the program a ``catastrophic catastrophe,'' under which many
elderly citizens are being forced to pay for coverage they already
have through other sources.
   The measures were approved 30-13 as part of a huge
deficit-cutting package for fiscal year 1990, which begins Oct. 1.
The package now moves to the House Budget Committee.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>NJ Congressmen: Adults Who Use Children in Drug Trade Should be</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Punished
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adults who use youngsters as lookouts and
couriers in the drug trade should be punished with stiff penalties,
three New Jersey lawmakers say.
   ``Drug dealers think they can exploit children because children
are rarely imprisoned for any great length of time,'' said Rep.
James Florio, D-N.J., author of a bill targeting a phenomenon that
experts say has surfaced in the last four years.
   Using children as young as 10 years of age ``demonstrates that
drug traffickers not only have no respect for society as a whole or
for other individuals, but that, within their own criminal class,
they are the bottom of the barrel, the scum of the scum,'' said Rep.
William J. Hughes, D-N.J., chairman of the House subcommittee on
crime.
   Hughes and fellow Democratic Rep. Donald Payne co-sponsored the
legislation.
   ``It is a new and deadly form of child abuse,'' Charles Knox,
director of the Bureau of Narcotics for the Sheriff's Office in
Essex County, N.J., told the subcommittee members.
   The number of 15- to 17-year-olds arrested in New Jersey for
working in drug operations jumped from 5,728 in 1986 to 7,988 in
1988, while arrests of 13- to 14-year-olds jumped from 480 in 1986
to 846 last year, Florio said.
</TEXT>
