<HEAD>Dollar Up Against Yen, Tokyo Stocks Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose today against the Japanese yen
in Tokyo while prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell for the third
consecutive day.
   The dollar ended the week at 139.50 yen, up 0.45 yen from
Thursday's close of 139.05 yen. After opening higher at 139.60 yen,
the U.S. currency ranged between 139.35 and 139.68 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost 70.36
points Thursday, shed another 56.39 points, or 0.16 percent, closing
the week at 33,574.77. The index lost 45.25 points on Wednesday.
   Shinya Hirota, a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo, described the
day's currency trading as ``very quiet'' because many market players
were staying on the sidelines prior to the release of U.S. economic
indicators in Washington later today.
   The statistics include the U.S. producer price index for June and
industrial production and retail sales figures, which are regarded
as important indicators of the state of the U.S. economy.
   Hiromichi Ishikawa of Yamaichi Securities, a major Japanese
brokerage, said trading on the stock market also was very thin, with
many participants also awaiting the U.S. economic figures.
   Volume on the market's first section was estimated at 330 million
shares, down from 550 million shares on Thursday.
   Contributing to the decline in the Nikkei index was investor
concern over continuing political uncertainty in Japan, Ishikawa
said.
   Political analysts predict the governing Liberal Democratic Party
will lose its majority in the 252-member House of Councillors, the
upper house of Japan's parliament, in elections July 23 because of
public reaction to an unpopular new 3 percent consumption tax, the
Recruit Co. bribery scandal, and a sex scandal surrounding Prime
Minister Sousuke Uno.
