<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Hook     07-14 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Hook,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sidney Hook, Philosopher, Author, Educator, Dead at 86</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philosopher Sidney Hook, a prolific
writer whose 1943 work ``The Hero in History'' is still used as a
college text, has died of congestive heart failure. He was 86.
   Hook, a leading figure in U.S. intellectual circles since the
late '20s, died at Stanford University Hospital on Wednesday. He had
been a senior research fellow at the Hoover Institution on War,
Revolution and Peace on the Stanford campus since 1973.
   His major books include ``The Metaphysics of Pragmatism,''
published in 1927; ``Towards the Understanding of Karl Marx,'' 1933;
``From Hegel to Marx: Studies in the Intellectual Development of
Karl Marx,'' 1936; and ``Common Sense and the Fifth Amendment,''
published in 1957.
   Hook's best-known work, ``The Hero in History,'' won the
prestigious Nicholas Murray Butler Silver Medal of distinction in
philosophy and education.
   Of all his writings, the one that received the most mail was an
essay in The New York Times in 1987 called ``In Defense of Voluntary
Euthanasia.''
   ``I shall not be sorry to leave this world,'' Hook wrote. ``I've
had a happy life. I'm one of the lucky people who can live in their
work, instead of after work.''
   He wrote in his 1987 autobiography, ``Out of Step: An Unquiet
Life in The 20th Century,'' that his key belief was that the central
problem of the modern era is ``the defense and enrichment of a free
and open society against totalitarianism.''
   Hook founded in 1951 the American Committee for Cultural Freedom
and was an early critic of Sen. Joseph R. McCarthy, who charged that
communists had infiltrated the U.S. government.
   Hook expounded his views on issues of that era in two books, one
titled, ``Heresy, Yes _ Conspiracy, No!''
   He took the Stanford position in 1973 after he retired from New
York University, where he had taught since 1927 and served as
chairman of the philosophy department until 1968.
   Hook became a leading proponent of philosopher John Dewey's
ideals, known as pragmatism, a peculiarly American philosophy that
an idea must be judged by how it works.
   ``The Metaphysics of Pragmatism,'' his first book, was an
exposition of Dewey's thought. At the time of his death, Hook was
planning a retrospective essay on Dewey, who died in 1952, that was
intended for publication in the final volume of Dewey's ``Collected
Works.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
