<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Stronger in Europe, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar firmed in light trading in Europe
this morning, while gold prices were slightly weaker.
   Foreign exchange dealers said their markets were subdued,
awaiting release of data on the state of the U.S. economy and the
start of the annual economic summit in Paris of the Group of Seven
major industrial countries.
   ``It's going to be a wait-and-see day,'' said a dealer at a major
West German bank in Frankfurt.
   In London, one British pound traded at $1.6205, a gain for the
dollar compared to Thursday's late $1.6240.
   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday:
   _1.8880 West German marks, up from 1.8815
   _1.6320 Swiss francs, up from 1.6190
   _6.4130 French francs, up from 6.3870
   _2.1307 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1155
   _1,369.75 Italian lire, up from 1,362.25
   _1.1920 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1922
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 139.50 Japanese yen, up 0.45 yen
from late Thursday. Later, in London, the dollar traded at 139.60
yen.
   Gold opened in London at $376, up 25 cents from late Thursday. At
midmorning, London's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended
price of $375 an ounce.
   In Zurich, gold was trading at $375, down from $375.75 late
Thursday.
   In Hong Kong, gold closed at $377.39, down from $377.87 Thursday.
   Silver bullion traded in London at $5.25 bid a troy ounce,
unchanged from late Thursday.
