<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Cherries 1stLd-Writethru a0454 07-14 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Cherries, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0454,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Group Seeks Chemical Tests on U.S. Cherries, Other Imports</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with lab report, ministry comment.
Picks up graf 8 pvs, `Song said ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consumer group said today that it
planned to test U.S. cherries and other agricultural imports to
determine if they contain unsafe levels of pesticides or carcinogens.
   The Citizens Alliance for Consumer Protection of Korea said the
tests would be conducted in overseas laboratories if South Korean
labs either cannot or will not cooperate.
   The first tests will be performed on imported U.S. cherries to
determine if they contain the chemical daminozide, or Alar, a
suspected cancer-causing agent.
   Other imported U.S. agricultural products also will be tested,
said Song Bo-kyung, vice president of the alliance.
   Meanwhile, the Ministry of Health and Social Affairs said today
that recent concerns over food safety would result in more detailed
testing of all imported food products.
   The ministry said laboratory testing on U.S. imported grapefruits
and oranges showed they contained no Alar, but it said tests would
be conducted on other agricultural products such as apple juice.
   The alliance recently led a nationwide boycott of Florida
grapefruit after it said a government lab report indicated the
presence of Alar on some fruit. Although the lab later clarified the
report to say that its test did not find the chemical, consumers
remained skeptical.
   The government lab declined to retest the grapefruit and an
independent lab said it did not have the equipment. Meanwhile,
Korea's consumer movement against all chemicals in food production
has grown.
   On Thursday, the Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries Ministry
announced a ban on the sale and use of Alar on Korean farm products.
   Last year, an estimated 12,540 pounds of Alar was sold to South
Korean farmers, the ministry said.
   Song said the concern is not restricted to Alar, which is used to
enhance color and perserve storage life.
   ``The other issue is residues of pesticides and chemicals on all
imported food commodities _ from the United States, the Philippines
or anywhere else.'' She said this included beef products as well as
fruits and vegetables.
   Song said that Korean consumer groups depend heavily on consumer
groups in the United States for research and information and the
alliance coordinates with groups in other parts of the world.
   ``We are concerned about the safety of foods the consumers eat,''
she said. ``We are not concerned for the businessmen or trade
issues.''
   Washington has pushed Seoul to open its markets to U.S.
agricultural products to help correct South Korea's trade imbalance,
which was $8.5 billion in 1988. South Korean farmers have staged
protests against U.S. products claiming they undercut domestic
prices.
   The citizen's alliance is one of the largest and most outspoken
of 10 leading consumer associations that claim a combined nationwide
membership of 2 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890714-0065 </DOCNO>
