<FIRST>r i PM-Albania-Yugoslavia-Quake     07-14 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Albania-Yugoslavia-Quake,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake Measuring 4.8 Rattles Albania, Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An earthquake measuring 4.8 on the
Richter scale shook northeastern Albania and southern Yugoslavia
today but there were no reports of injuries or damages, the state
news agency Tanjug reported.
   The agency said the 8:52 a.m. quake was centered in Albania,
about 60 miles southeast of the Yugoslav city of Titograd. It shook
an Yugoslav area extending from the Macedonian towns of Dabar and
Tetovo to the Montenegrin capital of Titograd.
   Quake-prone southern Yugoslavia has experienced several small
temblors in the past decade. Tanjug said the quake lasted for about
20 seconds, longer than usual in the region.
   There was no immediate report on the quake from Albania.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
semismograph.
   Authorities say a quake of magnitude 4 can cause moderate damage
in populated areas, while one of magnitude 5 is capable of causing
cause considerable damage in populated areas.
</TEXT>
