<FIRST>r a PM-FlagRdp     07-14 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flag Rdp,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Arrested For Flag Burning in Massachusetts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested a man for torching Old Glory but
charged him with destroying property rather than desecrating the
flag because of the recent U.S. Supreme Court decision.
   ``Since we didn't know whether (flag desecration) was still
punishable, we didn't want to endanger the case by using that
charge,'' Lt. Paul J. Gallagher of the police force in suburban
North Andover said Thursday.
   Meanwhile, the California Senate on Thursday approved a
resolution urging Congress to pass a constitutional amendment
against flag burning, a move already endorsed by President Bush. The
state Assembly passed a similar measure last month.
   North Carolina's Senate passed by 47-0 a bill backed by Gov. Jim
Martin that would revise the state's flag desecration law, making it
a misdemeanor to destroy or mutilate an American or North Carolina
flag except for disposal purposes.
   Martin said the bill would not violate last month's U.S. Supreme
Court ruling that flag burning is protected by the Constitution's
freedom of speech guarantee. The bill was modeled after a measure
proposed by New York Gov. Mario Cuomo and, unlike the Texas law
struck down by the high court, it does not refer to conduct that
could seriously offend people.
   In Austin, the Texas House passed without objection an amendment
to an anti-flag desecration bill that would extend criminal
penalties for desecration to flags of all U.S. states and
territories, in addition to Old Glory and the Texas flag.
   In Massachusetts, police charged Jack T. Fredyma of malicious
destruction of property, a felony punishable by up to 2{ years in
jail, rather than desecration of a national symbol.
   The key to the case is that Fredyma allegedly burned someone
else's flag, not his own. The Supreme Court ruling ``doesn't give
you the right to take someone else's flag and burn it,'' Gallagher
said.
   Fredyma allegedly took down a 5-by-8-foot flag in front of
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.'s plant in North Andover
Wednesday night, then set it on fire and ran it back up the flagpole.
   The 27-year-old man worked at the plant from January 1985 until
last October and apparently was expressing anger at AT&amp;T, Gallagher
said.
   Fredyma pleaded innocent Wednesday in Lawrence District Court,
and the case was continued until Oct. 16. He declined to comment on
the charge Thursday but said he was fired by AT&amp;T after complaining
about environmental hazards in the company's darkrooms, a claim the
company denies.
   Fredyma also faces federal charges of using the mail to make
physical threats against his former supervisors.
   According to an FBI affidavit filed in the case, he sent a June 1
letter to the Boston office of the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration in which he accused top AT&amp;T officials of being
``traitors against the U.S. Constitution and its people'' and
threatened to ``use deadly force against these traitors.''
   Walter Murphy, an AT&amp;T spokesman in New York, said the company
would not comment.
</TEXT>
