<FIRST>r a PM-DwarfTossing     07-14 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dwarf Tossing,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Wants to Ban Dwarf Tossing and Dwarf Bowling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two lawmakers said they will seek to outlaw
dwarf tossing and dwarf bowling, saying the barroom contests are
demeaning and dangerous.
   ``It's just unbelievable that in this type of society we're going
to start throwing people around,'' state Sen. Nicholas Spano said
Thursday.
   ``There are enough prejudices out there against people who are
different than others physically,'' Spano said. ``We are going to
play to those types of prejudices if we allow this to happen.''
   In Grand Rapids, Mich., meanwhile, a nightclub is facing state
penalties for violating a restricted entertainment permit by holding
a dwarf tossing contest, in which patrons competed to see how far
they could throw a person.
   The state Liquor Control Commission said Thursday that it also
cited the nightclub Carnival for two unrelated liquor violations.
The bar could be fined up to $300 per violation and faces possible
suspension or revocation of its liquor license, although revocation
is unlikely, said Ronalee Polad, a duty officer with the
commission's enforcement division.
   Club manager Scott Vokoun, who was aware that commission
investigators were present that night, said his attorney does not
believe he violated his entertainment permit.
   The contest drew more than 300 spectators as well as 50
demonstrators, many of them disabled, who said the event was
demeaning and cruel.
   State Rep. Richard Bandstra has said he will introduce
legislation later this year banning the event in Michigan.
   In New York, Spano and Sen. Guy Velella said they will introduce
legislation banning the practices when the Legislature returns to
session in January. A ban on dwarf contests was passed earlier this
year in Florida after dwarf tossing became popular near the
University of Florida.
   Dwarf bowlers compete by strapping a helmeted person to a
skateboard and pushing him or her head-first into bowling pins.
   Both contests originated in Australia and have become fads at
some parties and taverns across the country. Spano said contests
have been held at bars on Long Island and in New York City.
   A spokesman for Decisions, a nightclub in Mineola, said it had
one dwarf bowling contest to promote a special Australian night but
won't do it again because of a bad reaction.
   ``I'd like to try and get it stopped because it's demeaning to a
lot of little people,'' said Thomas Acquafredda, a Yonkers member of
the Little People of America, a national group representing dwarfs.
Acquafredda approached Spano seeking the ban.
   Acquafredda said bar owners take advantage of ``sick'' dwarfs who
think they can't find other jobs. There's no insurance to cover any
injuries they might suffer, he said.
   ``The people in bars who are doing it I think are disturbed and
jerks,'' Acquafredda said.
</TEXT>
