<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 0809EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSDrug     07-14 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Drug,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pharmaceutical Company to Distribute Experimental AIDS Drug Free
of Charge</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bristol-Myers Co. has announced it will make a
new drug available to people with AIDS at no cost, although safety
testing on the drug is not complete.
   DDI, or dideoxyinosine, appears to be effective but not dangerous
like AZT, or azidothymidine, the only drug now licensed to treat
AIDS.
   The New York-based company's decision Thursday was hailed as a
victory by advocates who have sought to give AIDS patients access to
experimental drugs.
   Supporters of DDI in the United States and Canada had asked that
it be made available because about half of all acquired immune
deficiency syndrome patients cannot take AZT.
   ``This is a historic development,'' Larry Kramer, a leading AIDS
activist who founded the AIDS Coalition to Unleash Power, told The
New York Times. ``We are grateful that pharmaceutical company has
put compassion before greed.''
   The Bristol-Myers announcement took government officials by
surprise. Officials of the U.S. Food and Drug Administration and the
National Institutes of Health had discussed making the drug
available but had not expected Bristol-Myers to act so quickly, the
Times and The Washington Post reported in today's editions.
   Under regular practice, a drug's safety is studied in Phase I
tests and its effectiveness is determined during a larger, longer
Phase II study. DDI has only been through the Phase I stage.
   It is still up to the FDA to decide if Bristol-Myers can legally
distribute the drug to people who are not part of the Phase II
testing, the Post said.
   ``We want to do what we can to help,'' said Jerry Parret, a
spokesman for Bristol-Myers. ``Any patient who does not meet the
criteria for Phase II clinical trials but for whom DDI is critical
would receive the drug.''
   The drug is expected to be distributed free of charge beginning
in September when Phase II testing begins, the newspapers said.
</TEXT>
