<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 0916EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TyphoidOutbreak     07-14 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Typhoid Outbreak,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cases Of Typhoid Fever Grows to 13</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health authorities have confirmed an outbreak
of typhoid fever among visitors to a Catskill Mountain resort town
last month, with 13 cases identified and another 20 suspected.
   The victims include people who attended a convention of the New
York State Association of Fire Chiefs at the Pines Hotel in South
Fallsburg, about 90 miles northwest of New York City, Health
Department spokeswoman Faith Schottenfeld said Thursday.
   In addition to several conventioneers, a hotel restaurant worker
and two members of a senior citizens group that stayed at the hotel
at the time have contracted the disease, Schottenfeld said.
   More than 10,000 New Yorkers attended the convention June 12 and
13. Thousands of other tourists who had stayed in the area are being
questioned in New York, New Jersey, Connecticut and Ohio,
Schottenfeld said.
   The disease has been identified in residents of New York, New
Jersey and Connecticut so far, she said. Visitors to the resort
should be showing symptoms of typhoid fever by now if they have the
disease, she added.
   The number of confirmed cases has grown since the Health
Department first reported four cases on Tuesday.
   Typhoid is spread by eating or drinking food and water
contaminated by people carrying the infection. The bacteria is shed
in the feces of carriers. Symptoms usually appear one to three weeks
after exposure and include fever, headache and diarrhea or
constipation.
   Typhoid is easily treated with antibiotics and victims usually
recover within a week.
</TEXT>
