<FIRST>r a PM-SexualAbuse-AIDS 1stLd-Writethru a0534 07-14 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sexual Abuse-AIDS, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0534,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Social Worker Charged After Failing to Report Sexual Abuse, Child
Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 5th pvs, `Edson was indicted...' to add
maximum sentencing for each count; SUBS 7th graf pvs, `Edson declined...'
to UPDATE with calls for comment not returned today. Julaan in last graf
is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state Department of Social Services
caseworker has been charged with failing to report a suspected case
of sexual abuse after an 8-year-old boy in a foster home died of
AIDS.
   The indictment issued Thursday by a Richland County grand jury
charged Frank Edson with not investigating the case or notifying the
proper law enforcement authorities as required by law.
   The foster mother of Brett Hall, of Columbia, told Edson in
October 1987 that the boy had been sexually abused, but Edson waited
eight months before beginning his investigation, according to the
indictment. By that time Brett was dying of acquired immune
deficiency syndrome, a breakdown of the body's immune system which
leaves the victim fatally susceptible to viruses.
   Brett was 9 when he died in November.
   Edson was indicted on two counts of obstruction of justice and
two counts of failure to report child abuse. A 1977 state law
requires child protection agencies to follow through on any
suspected case of child abuse or neglect within 24 hours.
   Each count of obstruction of justice carries a maximum 10-year
prison term. Each count of failure to report child abuse carries a
maximum 6-month prison term and $500 fine.
   Social Services spokeswoman Norma G. Anderson, who has worked at
the agency since 1973, said it was the first time in her memory that
an employee has been indicted on criminal charges for failing to
follow through on a suspected child abuse case.
   Edson declined to comment on the indictment, The State newspaper
reported today. Calls by The Associated Press to his home this
morning were not immediately returned.
   State policy requires employees who have been indicted to be
suspended or transferred to a less sensitive position until the
criminal charges are resolved. No action had been taken Thursday on
Edson.
   Now that Brett is dead, there is no way to prosecute the person
responsible, so the investigation has turned toward the boy's
caseworker, said Julaan Prince, an assistant solicitor in Conway.
</TEXT>
