<FIRST>r a PM-ForgeryPlea     07-14 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Forgery Plea,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Printer To Plead Guilty To Forging Nearly $10 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A printer has agreed to plead guilty to
forging almost $10 million cash in what authorities called one of
the biggest counterfeiting schemes in U.S. history.
   Hal J. Stepanich, 33, will enter a guilty plea in exchange for
certain concessions by prosecutors that could help reduce his
sentence, federal public defender H. Dean Steward said Thursday.
   Stepanich's trial was scheduled to begin Tuesday.
   A trail of phony bills throughout Southern California led
authorities to Stepanich and another Orange County man, Richard L.
Wattel, federal prosecutors said. Stepanich was arrested in April.
   Stepanich and Wattel, 62, allegedly made counterfeit bills at
Stepanich's ex-wife's garage near Palm Springs, authorities said.
Most of the money has been recovered. Wattel, who was arrested in
Texas, is awaiting trial there on counterfeit charges.
   Federal sentencing guidelines would allow the judge to sentence
Stepanich to 27 to 36 months in prison for pleading guilty to the
charge of counterfeiting $9.76 million.
   The counterfeiting case ranks among the largest in U.S. history,
said Richard Griffin, who heads the Secret Service office in Los
Angeles. A record $22.6 million in fake bills was confiscated last
year in Orange County, he said.
</TEXT>
