<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1027EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Mandela     07-14 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mandela,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mandela Wants Meeting With Anti-Apartheid Leaders, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jailed nationalist leader
Nelson Mandela wants permission to meet a wide range of
anti-apartheid activists to coordinate strategies, a newspaper
reported today.
   The anti-apartheid Weekly Mail said Mandela hopes to see several
black trade union leaders when he meets with his family on Tuesday,
his 71st birthday.
   Without citing sources, The Weekly Mail said Mandela has composed
a list of up to 150 people he would like to see at Victor Verster
Prison outside Cape Town, where he lives alone in a suburban-style
house.
   Mandela met July 5 with President P.W. Botha, fueling speculation
that the black leader soon may be freed and that the government is
seeking new means to break the country's political stalemate.
   ``The need (to meet with opposition leaders) has become
pressing,'' The Weekly Mail said, adding that some anti-apartheid
groups fear Mandela's isolation makes unified political action
difficult.
   The newspaper said Mandela wanted to see Jay Naidoo, Elijah
Barayi and Cyril Ramaphosa of the Congress of South African Trade
Unions, the country's largest labor federation.
   The Prisons Service declined to comment when asked if Mandela had
made such a request or if he would be receiving visitors in the near
future.
   Mandela, the country's best known black leader and head of the
African National Congress guerrilla movement, receives regular
visits from his family and attorney, but talks with anti-apartheid
leaders have been rare.
   He was imprisoned in 1962 under a life sentence for sabotage and
plotting to overthrow the white government.
   The anti-apartheid movement, which has many factions and numerous
disagreements, has reacted to the Botha-Mandela meeting with
conflicting statements.
   Mandela's wife, Winnie, initially dismissed the talks at the
president's official Cape Town residence as government propaganda
involving no shift in policy. But the tone changed when Mandela
released a statement Wednesday indicating he welcomed his chance to
talk with Botha.
   ``We do not condemn the meeting at all,'' Mrs. Mandela was quoted
as saying by the independent South African Press Association. ``For
us to get to the negotiation table, we have to start somewhere.''
   The African National Congress dismissed the meeting as a ``public
relations exercise.'' It has not commented publicly on Mandela's
statement.
   Among issues that divide the groups is whether or not they should
use violence to force change in South Africa.
   In another development, the New Nation newspaper said police
raided Mrs. Mandela's home on the day her husband visited Botha.
   The newspaper said it did not know the reason for the raid on the
house in Soweto, the huge township outside Johannesburg.
   Mrs. Mandela has mentioned no such incident and could not be
reached for comment. Police said they had no immediate comment but
would respond later.
</TEXT>
