<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1031EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-GlobalEnvironment 1stLd-Writethru a0455 07-14 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Global Environment, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0455,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0548, which should have been slugged 1st Ld-Writethru</HEAD>
<HEAD>Prominence of Environment at Summit Shows Concern</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS penultimate graf, bgng: `The seven,' to clarify that seven
nations account for 40 percent of carbon dioxide emissions</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prominence given to the environment at the
Paris economic summit reflects a growing view among world leaders
that the battle against pollution is too immense and complicated for
a single nation to tackle.
   President Bush and his advisers are expected to argue forcefully
that unless a resounding effort is made to enlist all countries, the
moves to cut pollution by a few nations could be wiped out by
actions taken _ or not taken _ elsewhere in the world.
   So leaders of the seven largest industrial nations _ the United
States, Britain, France, West Germany, Japan, Italy and Canada _
want to conclude their meeting Sunday with a unified voice that will
carry weight among leaders not present.
   The summit participants are aware that the environment has become
a hot political issue. Repeated polls indicate that people want
their leaders to tackle the world's pollution problems.
   At the same time, the Bush administration sees the environment as
a way for the United States to extend a new form of leadership in
the sometimes troubled Western alliance as well as becoming the
conduit toward closer East-West ties in the coming years.
   ``Our shared heritage is the Earth,'' President Bush said during
his stay in Hungary. ``And the fate of the Earth transcends borders.
It is not just an East-West issue.''
   Dozens of international conferences have been held or are
scheduled for the next few years to deal with global warming, the
decay of the protective stratospheric ozone layer, dirty urban air,
and oceans contaminated with everything from medical wastes to
sprawling oil spills.
   All of these topics will be the focus of debate at the economic
summit today through Sunday in Paris. The environment is coming on
like ``a freight train'' as an international issue, Bush has said.
   His chief environmental spokesman, William Reilly, head of the
Environmental Protection Agency, complained recently that some of
the conference participants may be trying to move too quickly.
   ``There is something of a race on by some of the economic summit
participants ... to be the greenest of all on this issue,'' said
Reilly, the first EPA administrator ever to attend an economic
summit. ``Restoring the environment is not a sprinter's game; it's
going to require steady, long-term commitments.''
   The Bush administration, however, has been criticized by some
environmentalists for being too slow in asserting U.S. leadership on
dealing with the growing global environmental mess.
   Earlier this year the United States dragged behind in calling for
a ban on the production of chlorofluorocarbons, or CFCs, which are
blamed for depleting the ozone layer. The United States announced
support for a ban only after European nations did.
   The administration also waited until the last minute before
calling for an international workshop on global warming and then did
so after critics charged the president was backing away from a
campaign pledge to host such a conference. The workshop was to be
held in Washington, but now is planned for Geneva in October,
although Reilly insists the United States will remain its ``host.''
   The seven nations at the summit use about 60 percent of the
world's ozone-depleting CFCs and account for about 40 percent of the
world's carbon dioxide emissions from the burning of fossil fuels,
the principal culprit in global warming.
   ``You wouldn't launch a Marshall Plan at an economic summit,''
Reilly quipped to reporters recently while reviewing his
expectations of the Paris meeting, the 15th such summit and the
first in which the environment has held this much attention.
</TEXT>
