<FIRST>r a PM-MayorRescue     07-14 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mayor Rescue,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>San Francisco Mayor Talks Down Jumper At City Hall</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Art Agnos persuaded a distraught man
to come off a ledge on the second floor of the City Hall rotunda
after he had threatened to jump.
   The man, who identified himself only as Lawrence, climbed over
the railing onto an outer ledge of the rotunda Thursday afternoon.
He spoke incoherently with police before asking for the mayor.
   Agnos invited the man into his office for coffee, and the two
chatted for a half-hour. The man, dressed neatly in blue jeans and a
pale blue shirt, was then taken by a police psychiatric unit to San
Francisco General Hospital.
   ``He's troubled by what he sees in the streets,'' Agnos said,
referring to their conversation.
   Press secretary Eileen Maloney said Lawrence told the mayor he
receives Social Security payments for a disability but that he had
not been taking his medication.
</TEXT>
