<FIRST>u a PM-WanderingPlane-Rescue 1stLd-Writethru a0(Expands) 07-14
0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wandering Plane-Rescue, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0493,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bahamas Rescue `Once-In-A-Lifetime Thing' For Special Unit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Root, who ..., to UPDATE with report of shooting.
Pick up 5th graf, `I was ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Wandering Plane, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The four members of a special U.S. Air Force Reserve
unit who parachuted over the sinking wreckage of a single-engine
plane routinely practice the sea rescue maneuver. They've never
rehearsed a miracle, however.
   The team watched the powerless Cessna 210 spiral into the sea off
the Bahamian island of Eleuthera with Thomas Root slumped
unconscious in the pilot's seat. When they leaped from the HC-130
Hercules plane 3,000 feet above the crash site, they assumed they
would recover a body.
   ``Then we saw there was a survivor,'' said Tech. Sgt. Dave Dahl.
``It was very special _ on the verge of being a miracle. In fact, it
was right at miracle.''
   Root, who passed out after taking off from Washington National
Airport about 6:30 a.m. Thursday and flew for nearly four hours on
autopilot, was awakened by the impact and managed to hang onto a
raft dropped from the HC-130. Authorities said today that he had
been shot in the abdomen at some point during the flight, and he was
bleeding from the abdomen when rescued. He was listed in stable
condition at Memorial Hospital in Hollywood, north of Miami. It was
not immediately clear how the shooting occurred.
   ``I was slowly parachuting down then I heard from the plane that
he was alive. My first reaction was that they either saw a body
floating or they were mistaken,'' said Staff Sgt. Scott Tracy.
``It's almost unreal.''
   Around the country, nearly 82,000 Air Force Reserve personnel
augment the Air Force in crises and in peacetime.
   The unit from the 301st Aerospace Rescue and Recovery Squadron in
Homestead is one of three such teams trained to ``bring 'em back
alive,'' said Air Force Lt. Col. Robert Dubiel in Robins, Ga. The
others are based near Detroit, and near Portland, Ore., he said.
   ``They have to know how to pull them from the water, pluck them
off a mountain if they have to,'' Dubiel said. ``They have to be in
super condition.''
   The three squads had more than 400 military and civilian rescues
during the past 10 years, Dubiel said. The unit based in Homestead,
about 20 miles south of Miami, is credited with 142 rescues in the
Atlantic and the Caribbean.
   Dahl said there are fewer than 10 sea-parachute rescue missions
in any year around the world.
   ``We wait for years for one of these missions,'' said Dahl. ``For
everything to go perfectly like this is just a great feeling.''
   After Root was given first aid and oxygen aboard the raft, he was
airlifted aboard a Coast Guard HH-3 helicopter to Nassau, Bahamas,
for initial treatment. The 36-year-old lawyer from Alexandria, Va.,
was then taken to Opa-locka Airport north of Miami on a Coast Guard
jet.
   ``Looking back now, the whole scene was incredible,'' said Sgt.
Paul Hayden. ``It's like a once-in-a-lifetime thing.''
</TEXT>
