<FIRST>r p PM-KochAnnounces     07-14 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Koch Announces,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Koch Formally Enters Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch has announced plans to seek
election to a fourth term.
   ``In the course of 12 years, I think I've done a lot of good
things,'' Koch said Thursday. I've done a couple of stupid things.
... I believe that my three terms will be perceived historically as
very good for the City of New York.''
   Koch, 64, then quoted the Rev. Jesse Jackson and said, ``I don't
think God is finished with me yet.''
   Koch long has said he was running for another four years, but had
not formally entered the race until his announcement on a radio show
Thursday.
   Less than an hour before the show, reporters at City Hall asked
whether he would make a formal announcement and Koch answered: ``I'm
an informal kind of a guy.''
   Koch filed 40,769 signatures Thursday with the Board of Elections
to enter the Democratic primary.
   His prime opponent for that nomination, Manhattan Borough
President David Dinkins, filed 135,386. City Comptroller Harrison J.
Goldin is also seeking the Democratic nomination in the Sept. 12
mayoral primary.
   Former federal prosecutor Rudolph Giuliani faces Ronald Lauder in
the Republican primary.
</TEXT>
