<FIRST>r a PM-NewsConferenceShooting     07-14 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-News Conference Shooting,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Domestic Shooting Provides Prelude To News Conference on Crack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reporters gathering in a dilapidated
neighborhood for a news conference about drug abuse watched in shock
as a gun battle erupted in an alley across the street.
   City Councilman John P. Kennedy had called the news conference
Thursday on a curbside across from some abandoned houses that he
said were hangouts for crack cocaine dealers.
   Kennedy's intention was to dramatize the problem of drug abuse in
Columbus. But before he even arrived, ``gunshots and shouting broke
out in an alley just across the street,'' said reporter Jerry Revish
of Columbus TV station WBNS.
   Reporters immediately focused their attention and cameras on the
area, where a woman was firing a rifle from a fire escape, Revish
said.
   Morris Brown, 29, was taken to St. Anthony Medical Center in
Columbus, where he was treated for a gunshot wound in the shoulder,
WBNS reported.
   Brown was listed in fair condition Thursday night, said a woman
at St. Anthony's patient information desk who refused to give her
name.
   Police were questioning two suspects in the shooting Thursday
night, authorities told Columbus radio station WTVN. The two had not
been charged, the station reported.
   A woman who answered the telephone at the Columbus Division of
Police referred calls to the sergeant on duty, who was out of the
office.
   After the shooting, reporters regrouped at the news conference
site, where Kennedy was just arriving, Revish said.
   Kennedy called for the creation of a citywide drug coordinator to
help fight the battle against drugs.
</TEXT>
