<FIRST>r a PM-TroopersShot     07-14 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Troopers Shot,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspect Arrested in Shooting of New York State Troopers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOTOWA, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former detective agency employee has been
arrested in the shootings of two New York state troopers who were
lured to a secluded area by a man posing as a federal agent, police
said.
   Victor A. Pulecio, 23, was scheduled to be arraigned this
afternoon after his arrest Thursday at his parents' home. Rockland
County District Attorney Kenneth Gribetz said Pulecio would be
charged with two counts of attempted murder.
   Pulecio was being held at the Essex County Jail in Newark, said
State Police spokesman Capt. Thomas Gallagher. He said he didn't
know when extradition proceedings would begin.
   Gribetz said Pulecio has been identified by one of the wounded
officers. He said state police in Middletown also had taped
Wednesday's telephone call from a man who said he was a Treasury
agent and needed police backup at Ford Products in Valley Cottage.
The voice has been identified as Pulecio's, Gribetz said.
   Troopers Noel Sanchez, 30, and Christopher Elg, 26, were
dispatched to the site after the call. Pulecio was a former employee
of Sahler Corp., a detective agency that provided security for Ford
Products.
   A man there chatted with officers for about 20 minutes before
saying, ``I'm sorry, guys,'' and opening fire. A third trooper in a
separate car recorded part of the license plate number of the
gunman's gettaway car.
   Gribetz said authorities were still searching for a motive in the
shootings.
   Sanchez was in stable condition today at the Westchester County
Medical Center in Valhalla, N.Y., with a gunshot wound to the neck.
Elg, of Congers, N.Y., was treated for a graze wound to the forehead.
</TEXT>
