<FIRST>r i PM-Olivier     07-14 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Olivier,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family, Friends Attend Service for Olivier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASHURST, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laurence Olivier's family and friends
said farewell at a private funeral service today with the flowers
and words of Shakespeare's plays.
   Olivier, considered the foremost actor of his generation, died
Tuesday at age 82.
   Friends and family, including Olivier's wife, Joan Plowright, and
his four children, attended a private service in the countryside at
the 12th-century St. James's Church, near Olivier's home south of
London.
   Anthony Hopkins, who recently played Lear in a production at the
Olivier Theater in London, read the lines from Shakespeare's play:
   ``I have a journey, sir, shortly to go;
   ``My master calls me, I must not say no.
   ``The weight of this sad time we must obey;
   ``Speak what we feel, not what we ought to say.
   ``The oldest hath borne most: we that are young
   ``Shall never see so much, nor live so long.''
   The hymns were ``Dear Lord And Father of Mankind,'' ``God Be In
My Head,'' and ``The King of Love My Shepherd Is,'' one of Olivier's
favorites.
   Among the mourners were actors Douglas Fairbanks Jr., Sir Alec
Guiness and Sir John Mills.
   The family asked that anyone wishing to mark Lord Olivier's
memory make a donation to the Actors' Benevolent Fund or cancer
research or ``that trees should be planted to enrich and restore the
countryside.''
   Atop the casket lay a floral crown from Olivier's family, made up
of flowers and plants mentioned in the works of Shakespeare _
lavender, marjoram, marigolds, daisies, mint and daffodils.
Olivier's well-worn prayer book, a gift from his mother, was also
atop the casket.
   Along the path were floral tributes from John Gielgud, Elizabeth
Taylor and other less famous fans. One message read: ``In memory of
the greatest actor in the world from two of his greatest fans.''
   The card on Miss Taylor's bouquet said only, ``Adieu.''
   Following the funeral, Olivier's remains were to be cremated. A
public memorial service is planned in London, but a date has not
been announced.
</TEXT>
