<FIRST>r a PM-PitBullOrdinance     07-14 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pit Bull Ordinance,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>District Judge Upholds Ordinance Banning Pit Bulls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today upheld the constitutionality
of a Dade County pit bull ordinance that imposes severe restrictions
on the dogs, but delayed enforcement for 30 days.
   U.S. District Judge William M. Hoeveler ordered the grace period
``to give the dog owners who have not complied with the ordinance
requiring registration pending my verdict an opportunity to comply
with the ordinance.''
   In three days of hearings this week, witnesses testified that
only seven owners of pit bulls had registered a total of eight
animals even though thousands are believed to be in the county.
   The legislation came under fire in a lawsuit brought by the
Michigan-based American Dog Owners Association. Nova University law
professor Steve Wisotsky, representing dog owners, said the
measure's description of pit bulls was too vague.
   The ordinance was adopted in April following the mauling of a
young girl and her mother.
   Owners are required to register their dogs with Dade County
Animal Services in a 90-day period that ended today.
   Owners must confine or muzzle their dogs except at dog shows.
They may not be walked within 50 feet of any public school, and
owners must carry $300,000 in liability insurance ``or show other
financial responsibility.''
</TEXT>
