<FIRST>u a PM-Turner-Abortion 1stLd-Writethru a0508 07-14 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Turner-Abortion, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0508,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turner Stirs Controversy with Remark About Abortion Foes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with protesters picketing outside
today, new quotes; Picks up 6th graf, `Turner said ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abortion opponents, labeled ``idiots'' and
``Bozos'' by Turner Broadcasting System Chairman Ted Turner,
picketed outside TBS headquarters today and called for air time to
present their views.
   About 10 protesters marched outside Turner's CNN Center in
downtown Atlanta, watched by three policemen. One carried a sign
that said, ``I'm no Bozo.''
   Mary Boyert, a spokeswoman for Georgia Right to Life, said the
group objected to Turner's name-calling and to a pro-choice
documentary planned for broadcast on SuperStation TBS July 20.
Abortion foes want equal time on the cable TV station to show
``Eclipse of Reason,'' a film showing the results of a 24-week
abortion, she said.
   ``We're disappointed with the biased programming,'' she said.
   Turner, who put his outspoken manner on the back burner the past
few years as his business dealings became more time consuming,
showed he hasn't lost his flair for controversy when he made the
remarks about abortion foes in Los Angeles Wednesday.
   In a speech, Turner said TBS would present ``Abortion for
Survival,'' a program that takes a pro-choice slant in line with his
own views.
   Turner said a televised debate on the issue is scheduled to
follow the program.
   ``We'll give the other Bozos a chance to talk back,'' Turner
said. ``They look like idiots anyway.''
   The debate panel will include Rep. Robert Dornan, R-Calif.; Faye
Wattleton of Planned Parenthood; and Nellie Gray, president of March
for Life.
   An aide to Dornan, an abortion foe, said Thursday the congressman
was not personally offended by Turner's remarks and still planned to
participate in the debate.
   ``He's still scheduled,'' Brian Bennett, Dornan's chief of staff,
said speaking from Dornan's Orange County, Calif., office. ``He's
known Ted Turner a long time. He's not taking it personally.
   ``He knows (Turner) is just speaking rhetorically. It's part of
the rhetoric that comes with the issue.''
   Though Turner's remarks were reported across the country, even
making the front page of the Atlanta newspapers, TBS headquarters
reported receiving only moderate response.
   TBS spokeswoman Kitsie Bassett Riggall said about 20 telephone
calls were received, half of them objecting to Turner's comments or
the premise of the program.
   Ms. Riggall said controversial programming has on occasion
prompted hundreds of telephone calls. ``Believe me, this is not
overwhelming,'' she said.
   Turner in the past acquired the nickname ``Captain Outrageous''
for his outspokenness, though he has been notably mellow in the past
few years as the size of his media empire has grown and consumed
more of his time.
</TEXT>
