<FIRST>u i PM-Czechoslovakia-Hajek 1stLd-Writethru   07-14 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia-Hajek, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0538,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former `Prague Spring' Foreign Minister Detained</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Hajek released, details of
seminar; Pickup 5th graf pvs, `Hajek, 56...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Czechoslovak Foreign Minister Jiri
Hajek, who served during the Prague Spring reforms, was detained for
five hours today while on his way to give a lecture on the 1968
reform movement, sources said.
   Sources in Vienna and Prague, who requested anonymity, said
police in Prague detained Hajek at the Hotel Olympic. The sources
said a West German group was holding a seminar on Czechoslovak
history at the hotel.
   An emigre source in Vienna said earlier today that Hajek was
picked up with a West German citizen, but the sources in Prague and
a West German who witnessed the detention said Hajek was alone.
   The sources said the seminar, where Hajek was to speak about the
short-lived Prague Spring liberalization period, was banned by
authorities but that no one else was detained.
   The West German Foreign Minister, Hans-Dietrich Genscher, visited
Czechoslovakia this week and met Thursday with Hajek. In talks with
top Czechoslovak officials, Genscher reportedly stressed the
``special importance'' of human rights in boosting East-West
relations.
   The sources said the detention prevented Hajek from attending a
reception at the French Embassy marking the bicentennial of the
French Revolution.
   Hajek was released at 2:15 p.m. and taken home in a police car,
but by then it was too late for the reception.
   Hajek, 76, who served as foreign minister during the 1968 Prague
Spring reform period that was crushed by Soviet troops, had his
passport confiscated July 4 after he returned from a Scandinavian
trip.
   Sources in Vienna said he was told the measure was taken because
of interviews he gave Western media while he was abroad and because
he attended a meeting of the Socialist International in Stockholm
June 20-22.
   During the interviews, Hajek accused the Czechoslovak regime of
being slow to implement reforms.
   Hajek is a member of Charter 77, the Soviet bloc's oldest,
unofficial human rights organization. It was formed in January 1977
and named for the document issued by founding members calling on
Czechoslovakia to respect civil liberties. Its members are often
detained by authorities.
</TEXT>
