<FIRST>u w PM-Barry-Election 3rdLd-Writethru a0570 07-14 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barry-Election, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0570,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barry Reportedly Will Seek New Term</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Jackson comment. Picks up
4th graf pvs, bgng: `The Washington'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Marion Barry Jr., whose administration
has been dogged by scandal, will run for a fourth term and does not
expect Jesse Jackson to oppose him, a spokesman said today.
   ``The mayor definitely intends to seek re-election,'' Barry's
press secretary, John White, said. ``I think he generally feels that
he would like to run one more term to complete some of the projects
that he started.''
   Jackson, who had said through aides he would consider running for
mayor only if Barry stepped down, said in a newspaper interview he
has ``no plans'' to seek the post.
   ``I'll be doing more and more work out of Washington for the
cause of the Rainbow Coalition,'' he told the Detroit Free Press on
Thursday. Jackson, who has plans to move to the nation's capital by
the end of the summer, said it makes more sense to have a house than
to stay in hotels.
   Barry's decision to seek a new term comes after months of
speculation about his plans, particularly in view of a string of
high-level resignations, the conviction of several former aides on
criminal charges and the mayor's friendship with a man convicted on
drug charges in the Virgin Islands who is awaiting trial on
additional charges in Washington.
   The Washington Post today quoted Barry aides it did not identify
as saying that letting word out that the mayor would run was an
attempt to force Jackson out of contention.
   Barry has indicated previously he would announce his candidacy
officially in the fall.
   Jackson, in Detroit for a speech to the National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People on Thursday night, told the Post,
``I have no comment. I don't know the context in which (the Barry
statement) was made.''
   But White said Barry feels Jackson ``will keep his word, which
was that he would never run against the mayor.''
   ``We expect Jesse Jackson to actively campaign for the mayor's
re-election,'' another Barry aide, Anita Bonds, told the Post,
pointing to Barry's early support for both of Jackson's presidential
campaigns.
   White said he did not know whether Jackson and Barry have
discussed the mayor's candidacy.
   Barry's recent problems have prompted some business and community
leaders to urge him to step aside after three terms.
   Barry has weathered a series of personal and political crises
since becoming mayor in 1979. Several of his top aides, including
two former deputy mayors, have been convicted of crimes they
committed while in office.
   Most recently, Barry was reported to have visited a man, Charles
Lewis, at a Washington Ramada Inn last year while Lewis was
suspected of trafficking in drugs. Lewis has since been convicted in
the Virgin Islands of dealing cocaine and has been indicted in
Washington on charges that he sold cocaine while he stayed at the
Washington hotel last December.
   White said Barry has put the Lewis situation behind him. ``He
feels he has explained (his relationship with Lewis) and that no
matter what he says not everyone will believe him.''
   Several top aides, including Police Chief Maurice Turner, also
have resigned.
   At the same time, the city's homicide rate has soared.
   Police say the 372 killings in 1988 were a record and that the
229 slayings committed through Thursday this year put the city on
pace to far outstrip last yea's total. Authorities estimate at least
60 percent of the homicides have been drug-related.
   Announced candidates for mayor include Council Chairman David
Clarke and former utility executive Sharon Pratt Dixon, both
Democrats. They would face Barry in the Democratic primary. Success
in the primary is tantamount to a general election victory in this
heavily Democratic city.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
