<FIRST>r a PM-PrincipalFired     07-14 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Principal Fired,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Principal, Who Suggested He Go Rather Than Teachers, Is Laid Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elementary school principal who urged
the school board to fire him rather than cut any of the teachers in
this financially pressed school district, was out of a job today.
   Some of the board members had tears in their eyes as they voted
unanimously Thursday night to lay off Norman Najimy.
   ``This was the shortest and saddest meeting in our history,''
board member Donna Slowick said after the 20-minute session.
   Immediately afterward, Najimy, a teacher for 37 years, turned in
his keys to Superintendent George St. Pierre.
   Maintaining it could balance the books with the least impact on
the children, Najimy suggested that the Berkshire Hills community
could save about $40,000 by firing him and paying a teacher an extra
$3,000 to run its 200-pupil elementary school.
   ``Building faculty is the hardest thing to do,'' Najimy said.
``If we lose our teachers we will never get them back.''
   Even though voters in the little town of 1,600 people approved
overrides of property tax limits totaling $75,000, it was not enough
to cover boosts in health insurance, the breakdown of its heating
plant and rising tuition costs for its high school students, Najimy
said.
</TEXT>
