<SECOND>PM-Hurt In Hospital,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Infant's Arms and Legs Broken During Stay at Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 4-week-old baby suffered two broken arms and a
broken leg after being admitted to a hospital for breathing
problems, and hospital officials and police say they are trying to
learn how it happened.
   The baby, Jasmine Ghoston, suffered three fractures in each arm
and a fracture in one leg, said officials at Mercy Hospital and
Medical Center.
   The girl was listed in good condition at Children's Memorial
Hospital after her parents transferred her from Mercy on Thursday.
   ``We wanted to get her out of there,'' said her father, Anthony
Ghoston. ``She was was hurt bad, and they (hospital officials) still
haven't told us what happened.''
   Doctors plan to check the possibility the child suffered from
osteogenesis imperfecta, a genetic condition in which bones are
abnormally brittle, officials at Children's said.
   The baby was admitted to Mercy on Sunday after her parents
noticed she was having difficulty breathing. Two days later, the
fractures were discovered.
   ``A nurse went to feed the baby and noticed a limpness in the
limbs. She then called a doctor who took X-rays,'' said Mercy
spokeswoman Judy Traynor.
   Police detective Cmdr. Toby Burton said, ``We don't know of any
criminal activity being involved at this time, but we haven't ruled
out anything.
   ``We don't know if it was an accident, a medical problem, o if it
occurred at the hands of another.''
   ``I don't understand why somebody would want to do this to my
little baby,'' said the mother, Yolanda Blunt, ``She is so little.
It would have to be a very cruel person.''
   Mercy's marketing-communications director, Sherwood Zellermeyer,
said the hospital is doing its own internal investigation.
   The family's attorney, David B. Selig, filed a $10 million lawuit
in Cook County Circuit Court Thursday accusing the hospital of
negligence and carelessness. The lawsuit, filed in the child's name,
asks for $1 million in compensatory damages and $9 million in
punitive damages.
   Selig said the girl's parents have been ruled out as suspects.
Hospital records show the child was in good health when Ms. Blunt
left Mercy on Sunday night, and she did not return until Tuesday
afternoon, he said. No other family members came to the hospital
during that time, Selig said.
