<HEAD>Kurdish Leader, Two Others Slain in Apparent Terrorist Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf, ``A fourth...'' with 1 graf to CORRECT surname
to Liebhart. Pickup 3rd, ``Police said...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unidentified men stormed a meeting of
Kurdish activists in an apartment and fatally shot three men,
including the leader of an anti-Iranian faction, police said today.
   A fourth man, a Kurd bearing an Iranian diplomatic passport was
seriously wounded, said Werner Liebhart, a police chief in Vienna.
   Police said the dead included Abdul Rahman Qassemlou, 59, leader
of the anti-Iranian wing of the Kurdish Democratic Party.
   The Kurds are an ethnic minority of 20 million living in Turkey,
Iran, and Iraq and small enclaves of 500,000 each in Syria and the
Soviet Union.
   Liebhart said the other two killed were Abdullah Ghaderi-Azar,
37, a Kurd who police said had identification papers issued by
France, and Iraq-born Fadel Mala Mahmoud Rasoul, 38, who has held
Austrian citizenship since 1985.
   The three were living in Austria as political exiles.
   Police refused to release the name of the wounded man, who was
shot in the mouth and who had not been interviewed by authorities.
   Liebhart said the shooting occurred at 7:20 p.m. Thursday in an
apartment near the city center that was made available by an
unidentified Austrian woman.
   ``It seems that more than four people took part'' in the meeting,
Liebhart told reporters. ``We have to assume that it was a political
discussion.''
   Two or three men stormed into the apartment and opened fire,
Liebhart said. The three fatalities were shot in the head.
   It was not clear how the assailants gained entrance to the
apartment, since the door was not damaged, the police official said.
   Qassemlou, who was educated in France, lived there in exile for
several years. In an Austrian newspaper interview published in April
he said the ``Kurds' war against Tehran and Baghdad'' would continue
despite the cease-fire between the two countries since August 1988.
</TEXT>
