<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1316EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     07-14 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korea Accuses U.N., South Korea of Incursions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea on Friday accused the U.N.
Command of infiltrating its waters with three South Korean combat
vessels June 23 to provoke another Korean war.
   North Korean army Maj. Gen. Choe Ui Ung, speaking at a meeting of
the Korean Military Armstice Commission, also said South Korean
troops opened fire June 28 at a communist guard post along the
Demilitarized Zone that separates the two countries.
   He said the incidents were part of an effort to increase tensions
and prepare for a new war on the Korean peninsula and said South
Korea was stockpiling arms. No casualties were reported in the
incidents.
   The commission meeting, held in the truce village of Panmunjom,
had been called by North Korea.
   U.S. Navy Rear Adm. Larry G. Vogt, senior delegate of the U.N.
Command, rejected North Korea's charges as ``fabrications and
fiction'' aimed at propaganda.
   Vogt said his command investigated the claims and the charges
were unfounded. North Korea earlier reported the incidents in a
radio broadcast and a message.
   Vogt said he had proposed a joint investigation but the communist
side did not respond.
   The U.N. Command, led by the United States, was formed at the
start of the 1950-53 Korean War to help South Korea repel communist
invaders. The joint armistice commission is charged with maintaining
the cease-fire that ended the war and meets periodically at the
request of either side.
   Choe alleged the United States deploys more than 1,000 nuclear
weapons in South Korea and has recently brought in modern jet
fighters. He also charged that the command conducted more than 800
reconnaissance flights over North Korea this year.
   On the alleged arms buildup, Vogt said the command has been
forced to take ``firm actions in self-defense'' since 1957 when he
said the command temporarily suspended a section of the armistice
agreement which bans the introduction of reinforcing weapons. He
said this was done in order to counter North Korea's arms buildup.
   Choe did not respond.
   Also Friday, South Korea's largest opposition party accused
President Roh Tae-woo of ``political suppression'' and urged his
government to scrap plans to question opposition leader Kim Dae-jung.
   Lawmakers from Kim's Party for Peace and Democracy joined forces
in demanding intelligence agents stop harassing the party head and
withdraw a request to question him about a party lawmaker's illegal
trip to North Korea.
   The Agency for National Security Planning has asked to question
Kim and other senior party members in connection with a secret trip
to North Korea in August by lawmaker Suh Kyung-won, who has been
arrested.
   Kim turned down two agency requests Thursday and Friday to answer
questions, saying he had nothing to tell about Suh's trip.
   Trips to North Korea without prior government approval are a
crime in South Korea, which maintains all contacts and dialogue with
Pyongyang must be made through official channels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
