<DOCNO> AP890714-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Bishop     07-14 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Bishop,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cardinal Appeals For End of Persecution in China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic bishop of Hong Kong has
appealed for international pressure on Britain to offer refuge to
the territory's people as a safeguard from the uncertain future
under communist rule.
   Cardinal John B. Wu, in a letter to about 2,500 cardinals and
bishops seen Friday, also urged pressure on China to end persecution
of participants in the crushed pro-democracy movement.
   Britain has agreed to return Hong Kong to China in 1997, and
Beijing has promised that the territory can maintain its capitalist
economy and enjoy a ``high degree of autonomy'' for another 50 years.
   But the June 3-4 military suppression of the pro-democracy
movement in Beijing and subsequent crackdown on dissent throughout
China has led to a loss of confidence in the future among the 5.7
million people of Hong Kong.
   ``These events have shaken not just China, but the entire
world,'' Wu said. ``Hong Kong has felt particularly deeply the
sufferings of its Chinese brothers and sisters.''
   Wu argued that recent events in China have increased anxieties in
Hong Kong, and he said London had a constitutional and moral
obligation to provide safeguards for the territory's people.
   ``A right to enter the United Kingdom would, in no small measure,
help restore people's confidence in Hong Kong,'' he said, echoing
arguments made by many of the colony's public opinion leaders.
   Wu appealed to his fellow churchmen to urge their governments and
international bodies to use their influence with London ``to ensure
that the people of Hong Kong enjoy all those safeguards from the
United Kingdom which are their right.''
   Hong Kong church spokesman Rev. Louis Ha said the right to live
in the United Kingdom was such a safeguard.
   The British government, however, has stated it will grant the
right of abode to only a fraction of Hong Kong people. No details of
the plan have been released.
   Wu also wrote emotionally about China's crackdown on dissent,
calling it a ``reign of terror.'' He urged church leaders to seek
support for pressure on the Beijing government ``to put an end to
all persecution and ensure those who have already been arrested are
given fair trials.''
   The letter also discussed another sensitive issue in Hong Kong,
the wave of Vietnamese who have sailed from their communist homeland
to this territory in search of a new life. Nearly 50,000 ``boat
people'' languish in local camps.
   Overseas resettlement of boat people has slowed down, leading to
a Hong Kong government decision to seek the repatriation of all
Vietnamese who fled their homeland for economic reasons.
   ``Hong Kong is almost at the end of its tether and desperate to
find a solution for this crisis,'' Wu wrote. In his letter, the
cardinal asked for help in offering the Vietnamese ``permanent homes
as soon as possible'' in other countries.
   Nearly 270,000 people in Hong Kong are Roman Catholic, or about 5
percent of the population. The church wields much influence in the
community, as it runs almost 300 schools and many medical services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
