<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   07-14 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0566,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspected Collaborator Killed, 150,000 Under Curfew</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New thruout to update with fatal beating not linked to uprising,
updates injury toll and adds bombing in south Lebanon. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Masked Palestinians in the occupied Gaza Strip
today fatally stabbed a Palestinian suspected of collaborating with
Israel, Arab reports said. Soldiers reportedly wounded at least 11
Arabs in clashes.
   The army ordered 150,000 Palestinians to remain in their homes in
the West Bank to prevent violence on the second day of a major
Moslem holiday.
   In Israel, a Jewish man was beaten to death near the southern
town of Ashdod and police were questioning four Arabs, Israel radio
said. It said the victim, an elderly building contractor, was killed
by two of his Arab workers to whom he owned money.
   Initial reports said police suspected the killing could have been
linked to the uprising.
   The killing raised anti-Arab emotions in the town, and angry
residents gathered in the streets to demand that Arab workers be
banned from entering, Israeli reports said.
   In the Gaza Strip town of Rafah, masked Palestinian activists
killed 26-year-old Mahmoud Amasi, Arab reports said. Amasi was a
hashish dealer and a suspected collaborator with Israeli security
forces, the reports said.
   The army confirmed the death and said police were investigating.
   Amasi's death brought to 561 the number of Palestinians killed in
the 19-month uprising against Israeli rule in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip. Most victims died in army gunfire, but more than 70 have been
killed as alleged collaborators. Thirty-five Israelis have been
slain.
   Clashes occurred between soldiers and stone-throwing youths today
in the Gaza Strip's Khan Yunis and Jabaliya refugee camps and in
Nablus, the West Bank's largest city, Arab reports said. The reports
said 11 Palestinians were wounded. The army said it was checking the
reports.
   Curfews confining people to their homes were reported in Nablus
and in the Tulkarem refugee camp and nearby villages. Army
checkpoints also blocked entry to Jerusalem on some roads from the
West Bank.
   The moves came as Moslems observed Eid Al-Adha, four days of
feasting marking the end of the annual pilgrimmage to Mecca.
   In Lebanon, meanwhile, an Israel-backed Lebanese militiaman was
killed and two others were wounded when a mine exploded near
Jezzine, north of Israel's self-declared security zone in South
Lebanon, the army said.
   The victims were members of the Israeli-financed South Lebanon
Army militia, which helps patrol the 6- to 10-mile-wide strip Israel
created in 1985 to protect its northern border from attack.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890714-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1334EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Angola     07-14 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government and Rebels to Resume Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUANDA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government officials and U.S.-backed rebels
will resume peace talks Sunday in the Zairean capital of Kinshasa, a
newspaper reported.
   Without identifying its sources, the state-owned Jornal de Angola
said Friday the talks originally were to start Saturday but were
postponed to allow Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko to return from
Paris, where he has been attending bicentennial celebrations of the
French Revolution.
   Mobutu was named mediator of a commission to negotiate an end to
Angola's 14-year civil war at a June 22 African summit where Angolan
President Jose Eduardo dos Santos and rebel leader Jonas Savimbi
agreed to a cease-fire and peace talks.
   Dos Santos called a government delegation home from Kinshasa two
weeks ago after only two days of talks with the guerrilla National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola, claiming the rebels
violated the June 24 cease-fire.
   The decision to resume comes on the heels of a three-day visit to
Luanda by Herman Cohen, assistant secretary of state for African
affairs, who apparently encouraged dos Santos to reopen talks.
   According to Jornal de Angola, next week's talks will focus on
the integration of guerrillas into Angolan society and institutions.
   African diplomats in Angola say the talks probably will deal with
ways of policing the truce.
   Government reports have said guerrillas cut power lines to the
capital and killed civilians in a number of attacks breaking the
cease-fire. The rebels have said both sides have committed minor
violations.
   The rebels' Voice of the Black Cockerel radio station, monitored
Thursday in Luanda, said a rebel delegation already is in Kinshasa,
``waiting for the government.''
   Angola's armed forces chief, Antonio dos Santos Franca was
expected to head the government delegation, that also is slated to
include dos Santos' presidential secretary on defense and security,
Jose Maria.
   The rapprochement follows a December regional accord under which
South Africa agreed to pull out of Angola and Namibia in return for
the withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops helping Angola's government
fight the guerrillas.
   Angola is eager for membership of the International Monetary Fund
and U.S recognition withheld since a Marxist-oriented government
seized power after the country gained independence from Portugal in
1975.
   Washington has pledged to continue aid to the guerrillas,
estimated at $15 million a year, during a two-year period of
national reconciliation.
</TEXT>
