<DOCNO> AP890714-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1319EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-GreenRiver 2ndLd-Writethru a0587 07-14 0895</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Green River, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0587,0915</SECOND>
<HEAD>Task Force Claims to Have `Viable Suspect' For Serial Killings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to CORRECT number of victims to 48 sted 49,
explanation of change, add new detail on videotapes; Picks up 9th graf,
`The nationally ...' ^LaserPhoto SX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After searching seven years for one of the
nation's worst serial killers, police say a former law student is a
``viable suspect'' in the Green River slayings of 48 women, and
perhaps other killings in the Northwest.
   William Jay Stevens II, 38, who is serving a jail term for
burglary, was named in an affidavit made public Thursday.
   The affidavit was filed to obtain a warrant to search two of
Stevens' residences in Spokane, 290 miles east of Seattle.
   ``Records obtained thus far have failed to provide him with an
alibi for any of the 49 suspected Green River homicides, or any of
those in the cities of Portland or Spokane,'' the affidavit said.
   ``Instead, interviews and records have produced the following
facts that tend to establish that Stevens is a viable suspect in the
Green River homicides and possibly others in the Pacific Northwest.''
   While the affidavit said there were 49 murders linked to the
Green River serial killer, King County Capt. Bob Evans, commander of
a task force investigating the case, said today there were only 48.
   Police searched the residences Wednesday, producing an additional
truckload of material including crime reports, 1,800 videotapes,
maps, credit cards, 14 police badges and two Seattle police uniform
shirts, according to court documents.
   Evans said today that some of the videotapes were homemade and
that others were commercially produced. He declined to say what any
of the tapes depicted.
   Forty to 50 cartons of confiscated materials arrived in Seattle
Thursday afternoon, and it could take a month or longer to sort
through them, police said.
   The Green River case involves the deaths of 40 women and the
disappearance of at least eight others in Washington state and
Oregon from 1982 to 1985. Most of the victims were young and almost
all were linked to prostitution. Early victims were found along or
near the Green River, southeast of Seattle.
   The nationally syndicated television show ``Manhunt'' aired a
program on the slayings Dec. 8. It generated thousands of calls,
including one from a viewer who told police to check a third-year
student at Gonzaga University Law School in Spokane, said King
County Capt. Bob Evans, commander of a task force investigating the
case.
   After finding Stevens, police found he had walked away from a
Seattle work release center in January 1981, before finishing a
one-year sentence for burglarizing a police equipment store.
   Stevens was rearrested Jan. 10 and is serving the rest of that
burglary sentence, plus an additional term for escape that will
expire Sept. 25, in King County jail.
   He has not been arrested or charged in connection with any of the
Green River killings.
   The affidavit also said the basement of a house Stevens owned
near Portland contained a secret room hidden behind a sliding
bookcase. The bookcase was activated by a switch on the wall or an
electric garage door opener. The home, which Stevens owned from 1981
to 1985, was one of several residences he had during the period, the
affidavit said.
   Several people quoted in the affidavit said Stevens said he liked
pornography, frequented prostitutes and carried photographs of
mutilated women.
   His father told The Associated Press his attorney had advised him
not to speak with reporters. Stevens declined a visit from an AP
reporter Thursday night.
   ``Any allegations of Bill being involved in that kind of a
serious crime are purely ridiculous,'' said Craig Beles, one of
Stevens' attorneys.
   Beles said he thinks the task force is ``grabbing at straws.''
   Besides the Green River slayings, the affidavit said Stevens may
be linked to an unidentified number of bodies found along highways
between Portland, Ore., and Vancouver, British Columbia, and from
Seattle to Spokane.
   After rearresting Stevens, police searched his room in his
parents' Spokane home after finding that Stevens owned a former
patrol car from Everett, Wash., and had equipped it ``like a real
police car,'' the affidavit said.
   Investigators had speculated that ``the killer could be a cop or
someone posing as a cop,'' Evans said.
   During that search police also found credit card receipts that
helped them trace Stevens' moves during the years of the Green River
killings.
   The materials found in Wednesday's searches at the parents' home
and at a rental home near Gonzaga University did not include any
clothing, jewelry or other effects belonging to any of the Green
River victims, most of whom were found naked. There was ``no smoking
gun,'' Evans said.
   Items seized included police records of sex crimes from Portland.
   In the affidavit, police quoted friends of Stevens saying he had
tried to pass himself off as a policeman and CIA agent who went on
``missions.''
   Some said Stevens would be hyperactive after these missions and
``acted very weird while `coming down,''' the affidavit said.
   The 40-page document said the task forcereceived several tips
about Stevens in 1986, including a call from Oregon saying Stevens
told friends the Green River killings were done for snuff films _
pornographic films that purport to show actual killings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
