<FIRST>r i AM-China     07-14 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Censors Pledge to Expunge Unacceptable Literature</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China-Songs, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese censors have pledged to expunge
unacceptable political works from bookstores, official reports said
Friday, and prosecutors said they will continue to punish dissidents
``without mercy.''
   Beijing officials also warned that more than a month after the
bloody military demolition of the student-led pro-democracy movement
that ``counterrevolutionary'' resistance persists, and the capture
of rebels is crucial to the survival of the state.
   Two more protesters were executed in southwestern city of
Chengdu, a foreign source in the Sichuan provincial capital said
Friday, bringing to 29 the known number put to death for actions
during the past month of social unrest.
   The State Press and Publications Administrations has taken new
measures to clean up the publishing industry, the official People's
Daily reported. It said there will be tighter surveillance of
pornographic material and a sweep against ``counterrevolutionary and
bourgeois liberalization propaganda.''
   Already, Culture Ministry workers have raided bookstalls to
remove works by scholars wanted by police for advocating democratic
reform before the June 3-4 military assault crushed the
pro-democracy movement and solidified power for senior leader Deng
Xiaoping and other aging ideologues.
   Before then, writers enjoyed a period of relative freedom of
expression, and publishers sought profits from adventure stories and
romances, some of dubious taste, popular among the general public.
   It said censors in the past had not been strict enough and
publishing companies ``pursuing economic results gave up principle
and flooded the book market with low-grade and vulgar materials
which contain violent murders and obscene pornography which have
corrupted people's souls.''
   The Beijing Daily quoted Li Qiyan, Communist Party deputy
secretary for Beijing, as saying organizers of the
``counterrevolutionary rebellion'' still are at large and ``their
capture is of vital importance to the survival of the party, the
stability of the society and the fundamental interest of the
people.''
   He said the counterrevolutionaries, China's term for leaders of
the democracy movement, ``are so arrogant that they are still
distributing anti-revolutionary rumor, resorting to demagoguery ...
and putting up a vain resistance.''
   At the same meeting of senior Beijing officials, municipal party
chief Li Ximing said supporters of ``bourgeois liberalization,'' of
Western ideas and culture, ``will never accept their defeat ... but
use every method to spoil our most important work.''
   In a separate report from the official Xinhua News Agency, senior
prosecutor Feng Jinwen said all those who violated the law during
the recent unrest will be punished ``without mercy.''
   Feng called for speedy trials and harsh verdicts for such crimes
as organizing and planning riots and rebellion in collaboration with
reactionary forces at home and abroad in an attempt to overthrow the
socialist system, inciting people to riot with counterrevolutionary
slogans, beating and killing troops, destroying or setting fire to
military vehicles and seizing weapons.
   In Chengdu, two men were executed July 8 for ``beating, smashing,
looting and burning'' _ a catchall of crimes China uses for rioting,
a foreign source said Friday, quoting local press reports.
   The source said the Chengdu court sentenced another man to death
with a two-year stay of execution and gave life sentences to three
others, one for arson and two for ``hooliganism.''
   Chengdu courts in the past week have sentenced 20 others to
prison terms ranging from five years to life, he said.
   Up to 30 people were killed in clashes between police and rioters
in Chengdu on June 4 and 5. China says about 200 civilians were
killed in Beijing. Chinese sources and Western diplomats say
thousands were slain.
   Meanwhile, officials continued a concerted campaign to convince
foreign tourists and businessmen they should return to China.
   The capital on Friday opened an international trade fair with
exhibits from 24 countries, and Xinhua said the ``festive and
friendly atmosphere at the fair did not seem to be affected by the
martial law still going on in the city.''
</TEXT>
