<SECOND>PM-Wandering Plane-Family,2nd Ld-Writethru,a0629,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Say Pilot May Have Been Shot</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf pvs `Hollywood, Fla.,...' to UPDATE
with FBI also saying Root was shot. </HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto WX6</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kathy Root said she never gave up hope her
husband would survive, even as his small plane flew hundreds of
miles out of control with pilot Thomas Root apparently unconscious
in the cockpit.
   Police said today that Root had been shot through the abdomen
before his plane crash-landed in the Atlantic near the Bahamas.
   Hollywood, Fla., Police Chief Richard Witt said Root had been
shot at close range, but didn't say the wound was self-inflicted.
Authorities earlier had speculated that Root had suffered a heart
attack or inhaled carbon monoxide.
   FBI agent William Gavin also said that Root had been shot.
   However, the National Transportation Safety Board refused to
confirm the police version of events. Andrew Alston, an air safety
investigator, said there was no conclusive evidence that Root's
injury was a gunshot wound, although he acknowledged there was a
``burn area'' around the wound.
   Alston said doctors had removed a ``very, very small fragment of
metal,'' which would be analyzed to determine if it was part of a
bullet.
   Mrs. Root, who was en route to Florida, could not immediately be
reached for comment about the police reports. Earlier, Root's family
requested that Memorial Hospital in Hollywood not release any
information on his injuries.
   Root remained in stable condition today under heavy sedation
after undergoing three hours of exploratory surgery.
   Signe Schilperoort, a paralegal at Root's firm, Thomas L. Root
P.C., said today that Root is a gun collection.
   ``I've been under the impression that he has been involved in
selling some of his guns,'' she said. ``My assumption is that he had
some (guns) in the plane and something went off when the plane went
down.''
   Kevin Quarles, a researcher the firm, said he was unaware of any
problems facing Root.
   ``There was no outward appearance of any undue stress or any set
of circumstances that would lead or contribute to, as is being
hinted at, an apparent suicide attempt,'' Quarles said.
   ``It was like a roller coaster,'' Mrs. Root, 35, said Thursday
about the daylong wait before her husband was rescued after
incredibly surviving the crash.
   And her message to her husband? ``I said to tell him, `Root, you
really did it this time,''' Mrs. Root said she told hospital
officials who called her from Florida.
   The 36-year-old lawyer was flying his own plane to North Carolina
when he became ill. His plane winged southward, running out of fuel
and crashing into the ocean where Air Force parachutists pulled him
from the water.
   ``This is somebody you've loved and lived with a long time. The
suddenness of it is breathtaking, awful,'' said Mrs. Root after her
agonizing eight hours of uncertainty. ``It was very exhausting, very
difficult to deal with.''
   Mrs. Root said she first heard her husband's flight was in
trouble around 8 a.m. when air traffic control officials called to
say they ``had not heard from him.''
   She said she was updated throughout day about the status of plane
and eventually saw TV pictures of her husband being pulled from the
water.
   Mrs. Root, who celebrated her 10th wedding anniversary last week,
said she never gave up hope her husband would survive.
   ``I decided I was not going to believe he was dead until they
told me he was dead,'' she said.
   But she said the hours of uncertainty were ``horrible, awful.
It's a terrible feeling.''
   Coast Guard Capt. Dr. James Rahman said Root may have passed out
from carbon monoxide poisoning in the cockpit of his single-engine
Cessna and that water splashing in his face apparently roused him.
   Mrs. Root said she told only the oldest of their three children,
7-year-old T.J. (Thomas), what had happened, and ``he took it very
hard and was very sad, and very elated when we found out he had been
pulled out of the water.''
   The couple's other two children, Leslie and Travis, are 4 and 1.
