<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     07-14 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tamil Leaders Killed By Tamil Rebels During Meeting</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This story was submitted to a Sri Lankan
government censor, who did not make any changes.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Tamil Tiger rebels met with
moderate Tamil leaders and fatally shot two of their hosts before
they were killed by bodyguards, officials said Friday.
   Appapillai Amirthalingam, the leader of the Tamil United
Liberation Front, and Vettivelu Yogeswaran, a party colleague, were
killed Thursday at their common residence in the city.
   Sarojini Yogeswaran, speaking Friday before a court of inquiry,
told Magistrate Mohammed that she offered tea and biscuits to the
three visitors.
   ``They were having a friendly discussion for about 20 minutes and
then we heard loud noises,'' she said.
   Several people ran into the room and found the two Tamil leaders
lying in a pool of blood and heard more shooting outside, she said.
   Police said all three assailants were shot and killed by
bodyguards.
   Another Tamil front leader, Murugesu Sivasithamparam, was
seriously wounded in the shooting.
   Mrs. Yogeswaran named two of the visitors as Visvu and Aloysius
and said they were Tamil Tigers from Vavuniya, 135 miles north of
Colombo.
   A statement Friday from the Tamil Tigers, however, denied
involvement in the murders and said the suggestions had emanated
from the Indian High Commission, or embassy.
   ``We deny categorically the reports emanating from Indian High
Commission in Colombo that one of the members of the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam was involved in the killings,'' the statement
said.
   An Indian High Commission spokesman, who cannot be identified
under briefing rules, denied the mission had suggested a Tamil Tiger
involvement. ``Perhaps it is only their guilty conscience
speaking,'' he said, refusing to elaborate.
   Tamils comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people. The
rebels claim Tamils are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who
make up 75 percent of the population and control the government and
the military.
   The Tamil United Liberation Front has differed with demands by
the government and the Tiger rebels that Indian soldiers posted on
the island nation be withdrawn.
   The demand followed talks in May between the rebels and the
government, the first direct contact between the two sides since the
Tamil Tigers launched a war for an independent nation in 1983.
   Amirthalingam in public statements welcomed the demand but said
the withdrawal should be gradual and done only after political
powers were given to the Tamils. India has said it will pull out its
estimated 40,000 troops after this condition is met.
   Amirthalingam, a lawyer, was elected to Parliament in 1956. His
party became the second largest group in Parliament after the 1977
elections but was relegated to the background after the Tamil Tigers
launched their militant movement.
   India became involved in Sri Lanka's ethnic problems because its
own 60 million Tamils are sympathetic to the rebel cause.
</TEXT>
