<FIRST>u w PM-FernaldProbes 1stLd-Writethru a0600 07-14 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fernald Probes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0600,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Investigating Alleged Financial Fraud at Weapons Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new 4th graf, Henson Moore, with deputy secretary saying
department not told about FBI probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI said today it is conducting a
preliminary investigation of alleged financial fraud at an Energy
Department plant in Ohio that makes materials for nuclear weapons.
   Edwin Boldt, an FBI spokesman in Cincinnati, said the probe was
unrelated to the Energy Department's decision to launch on Thursday
its own investigation of environmental controls and other operations
at the Feed Materials Production Center, one of the key contributors
to U.S. nuclear weapons production.
   The plant is situated at Fernald, about 18 miles north of
Cincinnati.
   Henson Moore, the deputy energy secretary, said in an interview
that his department had not been notified of the Justice Department
probe, which marks the third time in recent weeks that FBI agents
have entered federal nuclear facilities.
   Pete Kelley, a spokesman for Westinghouse Materials Co. of Ohio,
which operates the plant under an Energy Department contract, said
he was unaware of the FBI inquiry.
   Westinghouse announced earlier this week it was shutting down
production indefinitely in order to focus more work on cleaning up
the site's hazardous wastes.
   Westinghouse said the shutdown decision was unrelated to the
Energy Department probe.
   Will Callicott, a department spokesman, said today the shutdown
was temporary and would not interfere with normal weapons production
schedules. He said the shutdown decision was made by Westinghouse
alone and that he could not comment on how long it might last.
   Boldt said in a telephone interview that the FBI investigation
was triggered by an allegation of criminal wrongdoing in contracting
of the Fernald plant work. He declined to identify either the origin
of the allegation, the date of its receipt by the FBI or the
specific nature of the alleged fraud.
   He also declined to say whether the charge was against an
employee of the Energy Department, Westinghouse or another
contractor at the site.
   ``It could concern any level of the whole contract process,'' he
said, from the granting of contracts to their execution.
   Callicott said he was not sure whether the department had been
informed of the FBI investigation and had no immediate comment.
   Boldt said he believed it was the first such FBI inquiry at the
Fernald plant, and added that the investigators had not yet
determined whether a crime had been committed.
   He stressed that the inquiry had no connection to the plant's
production facilities.
   ``There's no physical danger involved; it involves paperwork,''
Boldt said.
   The plant processes uranium compounds, produces uranium billets
for nuclear weapons production and makes uranium target elements for
defense nuclear reactors.
   FBI agents in June raided an Energy Department weapons production
center in Colorao in search of evidence of criminal violations in
the storage of hazardous wastes, and the bureau on July 6 opened a
similar probe at a department facility in New York states.
   Callicott said there was nothing to report on the department's
own investigation at Fernald, which is focusing on health and safety
measures, documentation, permits, planning and management. He said
it would last about a month and a half.
</TEXT>
