<FIRST>r i AM-Somalia     07-14 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Somalia,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Civilians and Troops Killed in Shooting Outside Somali Mosque</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops opened fire Friday on worshipers
outside a mosque in Mogadishu, the Somali capital, and state radio
reported eight people were killed in what the government called
religious disturbances.
   A resident said it appeared troops opened fire as Moslems left
their place of prayer during Eid al-Adha, the three-day Feast of
Sacrifice that is Islam's holiest celebration.
   The resident, who spoke on condition he not be identified
further, said gunfire erupted around midday and continued
sporadically through the afternoon. He said most of the shooting
appeared to be around a mosque in a western neighborhood.
   The shootings come in a week of unconfirmed reports that
authorities have detained several Moslem religious leaders.
   A Ministry of the Interior statement broadcast on state radio
said a group of ``troublemakers masquerading behind the cloak of
religion'' started the disturbances in Hodhan neighborhood.
   The report, monitored in Nairobi, said security forces were
called out to curb the disturbances but the ``troublemakers refused
to disperse peacefully.''
   Fighting broke out and eight people were killed and 24 were
injured, according to the statement. The dead included
``troublemakers'' and members of the security forces, it said.
   The resident said the government imposed a 6 p.m. to 6 a.m.
curfew in the capital.
   He said he saw little activity during an afternoon drive through
Mogadishu, except for two soldiers guarding an army post.
   ``However, people in the neighborhood say they've heard gunfire
all around,'' he said.
   On Sunday, an unidentified gunman shot and killed Mogadishu's
Roman Catholic Bishop Salvatore Pietro Colombo. It was not known
whether Friday's disturbances were related.
   This East African nation on the Indian Ocean has been led since
1969 by the autocratic President Siad Barre, who allows no
opposition to his rule. It is difficult to get news from the country.
   Since 1981, the government has battled the Somali National
Movement, a northern insurgency that demands Barre's removal.
Intensified fighting between the rebels and the government the past
18 months has driven more than 200,000 Somalis into refugee camps in
neighboring Ethiopia.
   The impoverished nation is overwhelmingly pastoral and most of
the 9 million people are Moslem.

</TEXT>
