<SECOND>AM-Cigarette Papers,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Chain Agrees To Stop Selling Cigarette Papers In Baltimore</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of ministers used a petition drive to
get a drug store chain to pull cigarette rolling papers from shelves
in the Baltimore area and hopes to expand the ban to all stores in
the chain.
   The Southern Christian Leadership Conference had asked Rite Aid
to discontinue sales of the product in Baltimore because it can be
used to make marijuana cigarettes.
   Ray Doering, a Rite Aid spokesman at the company's headquarters
in Harrisburg, Pa., said the papers would be removed from about 80
stores. The chain has 2,281 stores in 22 Eastern states.
   ``No decision has been made with respect to the rest of the
chain,'' he added.
   The Rev. Henry A. Silva, national vice president of the SCLC,
said Thursday that the group will increase pressure on Rite Aid to
stop selling the papers from all stores.
   Olivia E. Carter, president of the Baltimore chapter of the SCLC,
said the committee also has its sights on drug dealers' use of
public telephones to conduct drug transactions on street corners and
intends to seek telephone company assistance in investigating the
practice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
