<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1443EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-RetailSales     07-14 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Retail Sales,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Auto and Home Furnishing Purchases Drag Down Retail Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales fell 0.4 percent in June, dragged
down by falling auto and home furnishing purchases, the government
reported Friday, and analysts said big-ticket items would continue
to bear the brunt of the anti-inflation fight.
   ``The decline in sales reflects that people are getting a little
cautious about spending their money,'' said David Wyss, senior
financial economist for DRI@McGraw-Hill, a Lexington, Mass.,
economic forecasting organization.
   ``That's partially because there's been a lot of talk about the
risk of recession and people are taking that seriously,'' he
explained.
   Robert G. Dederick of Northern Trust Co. in Chicago, agreed,
saying: ``The pocketbook hasn't been zipped up completely, but it's
closed to a considerable degree.''
   Rosalind Wells, chief economist for the National Retail Merchants
Association in New York, noted the sales decline was concentrated in
the durable goods area and predicted the pattern would continue for
the remainder of the year because of high interest rates.
   The Commerce Department reported that sales fell to a seasonally
adjusted $140.8 billion last month after dropping 0.1 percent in
May. It was the first back-to-back monthly decline since 1987 when
sales declined 0.8 percent in September and 0.9 percent in October.
   Retail spending is watched closly as a measure of the overall
economy since it accounts for about a third of economic activity.
   Car sales, which represent about 20 percent of total retail
sales, led the overall decline last month. They fell 2.0 percent,
following a 1.8 percent drop in May. It was the steepest fall since
a 4.0 percent decline in October 1987.
   However, Dederick and Michael Evans of Evans Economics Inc. of
Washington said auto sales have picked up since the June survey was
taken.
   Some analysts said the latest retail sales report would provide
the Federal Reserve additional incentive to lower interest rates as
it seeks a ``soft-landing,'' rather than drive the economy into a
recession as it fights inflation.
   ``It's not a question of whether the Fed will ease further,''
said David Jones, an economist for Aubrey G. Lanston &amp; Co. in New
York. ``It's only a matter of when.''
   Until recently, interest rates have risen as the Fed tightened
its grip on credit to slow the economy and stem inflation. While
rates have begun to fall, they are still high enough to affect
spending on durable goods _ big-ticket items expected to last more
than three years.
   Durable goods sales were off 1.3 percent in June after falling
0.5 percent in May, Commerce said. Besides autos, sales of furniture
and other home furnishings were off 0.1 percent.
   Sales of non-durable goods rose 0.2 percent, including a 2.1
percent increase in department store and other general merchandise
spending and a 1.9 percent hike in clothing sales.
   ``The one shining light will continue to be apparel,''
particularly women's clothing, said Ms. Wells of the National Retail
Merchants Association. ``It's the only area where there's pent-up
demand,'' she said, following several years when women postponed
purchases ``because they didn't like the style or whatever.''
   Non-durable categories posting sales declines included food
stores, down 0.7 percent; gasoline stations, down 0.5 percent;
restaurants and bars, down 0.2 percent and drug stores, off 0.3
percent.
   Retail sales were up 5.3 percent from April through June,
compared with the same period in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
