<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     07-14 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rival Moslems Clash over Water and Land; One Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Moslem sects in the Central Asian republic of
Tadzhikistan fought over water and land rights, and one person was
killed and 18 were wounded, Tass reported Friday.
   Thousands of people, some with guns, clashed Thursday night
between the villages of Vorukh and Chorku in the Isfara region, the
traditional site of rivalries between Iranian-speaking and
Turkic-speaking Moslems.
   Tass, the official Soviet news agency, said Communist Party first
secretaries of the neighboring republics of Kirghizia and
Tadzhikistan rushed to the scene to calm things down.
   Elsewhere in the Soviet Union, ethnic tension continued to run
high in Nagorno-Karabakh and Georgia in the Caucasus Mountains,
according to reports reaching Moscow.
   The violence continued as preparations continued for a Communist
Party Central Committee meeting in late July on nationality problems
that have erupted under the liberalizing reforms of President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev. Authorities have not announced a date for the
plenum.
   The latest violence in Soviet Central Asia stems from an old
dispute about land and water use at Isfara, in Leninabad Oblast on
the border between Kirghizia and Tadzhikistan.
   The border near the disputed area is jagged as authorities
gerrymandered along ethnic lines when they carved the republics from
the former Tsarist province of Turkestan in the 1920s.
   Cooperative use of an irrigation canal at Isfara ended at the
beginning of this year when the disputing parties filled it with
stones, ``causing substantial agricultural losses,'' Tass reported.
   The situation worsened the last three months as local authorities
decided to build additional settlements in the area ``without
undertaking the necessary consultations with residents'' on water
and energy supplies, it said.
   In Stepanakert, capital of the Nagorno-Karabakh Autonomous
Region, Armenian residents circulated a photograph of an Armenian
watchman killed at a livestock complex Wednesday night in the nearby
town of Shush, said a worker at the State Radio and Television
Committee there.
   ``His throat was slit and his eyes were cut out,'' said the
worker, an Armenian who declined to identify himself.
   Demonstrations began nearly two years ago in Nagorno-Karabakh and
the neighboring republic of Armenia to protest the administration of
the enclave by the Azerbaijani Republic. Nagorno-Karabakh lies
within Azerbaijan, a predominately Moslem republic, but the majority
are Armenian Christians.
   No one has been arrested for the most recent murder, although
investigators have been sent to the region and Interior Ministry
troops have been patrolling all week, according to official reports.
   In the nearby republic of Georgia, the situation remained tense
in the town of Marneuli, said Roland Beridze of the Georgian
Ministry of Foreign Affairs. Five people were hurt in a June 25
disturbance in Marneuli, but the exact nature of the problem has not
been reported by the Soviet media.
</TEXT>
