<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1452EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Summit-Japan Bjt   07-14 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Japan, Bjt,660</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Uno Seeks to Assert Japan's Leadership, Reassert Government's Standing
^By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PARIS (AP)_ Japan's embattled prime minister, a part-time poet,
spoke lyrically of brotherly love and the future in explaining his
vision of the Paris summit. But beneath Sousuke Uno's soft words was
his determination to overcome sex and money scandals and maintain
his party's three-decade hold on power.
   The 66-year-old Uno, who took office only a month ago after the
downfall of his predecessor, Noboru Takeshita, heralded his arrival
in Paris for the 15th annual economic summit with lavish promises of
aid for poorer nations and the environment.
   To promote his plan, Uno quickly threw himself into a series of
bilateral meetings with leaders of countries both rich and poor,
ranging from the United States and Great Britain to Bangladesh and
Mexico.
   President Bush gave him a personal boost Friday by suggesting
they treat each other on a first-name basis, saying ``close personal
relations'' were important for their countries' ties, Japanese
officials said.
   ``Thank you, George,'' Uno said as he left a short bilateral
meeting.
   At the meeting, the two leaders agreed to launch talks on
removing trade barriers. The move gives Bush the opportunity to
press Japan to open its markets further to U.S. goods while
satisfying Japan in removing such talks from the threat of
retaliation posed by the U.S. trade bill.
   Japanese officials have spoken confidently here of the
strengthened role their nation will take in future meetings.
   While Japan has been criticized for its excessive trade
surpluses, chief government spokesman Taizo Watanabe said, officials
are now ``determined to be an active member of the summit and try to
contribute as much as possible to the welfare and future growth and
burden-sharing of the next seven years.
   ``(The aid proposals) are signs of determination on the part of
Japan and Uno himself to try to contribute to the constructive
discussion of the summit meetings.''
   Watanabe said that enroute to Paris, Uno, the author of three
books of haiku poetry, told his spokesman he sees the summit as a
forum for love for humanity through fighting terrorism and drugs,
light for the future through economic growth and burden-sharing by
helping nations in debt.
   Still, Uno and his Liberal Democratic Party, which has governed
Japan since 1955, may be too deeply mired in problems at home to win
total forgiveness from voters through deft summit work.
   Political analysts were predicting Uno's party would lose its
majority in the upper house of the Diet (Parliament) in elections on
July 23 in the wake of an unpopular sales tax, a widespread
influence-peddling scandal and allegations Uno kept paid mistresses,
including a geisha.
   The allegations about Uno became widespread soon after he took
over last month from Takeshita, who resigned as prime minister after
accepting responsibility for an influence-peddling scandal that
brought down three members of his Cabinet.
   Uncharacteristically for Japan, where political wives are nearly
anonymous, photos of Mrs. Uno and the Uno family were featured
prominently in a press packet prepared for foreign reporters
covering the summit.
   At the summit, Uno will pledge nearly $40 billion in new aid
funds, including a $35 billion extension of Japan's program, which
had been scheduled to end this year, to recycle its trade surpluses
for the benefit of developing countries.
   Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, who met with Uno on
Thursday, was ``very impressed'' with the aid figures, officials
said.
   Canada's finance minister, Michael Wilson, welcomed the debt
relief, which will be one of the discussion topics between the seven
summiteers.
   ``Japan is in the position to take the lead role here,'' he told
reporters. ``They are in the strongest position from the
balance-of-payments standpoint.''
   Japan also announced it will set aside $2.25 billion for projects
to preserve the global environment, an area where it has recently
been trying to change its longtime image as an abuser of resources.
</TEXT>
