<FIRST>r i AM-France-Slaying     07-14 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Slaying,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Victims Buried; Farmer Charged With Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMTIH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUXIOL, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mourners packed a small, 17th century
church where eight coffins were lined up Friday beside mounds of
flowers at a funeral for some of the 14 people killed in a farmer's
shooting rampage.
   ``It's not fair!'' one mourner cried over and over.
   Eight of those killed in Christian Dornier's two-hour shooting
spree Wednesday, including two children, were buried in a churchyard
in the tiny village of Verne. Separate ceremonies for the six other
victims were held in five other villages _Voillans, Autechaux,
Baumes-les-Dames, Athose and Grosbois.
   Dornier was moved from a hospital in Besancon, the nearest large
city, to the Fresne prison hospital near Paris on Friday and charged
with murder and attempted murder, police said.
   He was recovering from wounds suffered in the shootout that ended
the killings, which began with the deaths of Dornier's mother and
sister. Witnesses said Dornier, 31, then drove around the area
shooting from his car window at everyone he saw.
   People from all over the region flocked to Verne, 1{ miles from
Luxiol, for the main burial ceremony conducted by Monsignor Lucien
Daloz, Roman Catholic archbishop of Besancon.
   Many eyes filled with tears as Daloz urged people to follow the
example of Jesus' mother, Mary, and find cause for consolation in
grief.
   The government was represented by Gilbert Peyronne, governor of
the Doubs department, who read a message from President Francois
Mitterrand expressing his ``sad condolences, sentiments of deep
sympathy and compassion.''
   Neighbors said Dornier had frightened them long before his
two-hour shooting spree Wednesday.
   ``Christian was a taciturn, depressed fellow,'' said his brother,
Serge, who lost his mother and newly married sister. ``He had no
friends, hardly ever talked to anyone. A few weeks ago he suddenly
got a punk haircut. He did strange things like that and we did not
pay much attention.''
   Ceremonies to mark the 200th anniversary of the French Revolution
on Friday were canceled throughout the area.
   Mourners filled the 17th century church and spilled into the
square below where they followed the ceremony over loudspeakers.
Cars were parked for a mile on both sides of the narrow roads
leading into Verne.
   Among mourners was Luxiol Mayor Roger Clausse, who said Dornier
``was not always normal and coherent, but he had not committed any
crimes and I had no basis to have him interned.''
   Clausse's son, Joel, also was there. Joel fired at Dornier early
during the shooting spree, injuring him in the neck, but could not
prevent the farmer killing his 5-year-old cousin, Pauline.
   Dornier's father, Georges, 63, was recovering in the Besancon
hospital following an operation for injuries he suffered in his
son's shooting spree.
</TEXT>
