<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1545EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FactoryUse     07-14 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Factory Use,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Factory Operating, Industrial Production Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both the factory operating rate and industrial
production fell last month, the government said Friday, providing
more evidence of a slowing economy caused by anti-inflation measures.
   The Federal Reserve said the June operating rate declined to 83.5
percent, a 0.3 percentage point drop from May. The rate was 84.1
percent in April and hit a 10-year high of 84.3 percent in December.
   The Fed also said industrial production was off 0.2 percent last
month, with its industrial production index standing at 141.1
percent of its 1977 base, down from May's 141.4 percent. It was the
first decline since it fell 0.2 percent in February, which had been
the first drop in a year.
   ``It's really related to the consumer pulling back on autos and
other durable goods that go with housing,'' said economist David
Jones of Aubrey G. Lanston &amp; Co. in New York. ``It was that high
interest rate environment that was really the major source of the
weakness.''
   Until recently, the Fed has been pushing up interest rates in an
attempt to cool inflationary pressures without slowing economic
growth so much that the economy slides into a recession.
   Jerry Jasinowski, chief economist for the National Association of
Manufacturers, said Friday's reports ``are not indications of an
emerging slide into recession.''
   ``Rather, they should be viewed as the temporary softenss that is
likely to be associated with a soft-landing scenario for the
economy,'' he said.
   Analysts also saw the decline in the factory operating rate as
further lessening of inflationary pressures. The closer that
industry gets to full operating capacity, the greater difficulty it
has producing enough to meet demand, leading to shortages and price
increases.
   ``The decline in capacity utilization _ which reflects increased
capital investment as well as slower output growth _ provides
additional confirmation that contrary to previous fears, the economy
is not in danger of capacity shortages,'' Jasinowski said.
   Robert G. Dederick of Northern Trust Co. in Chicago said
operating rates for iron, steel, paper and industrial chemicals are
down.
   ``These are the industries that were so strong earlier and where
a lot of the inflation was occurring,'' he said.
   The manufacturing plant operating rate fell 0.3 percentage point
to 83.8 percent, down from May's 84.1 percent. Prior to April, the
rate had declined since it peaked at 84.7 percent in January.
   The rate at factories producing durable goods, big-ticket items
expected to last more than three years, fell 0.3 percentage point
from 82.7 percent in May. This reflected in large part a reduction
in the production of cars.
   The rate at factories producing non-durable goods dropped to 85.8
percent, compared with May's 86.0 percent.
   Production remained flat at manufacturing plants making both
durable and non-durable goods.
   Output at mines and oil wells fell 1.1 percent after a revised
0.3 percent decline in May. Production at utilities dropped 1.3
percent in June after a 0.2 percent drop in May.
   Jasinowski said output of energy materials should increase when
coal strikes are settled. More than 30,000 coal miners have been on
strike for over a month in Appalachia and the Midwest.
   Jasinowski also said warmer weather demands for electric power
would result in increased utility production this summer.
   Last month's factory operating rate was up from 83 percent a year
earlier. The industrial production index was 3.4 percent higher than
a year ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890714-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1546EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-EmbarassingInitials     07-14 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Embarassing Initials,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>School With Initials PMS Considering Change, At Least For Uniforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENDLETON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials are considering changing the
name of Pendleton Middle School or at least removing its initials
from athletic uniforms to avoid embarassment for its girls' teams.
   PMS also is the acronym for pre-menstrual syndrome, a condition
that can cause physical and emotional distress in some women for a
few days before their menstrual periods. Sports page headlines such
as ``PMS Sweeps Alex'' have prompted kidding on radio stations. Alex
is short of Alexandria, a nearby community.
   At a meeting last week of the South Madison Community School
Corp. board, secretary Arthur Eversole said girls on the athletic
teams have become the target of jokes and jeers.
   ``Our girls came out with PMS on their shirts,'' he said.
   Eversole suggested the school name be changed to Pendleton Junior
High School _ PJHS. Board member Albert Stewart suggest South
Madison Middle School, or SMMS.
   However, there is no consensus on the board for the change.
   ``What's wrong with the name?'' asked board member Sue Lineberry.
   ``It has been Pendleton Middle School for years,'' added Mark
Matlock.
   Board President Paul Wilson said the motion was tabled last week
and will be taken up again at an Aug. 7 session, after board members
have had time to poll their constituents.
</TEXT>
