<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1537EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     07-14 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Willie? Or won't he?''
   The question is going public on an Atlanta billboard featuring
Willie B., Zoo Atlanta's 31-year-old male gorilla who is being
introduced to female companionship for the first time in the hopes
that a baby gorilla will result.
   Capitalizing on public interest in Willie's love life, the zoo
put up the first gorilla billboard this week. A second will read:
``Willie: Will he?''
   Pictures of Willie B., long a zoo favorite, and his two female
companions grace both billboards.
   Willie B. was isolated in a cage from his capture as an infant
until about a year ago. He was introduced recently to two females,
but experts say a lifetime of isolation may have left Willie without
the social skills needed to mate.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assemblyman Thomas Foy wants the package of
5,000 postage stamps issued to him for constituent mail returned to
sender because they bear the name of North Dakota.
   Last year, the Legislature gave Foy stamps with New Hampshire on
them, and he had to trade them in to his local postmaster for a
series depicting New Jersey.
   ``Enough is enough,'' Foy said in damanding a new package.
   Each year each state lawmaker gets 5,000 25-cent stamps to sent
letters out to the voters. But Foy says the commemorative stamps
that happen to commemorate some other state make him look silly.
   ``I am proud to say I serve in the state Legislature of New
Jersey,'' said Foy, D-Burlington. ``But how can I or any other
legislator be very convincing when the mail sent to constituents has
a New Hampshire or North Dakota stamp on it?''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONG BRANCH, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It all started with a broken shoelace.
   As part of a promotion drive, a disc jockey at radio station WZVU
asked listeners for suggestions about what to do with the lace left
over after he bought a new pair.
   A United Way official offered to trade a picture of New York Mets
coach Bill Robinson for the extra lace, and the promotion took off,
said station spokesman Gary Spurgeon.
   The Robinson picture was traded for a $25 restaurant gift
certificate, which was traded for $60 worth of dry cleaning, which
went for a free pool cleaning.
   Then the heavy hitters joined in.
   Traded in turn were two New York Giants tickets, a custom jungle
gym set, two trips to day camp, a house painting, a salt-water
aquarium, two passes to a fitness center and a living room set,
which was traded for a whirlpool bath.
   The owner of a computer software and consulting company then gave
$3,000 in equipment to WZVU for the whirlpool.
   ``We had no idea how far it would go,'' Spurgeon said. ``We were
hoping for a vehicle.''
   They got it.
   A Ford dealer traded an auto, which the station planned to
auction to raise money for the United Way.
</TEXT>
