<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1520EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-KGB     07-14 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-KGB,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>KGB Chief Confirmed, But Told to Stop Spying on Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet lawmakers voted overwhelmingly Friday to let
the KGB chief keep his job, but they told him to stop spying on
ordinary citizens and laughed in disbelief when he insisted the
agency doesn't tap telephones.
   It was the first time a KGB chief had stood up in public to
justify the actions of the secretive intelligence agency, which is
blamed for killing millions during Josef Stalin's rule.
   Political reforms gave the Supreme Soviet the power to reject
Cabinet-level appointees, and the official Tass news agency quoted
KGB chief Vladimir Kryuchkov as saying Thursday's questioning was
the most difficult examination of his life.
   But in the end, only six of the 542 deputies in the Supreme
Soviet voted against his confirmation. Twenty-six deputies abstained.
   Kryuchkov has been KGB chairman since last year and was deputy
chairman for 10 years before that.
   Deputies submitted written questions, and Kryuchkov read them
himself, reducing the stinging tone.
   ``By what right do you tap people's telephones?'' asked one
legislator.
   Derisive snorts of laughter greeted Kryuchkov's answer that the
KGB does not bug telephones of Soviet citizens. Maverick Communist
Boris Yeltsin told Western reporters during a break he did not
believe it.
   Kryuchkov said the KGB, which performs both domestic and foreign
security functions, ``strictly follows Soviet laws'' and has only a
few ``helpers'' who inform on neighbors and colleagues. He said 30
Western spies have been captured in the last three years.
   Yeltsin said in a speech later that there were agents in every
Soviet institution, doing great moral damage with their snooping.
But he said that during the 10 years he was Communist Party chief in
the city of Sverdlovsk, the agents ``never caught a single spy.''
   Marju Lauristin, a professor and reform leader from Estonia, told
deputies that many students have told her they were offered money
within the past year to inform on other students and teachers.
   The balding, spectacled Kryuchkov responded to questions at
rapid-fire speed but provided few real answers.
   He refused to reveal the KGB's budget despite repeated inquiries
but said it would be published soon.
   He also refused to say how many employees the KGB has, but he
said its border guard contingent alone numbers 200,000.
   Kryuchkov also said the KGB does not maintain dossiers on any
dissidents except those who present a threat to the state.
   He did disclose that he was personally involved in starting the
controversial investigation of a pair of popular prosecutors, who
claim they ran into trouble when their investigation of corruption
reached into the ruling Politburo.
   Kryuchkov said he thought of the prosecutors _ Telman Gdlyan and
Nikolai Ivanov _ as ``legends'' when he became KGB chairman but that
within a week, his staff suggested they were guilty of coercing
confessions. Kryuchkov said he alerted the chief prosecutor and they
found substance to the allegations.
   Kryuchkov also admitted the KGB should have done a better job
dealing with recent ethnic rioting in the republic of Uzbekistan,
where about 100 people died. He held out the possibility the KGB
could join Interpol, the international police network in the West.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev chaired the session and tried to
cut off debate several times, but the deputies refused. Gorbachev
joined the discussion only once, to agree that the new KGB building
in the city of Ufa was too grandiose. Gorbachev said that when he
saw the imposing edifice, he suggested the local KGB move back to
its old quarters.
   Kryuchkov later said that secrecy must exist.
   ``If we tell everything about what we are doing, then we will
probably weaken ourselves and strengthen those whom we must _
unfortunately from time to time _ try to counter,'' he told the
evening TV news program ``Vremya.''
   ``I think in this matter, my colleagues from the United States
and other countries probably agree with me,'' he said.
</TEXT>
