<DOCNO> AP890714-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1601EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Poland-Convent 3rdLd-Writethru a0680 07-14 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Convent, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0680,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Led By U.S. Rabbi Expelled From Auschwitz Convent</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Rabbi Jacob...' to CORRECT Weiss' first name
to Avraham.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSWIECIM, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American rabbi and six students today
occupied a Roman Catholic monastery on the edge of Auschwitz to
demand its nuns leave, but men working at the convent beat the
protesters and dragged them out.
   About 20 people including uniformed and plainclothes police
watched as the workers came out of the convent and asaulted the
protesters, who called the convent a ``desecration'' of the Jews
killed at the Nazi concentration camp.
   Rabbi Avraham Weiss of the Hebrew Institute of New York said his
group suffered bruises, scrapes, bleeding noses and lips. Their
signs were destroyed, their clothes were torn, and they were forced
to leave the convent grounds.
   Weiss said that the nuns watched from the window of the convent
and did not move to stop the workers.
   ``It's extraordinary that 50 years later, something like this
could happen,'' said Weiss. ``I demand an apology from these nuns.''
   The incident occurred five hours after the protesters climbed a
seven-foot wrought-iron fence and occupied the monastery. The
facility is located in a former Nazi warehouse on the perimeter of
the camp where 4 million people died from 1940 to 1945, an estimated
2.5 million of them Jews.
   When he occupied the monastery, Weiss said the group would stay
until the end of the Sabbath, Saturday night.
   It was the second time the workers confronted Weiss and the
students.
   Earlier today, workers on the second floor of the convent doused
the protesters with water, jeered and told the men to leave.
   The workers began manhandling the protesters and trying to expel
them, but the workers returned to the convent when police officers
outside the convent gate shouted at them to stop.
   It was not clear why the police did nothing the second time the
workers attacked the protesters, who wore yarmulkes, draped prayer
shawls over their shoulders and held lighted candles.
   ``How dare you throw water at a rabbi or any Jew here at
Auschwitz! Shame, shame, shame on you!'' Weiss shouted at the
workers.
   He spoke English, but the workers and nuns spoke only Polish.
   ``I saw when they (workers) came to us. I saw the vengeance in
their eyes. We want our dead respected,'' Weiss said.
   The protest brought out strong emotions of hurt, anger and hatred
among several dozen Poles who passed by the convent during the day
and began to argue with the group.
   ``This is our Poland. What are you doing here?'' one middle-aged
woman said to the group.
   ``They (the group) should think about Palestinian Arabs,'' said
another man, Piotr Wron. ``It's a kind of rape because the sisters
are innocent.''.
   Weiss tried to talk to the passersby but he couldn't speak their
language.
   The cloister was founded in 1984 in a former Nazi storehouse on
the perimeter of the former death camp. The lawn, with a 23-foot
wooden cross in the middle, is a former gravel pit where political
prisoners were gunned down by Nazi executioners in 1940 and 1941.
   A 1987 Geneva declaration, signed by 18 Roman Catholic and Jewish
leaders, called for the transfer of the 14 Barefoot Carmelite nuns
to an interfaith prayer and education center to be built at an
undetermined site farther from the camp.
   The international controversy surrounding the convent has become
even more emotional since the deadline for moving the nuns passed
Feb. 22.
   In May, 300 women from 27 countries held a peaceful protest in
front of the convent.
   ``Don't darken the memory. This convent is a desecration of the 6
million,'' said a sign held by today's protesters, referring to the
estimated 6 million Jews killed in the Holocaust.
   Weiss said his group is demanding the ``convent be removed, the
cross dismantled, and the nuns leave.'' Cardinal Macharski is
responsible for arranging the transfer of the convent.
   Weiss said that despite the church promise to move the convent by
February, it appeared the nuns were refurbishing the building and
grounds.
   ``Our patience has run out,'' said Weiss, whose Hebrew Institute
is in Riverdale in the Bronx.
   ``We're here to stay,'' said Glenn Richter, one of Weiss'
students.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
