<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1605EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Kadar     07-14 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kadar,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarians Pay Final Tribute to Former Communist Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Janos Kadar, who led the Communist Party
for 32 years until losing power to a new generation of reformers,
was buried Friday and praised as an early advocate of change.
   Thousands of people attended the somber state ceremony, which
culminated two days of emotional tribute to the 77-year-old leader
who died July 6, 14 months after his ouster.
   ``His great merit was to become a reformer in an age of
rigidity,'' said President Bruno F. Straub, referring to Kadar's
cautious support of economic reforms in the late 1960s and early
1970s.
   Party chairman Rezsoe Nyers, the architect of pioneering economic
reforms in the late 1960s, said Kadar's name ``has become
inseparable from the Hungarian cause and international progress.''
   Neither speaker alluded to the criticism of Kadar that followed
his ouster as party leader in May 1988.
   Thousands of Hungarians lined the streets as the black Mercedes
hearst carrying Kadar's body slowly made its way from the Central
Committee building in downtown Budapest to Kerepesi Cemetery, where
top-level communist officials are traditionally interred.
   Kadar's rule began amid the bloodshed of the 1956 anti-Stalinist
revolt as Soviet troops and tanks entered Budapest to quell the
uprising. It ended 32 years later, when party leaders increasingly
viewed him as an obstacle to change.
   Kadar's body lay in state for two days in the gallery of the
party's Central Committee building, and officials said more than
60,000 people had come to pay their respects.
   ``These people were not just saying goodbye,'' deputy party
spokesman Emil Kimmel said. ``They came to express their thanks for
the last 30 years.''
   Karoly Grosz, who replaced Kadar as party general secretary in
the changes that swept reformers into top party ranks, said Kadar's
death ``closed a major era of our history.''
   ``We pay our respects in a worthwhile manner if we sincerely and
objectively face ... the lessons of the age marked by his name,''
Grosz said in a eulogy at Central Committee headquarters.
   Hungarian TV carried live coverage of the funeral.
   Kadar was stigmatized for helping the Soviets crush the 1956
revolt and blamed for economic stagnation after his cautious reforms
stalled in the 1970s, but many Hungarians credit him with guiding
Hungary to relative prosperity.
   ``My parents always taught me that until 1975, they had a good
life and that it was due to Kadar,'' Attila Bauer, 27, was quoted as
saying in the Hungarian daily Magyar Hirlap.
   A man in his early 30s told Hungarian TV: ``I know that he led
the country to a catastrophic situation, but I'm convinced that he
always had the best of intentions.''
   Kadar gained respect at home and abroad for his cautious economic
reforms and policy of relative tolerance of dissent.
   But as the reforms stalled and the nation's foreign debt mounted,
Kadar became increasingly at odds with younger reformers pressing
for bolder change.
   Kadar was named honorary party chairman after he lost the top
party post to Grosz, but one year later he was removed from that
post. He also was stripped of his membership in the policy-setting
Central Committee, which criticized him for mistakes during his rule.
   It was under Kadar's rule that the 1956 uprising was officially
dubbed a counterrevolution and its leader, Imre Nagy, was executed.
   The Communist Party recently re-evaluated the uprising as a
popular revolt, and Nagy was rehabilitated. His remains were
reburied in an elaborate ceremony June 16 that was attended by
hundreds of thousands of Hungarians.
   Only hours after Kadar's death, the Hungarian Supreme Court
declared Nagy innocent of all charges.
</TEXT>
