<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Israel,0160</SECOND>
<UNK>Roadside Bomb Explodes in Israel's Security Zone</UNK>
<DATELINE>HASBAYA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded Friday on a roadside in
south Lebanon, killing one militiaman of the Israeli-allied South
Lebanon Army and wounding two others, police said.
   The explosion occurred in Israel's self-declared security zone.
   Police said Israeli and SLA artillery batteries retaliated by
shelling guerrilla bases of the Iranian-backed fundamentalist
Hezbollah, or Party of God, in three villages north of the zone. Two
villagers were reported wounded.
   The targeted villages were identified as Arabsalim, Jarjou and
Kfar Rumman, all strongholds of the Hezbollah militia, a police
spokesman said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The explosion occurred in the afternoon on a road leading from
the security zone to Arabsalim.
   Israel carved out the 6- to 10-mile-wide zone as protection from
guerrilla attacks after it withdrew the bulk of its forces from
Lebanon in 1985.
   Israeli forces and the SLA patrol the zone.
