<FIRST>u i AM-BRF--Italy-Beaches 1stLd-Writethru   07-14 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Italy-Beaches, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0621,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Health Experts Say Swimming in Algae Is Safe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with later statement advising against swimming in algae.
EDITS to trim. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bathing in the slime-covered waters along Italy's
Adriatic coast poses no health risk, but it is probably best not to
swim in the algae, government health experts said Friday.
   ``The sea is dirty but it is not dangerous,'' said Professor
Alessandro Beretta Anguissola, president of the Superior Health
Council.
   The floating algae appeared along the coast last week and hotel
operators in the Friuli, Veneto, Emilia Romagna and Marche regions
say tourists are canceling reservations.
   Anguissola said tests confirmed the algae wasn't toxic and there
was no need to ban swimming. But later in the day, the council
released a document recommending against swimming in algae ``for
reasons of prudence and hygiene.''
   Anguissola reiterated the government's earlier warning against
swimming in the algae for those with open wounds or cuts.
   He said the algae has flourished in warm, still water. When it
rots, tiny gas bubbles carry the slime to the surface.
   The Federation of Italian Hotel and Tour Operators predicted that
tourist losses this summer due to the algae could total nearly $200
million.
</TEXT>
