<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1754EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mandela-ANC     07-14 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mandela-ANC,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>ANC Notes Notable Shifts in South Africa, Especially on Mandela</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa's government has made notable
shifts in policy recently, particularly concerning imprisoned black
leader Nelson Mandela, the African National Congress said Friday.
   Thabo Mbeki, foreign affairs secretary for the guerrilla
organization, said the ANC would not oppose a negotiated solution to
end race segregation in South Africa, but that it does not believe
the government is committed to peace talks.
   ``Nothing, really, of any seriousness has been said or done to
convince us that the other side has in fact opted for a political
solution of this matter,'' Mbeki said at the outlawed organization's
headquarters in Lusaka.
   He said F.W. de Klerk, designated to succeed South African
President P.W. Botha, has not addressed the main conditions the ANC
has stipulated for opening talks:
   _ The release of Mandela and all other political prisoners;
   _ The legalization of the ANC and other outlawed organizations;
   _ Ending the state of emergency;
   _ Withdrawing South African soldiers from black townships; and
   _ The return of exiles.
   Mbeki made no comment on a July 5 meeting between Mandela and
Botha, who is to retire in September. The ANC has said the meeting
had no meaning, but has been silent since Mandela issued a statement
saying he and Botha discussed peaceful development for South Africa.
   Mbeki said there were notable shifts in South African policy. He
noted the government no longer requires that Mandela formally
renounce violence before it will consider freeing him from his life
prison term.
   ``To that extent, one could talk about new thinking,'' said
Mbeki, whose father, Govan, was convicted with Mandela in 1964 for
sabotage and plotting to overthrow the white government. The elder
Mbeki was released from his life term in 1987 but is banned from
speaking in public, talking to the press or leaving his hometown
without police permission.
   Mbeki acknowledged his organization's insistence on the five
pre-conditions was not ``new thinking.''
   ``It is, though, a readiness on the part of the ANC to find such
a political solution, if the conditions are there.''
   Otherwise, he said, ``We need to continue the struggle, escalate
the pressures.
   Mbeki was due to meet Saturday with a delegation from the
anti-apartheid Democratic Party which is fighting its first South
African election campaign in September. South Africa's 28 million
black majority has no vote in national politics, which are dominated
by the 5 million white minority.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
