<DOCNO> AP890714-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1619EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-US-Israel     07-14 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Israel,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Won't Send Delegation to Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has decided against sending a U.S.
delegation to Israel to make sure that Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
remains committed to holding elections among Palestinian Arabs, the
White House announced Friday.
   The decision, relayed by presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater,
represents an easing of pressure on Israel. It was taken after
Secretary of State James A. Baker III consulted with key aides.
   ``We are not sending anyone to Israel at this time, although it
might be necessary at some later point ... to discuss the election
proposal,'' said Fitzwater, in Paris with Bush and Baker for the
economic summit meeting.
   He added, ``Baker feels we do not need to do that now.''
   The decision reverses tentative plans by Bush and Baker to send a
mid-level delegation from the State Department to Jerusalem next
week. There, the officials were to meet with Shamir about the
hard-line position taken by the prime minister and the Likud party
at a convention in Tel Aviv two weeks ago.
   Under pressure from hardliners, Shamir ruled out a Palestinian
state or relinquishing any of the territory Israel holds on the West
Bank and in Gaza. Shamir had also said that Palestinians living in
East Jerusalem would not be permitted to participate in the
elections and that balloting would begin only after violence in the
territories ceased.
   Even though Bush also is opposed to the establishment of a
Palestinian state, he was sharply critical Thursday of the stand
taken by Shamir and Likud.
   Flying here for a seven-nation economic summit, the president
said U.S. policy against new Jewish settlements on the West Bank and
in Gaza had not changed.
   ``I understand the political pressures,'' he said of the
development in Israel. ``But I can't be varying U.S. policy every
day to accommodate political change.''
   Bush said Israel was a friend of the United States ``and will
remain a friend, but I have to say what our policy is.''
   While Bush said Thursday that he would not send a high-level
emissary, State Department officials, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said mid-level U.S. officials would be dispatched.
   Among those known to be included was Dennis Ross, a key aideto
Baker who plays a leading role in U.S. policy in the Middle East.
   In Jerusalem, Yossi Ben-Aharon, a top aide to Shamir, said, ``The
Americans did not want to be seen as though they are interfering in
the internal affairs of Israel with regards to this mini-crisis.''
   The center-left Labor Party has said it may pull out of a
governing coalition with Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc over Likud's
hard-line stance.
   For his part, Shamir told U.S. members of the Israel Bonds drive
that ``if they (the United States) want to send some delegation,
some envoys, we will always welcome them.''
</TEXT>
