<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 2005EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;Ls     07-14 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Negotiators Reach Tentative Agreement on S&amp;L Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional negotiators, breaking a
procedural deadlock, tentatively agreed Friday to toughen proposed
regulations on savings and loans as part of a $157 billion taxpayer
bailout of the industry.
   Although nothing was adopted, Senate and House conferees moved
toward embracing a combination of the toughest specific capital
requirements in separate Senate and House bills to make S&amp;Ls back up
loans with more of their own money.
   The conferees are trying to meld some of the most stringent
features of both bills aimed at reforming S&amp;L abuses into one
legislative package acceptable to both houses.
   Lax laws and accounting practices that let some thrifts lend
federally insured deposits for risky and often fraudulent ventures
while risking no money of their own is widely blamed as the chief
factor behind the S&amp;L crisis, the largest financial debacle since
the Depression.
   Covering the estimated $100 billion in losses is expected to cost
each of the nation's taxpayers between $500 and $1,500 over the next
30 years.
   Differences in the way the House and Senate have approached the
S&amp;L legislation flared Thursday when the Senate offered a
comprehensive package and asked the House to counter with an
all-encompassing proposal of its own.
   ``Except for financing, we're not very far apart,'' said Sen.
Jake Garn of Utah, the ranking Republican senator in the conference.
``To go through them one-by-one, we might be here past Labor Day.''
   The chief House conferee, Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas,
balked, calling the move a ``horrendous injustice'' to an earlier
agreement to tackle one-by-one each of the hundreds of differences
between the two bills.
   But after examining a rough outline of the Senate's proposal
overnight, Gonzalez said Friday that the two sides were ``so close
on an overwhelming majority'' that the House would try to put
together a counteroffer Monday.
   ```My intention is to provide a starting point for an overall
settlement,'' he told the Senate negotiators. ``I believe this
provides the basis for us to resolve the impasse.''
   Later Friday, however, House conferees balked at Gonzalez's
suggestion to accept a Senate-proposed timetable that would make
S&amp;Ls meet the toughest of the new capital requirements immediately
upon the bill's enactment rather than in June 1990, as in the House
bill.
   ``We have to have some minimal amount of time before the
regulations are issued,'' said Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., one of
the most vehement supporters of making S&amp;L owners put more of their
own money at risk.
   As passed in its original form, the Senate bill would not have
imposed the new requirements until June 1991. That issue, like
dozens of others, remained unresolved.
   Nonetheless, Gonzalez said he was optimistic that the two sides
can iron out their major differences by Wednesday, with the possible
exception for how to raise the immediate $50 billion cost of the
bailout.
   To prevent the bailout from swelling the federal deficit,
President Bush and the Senate want to use 30-year bonds to raise the
money needed immediately to cover industry losses of federally
insured deposits.
   The House, citing potential interest cost savings of $4.5 billion
over the next three years, wants to borrow the money directly
through the Treasury, a move that would increase the annual deficits
for fiscal 1990, 1991 and 1992 by a total of $44 billion.
</TEXT>
