<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1643EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Summit-Debt     07-14 0791</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Debt,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Willing to Arrange Loan to Aid Mexico in Debt Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States, trying to knock down the last
hurdles to its new Third World debt strategy, has promised to
arrange as much as $2 billion in loans for financially strapped
Mexico, officials said Friday.
   French President Francois Mitterrand said Mexico, burdened by a
whopping $100 billion in foreign debt, urgently needs help.
   ``Mexico,'' he told French television, ``is on the edge of an
explosion because of the weight of its debt and the impossibility of
carrying the burden.''
   ``No one,'' he said, ``has an interest in this explosion taking
place, which would mean more misery for a suffering people.''
   Mexico is the test case of the Bush administration's approach for
easing the $1.3 trillion debt of poor nations. The strategy,
representing a marked shift in U.S. policy, emphasizes debt
reduction or forgiveness.
   Mexico has been holding intense negotiations with private banks
to reach an accord to show off at the annual economic summit of the
world's seven big democracies, which got under way Friday.
   But Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady said it was unclear when
Mexico and private bankers would wind up their bargaining, which
began in mid-April.
   ``Whether or not the negotiations will proceed far enough to have
closure by this weekend, we don't know. We didn't set any
deadlines,'' he told a news conference. ``But they're in good
shape.''
   The summit, he said, ``would be a suitable event to have that
arrangement announced while we were here.''
   White House Chief of Staff John Sununu emphasized earlier,
however, that ``the quality of the solution is more important that
the timetable.''
   The unrelieved debt problem was high on the summit agenda of
President Bush and the leaders of Britain, Canada, France, West
Germany, Italy and Japan. They were expected to discuss it in detail
Saturday.
   The summit began at the same time that France was marking the
200th anniversary of its revolution, a celebration that has
attracted some three-dozen leaders of the world's richest and
poorest nations. The poor have taken the opportunity to lobby their
wealthier counterparts for help.
   But it was highly unlikely the rich democracies would respond
with any dramatic proposal.
   Nigel Lawson, Britain's chancellor of the exchequer, said, ``What
is important is we have agreed (on) this extension of the debt
strategy,'' referring to the Brady plan.
   ``And the commerical banks need to be absolutely clear there is
no new initiative coming forward,'' he said. ``That is the position,
and it is up to them to negotiate a debt-reduction agreement with
the debtor countries, starting with Mexico.''
   Bush held a hastily arranged meeting Friday morning with Mexican
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari to discuss the debt issues.
Salinas de Gortari met earlier in the week with German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl and Japanese Prime Minister Sousuke Uno to press his
case.
   White House officials confirmed reports that the United States
was willing to arrange a $1 billion to $2 billion bridge loan to
help Mexico meet its financial obligations until a final debt deal
is in place.
   ``We would be willing to do this with other countries if Mexico
and the their banks can get together,'' Brady said. ``We have
indications that other (industrialized nations) would be willing to
join as well.''
   Mexico has received similar loans from the United States in the
past to help it close the gap between its financial obligations and
the amount of money left in its coffers. A bridge loan helps sweeten
a deal because it ensures bankers the debtor nation will continue
making interest payments.
   Mexico, which is believed to be running low on foreign reserves,
is the developing world's second largest debtor after Brazil. Mexico
owes private lenders $54 billion, with about $15 billion due
American banks.
   In its negotiations with a 15-member bank panel, Mexico has
pressed for sharp cuts in both its overall debt and its annual
interest fees, which run about $10 billion a year. By reducing those
charges, the Mexican government would have more money left from
foreign earnings to pump into its flat economy.
   Mexico wants to cut its annual interest fees from 6 percent of
its gross domestic product, the total value of a nation's economic
output, to 2 percent.
   It went into the talks demanding a 55 percent discount on a
portion of its $54 billion private debt. Bankers countered with a 22
percent discount. The two sides, sources said, have tentatively
centered on a 35 percent cut.
   To do that, negotiators are discussing a variety of options,
including swapping old debt for new, guaranteed bonds, and putting
up new loans to dilute the debt concentration.
</TEXT>
