<FIRST>u a AM-OilSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0705 07-14 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0705,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greek Tanker Captain Involved In Oil Spill Indicted In Rhode Island</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf `The attorney general...' to CORRECT spelling
of Georgudis, ADDS six grafs after 10th, `Georgudis refused...' to include
background on charges, prior testimony on spill, costs of cleanup. No pickup.
</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The captain of a Greek tanker who already
faced federal pollution charges after the ship ran aground off
Newport, spilling thousands of gallons of oil, on Friday was
indicted on two state felony counts.
   Iakovos Georgudis, 43, of Athens was charged with failure to have
a harbor pilot on board the World Prodigy at the time of the June 23
spill and with polluting the coastal waters, Attorney General James
E. O'Neil said.
   The Coast Guard says about 300,000 gallons of toxic No. 2 heating
oil spilled into Rhode Island Sound at the entrance to Narragansett
Bay. Most of the oil, which was lighter than the crude oil that has
fouled Alaska waters since March, has now been cleaned up or
dissipated.
   The failure to have a pilot on board carries a potential penalty
of $10,000 and one year in jail, O'Neil said. The pollution count
carries up to 30 days in jail and a $10,000 fine. O'Neil, however,
indicated that Georgudis, 43, was unlikely to spend time in jail,
even if convicted.
   ``What we're looking at here are fines right now,'' O'Neil said.
   Georgudis, who is in New York City, where the ship is being
repaired, likely will surrender to Rhode Island authorities within
the next week to 10 days for arraignment, O'Neil said.
   The attorney general said Georgudis' attorney, Michael DiBiase,
had indicated the captain would cooperate.
   Georgudis also faces federal counts of violating the Clean Water
Act and the Refuse Act, which prohibit dumping of pollutants. He has
admitted making a mistake and steering the ship in the wrong
direction onto the reef, according to Gov. Edward D. DiPrete and
Coast Guard officials who have interviewed him.
   A statewide grand jury began meeting in the week after the
accident and the indictments were expected.
   Georgudis refused to testify in front of the grand jury or a
Coast Guard inquiry into the grounding, citing his right not to be
forced to incriminate himself.
   The indictment charges that Georgudis ran the World Prodigy onto
the rocks through ``gross negligence.''
   The ship's helmsman testified during the Coast Guard inquiry that
he spotted a red buoy warning of the reef on the left side of the
ship, when it should have been on the right, as the World Prodigy
approached the harbor but he did not tell the captain.
   The harbor pilot who was supposed to meet the tanker said he
tried to warn it away from the rocks three times but saw no response.
   O'Neil said most of his office's efforts were going to recovering
the costs of the spill from the ship's owner, Ballard Shiopping Co.
The Coast Guard has estimated the costs at almost $2 million, but
O'Neil said the state costs were not fully tallied.
   The attorney general said Ballard and its insurance company so
far had cooperated in the assessment of damages.
   ``We're fortunate they're insured. We're fortunate they have an
owner who seems to have some social conscience,'' O'Neil said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
