<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Americans 1stLd-Writethru a0660 07-14 0857</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Americans, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0660,0877</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian-Americans Caught in Israeli Judicial System</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS number of Israelis killed to 35 in 8th graf `At least';
in 17th graf, `Cases are' the name Suzane is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KFAR AKUB, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ola Fareh Awad is among
thousands of Palestinian teen-agers enmeshed in the Israeli judicial
system because of stone-throwing, and could be sent to prison for 20
years.
   Miss Awad, a 14-year-old American citizen who lives in this
Palestinian village north of Jerusalem, is accused along with three
friends of ``acting with intention to endanger public life'' by
throwing rocks at an intercity bus in December.
   She was 13 at the time, and says they were innocent bystanders.
   ``We were walking home from school and saw the bus stop,'' she
said in an interview. ``Jewish people got out and started shooting
in the air. We were scared and ran away, but they caught us and hit
us and said we threw the stones.''
   Uzi Hasson, the Israeli chief prosecutor, said no one was hurt
but the glass in the rear door of the bus was broken and the
passengers were endangered.
   ``We are pursuing the case because we take stone-throwing very
seriously,'' he said. ``I don't wish anybody to be in such an
attack. You are helpless. If you're driving, it can be very
dangerous.''
   More than 1,500 Israeli soldiers and civilians have been injured,
nearly all by stones, since the Palestinian uprising in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip began more than 19 months ago.
   At least 560 Palestinians and 35 Israelis have been killed,
mainly by gunfire or means other than stones, and more than 8,000
Palestinians have been wounded.
   Hasson said conviction on the charge against the girls carries a
maximum of 20 years, but the average jail sentence has been about 15
months.
   Jawad Boulos, Miss Awad's lawyer, said the case could drag on for
months because of overloaded court calendars.
   ``I think this is symptomatic of the insanity of the Israeli
judicial system,'' he said. ``They are trying to teach the girls a
lesson and deter them and others from having a part in the uprising.
This isn't the way to influence people.''
   Miss Awad said interrogators slapped her and threatened to put
her in jail if she refused to confess. Before being sent home, she
and her mother, Jamileh, had to sign a statement agreeing to an
automatic three-month prison sentence if Ola was detained for
another alleged offense.
   Apparently because she was only 13 at the time her arrest,
authorities allowed Miss Awad to return to her ninth grade class at
the Holy Rosary School. Her Palestinian companions, aged 15 and 16,
were held for several months in a makeshift detention center in a
convent, then put under house arrest.
   Ola Awad never lived in the United States, but her father worked
in Los Angeles until his death in 1983. She is among 16 holders of
American passports who have been caught up in the judicial system
since the uprising began.
   According to the army, nearly 8,600 Palestinians from the West
Bank and Gaza Strip are in detention in cases related to the
uprising, most of them involving stone-throwing.
   About 7,000 Palestinian-Americans are among the 1 million Arabs
in the West Bank, U.S. officials estimate. About 100 holders of U.S.
passports are among the Gaza Strip's 700,000 residents.
   The Americans in detention include Mansour Abed al Samad, 16,
born in Puerto Rico. He was sentenced in June to 10 months in jail
after conviction on charges of erecting road barriers.
   Cases are pending against Usama Nazmi, 17, formerly of Milwaukee,
Wis., for allegedly throwing stones at soldiers, and Suzane Abu
Nijmeh, 16, formerly of Cicero, Ill., accused of participating in an
anti-Israeli demonstration.
   Palestinian-Americans do not get special treatment.
   Catherine Barry, a consulate officer, said American officials
visit the detainees but do not intervene in judicial proceedings.
   ``Our primary interest is seeing that they are treated humanely
and equitably,'' she said. ``We have to respect the legal systems.''
   The Jerusalem branch of the American-Arab Anti-Discrimination
Committee believes this is not enough, and said in a statement:
``Lack of effective action by the U.S. government will invite
further Israeli violations of the rights of American nationals of
Palestinian origin.''
   It has taken up the case of Jaafar Hamayel, 25, a
Palestinian-American who was detained without charge May 28 and is
being interrogated in an Israeli prison on suspicion of anti-Israeli
activities.
   Hamayel, an accounting student at the InterAmerican University of
Puerto Rico, returned to his village of Kufr Malik in April to renew
his identity card. He must have the card, issued by Israel, to
return to the West Bank.
   His lawyer, Jonathan Kuttab, accused government interrogators of
depriving Hamayel of food and sleep, forcing him to stand with a
sack over his head, and handcuffing him in uncomfortable positions.
   ``I don't know of any country in the world where a U.S. citizen
can be held for so long and interrogated so roughly without any
charges,'' Kuttab said.
</TEXT>
