<FIRST>r a AM-PrincipalFired     07-14 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Principal Fired,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Principal Sacrifices Job For Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A principal who told officials that
students needed teachers more than they needed him at his
financially pressed elementary school of 200 was out of a job Friday.
   Some board members had tears in their eyes Thursday night when
they voted unanimously to lay off Principal Norman Najimy. His
teachers wept openly.
   ``This was the shortest and saddest meeting in our history,''
said board member Donna Slowick.
   ``No one seemed to believe it would really happen, but me, ''
Najimy, a teacher for 37 years, said by telephone Friday. ``But with
the governor's announcement of further state aid cuts, there was no
way.''
   Hours before the school committee met, Gov. Michael Dukakis
announced he was vetoing $491 million in state spending, including
cuts in community and education aid, because of the state's own
fiscal problems.
   ``He is a public servant, a teacher, who stood up to be counted
and put his own personal welfare behind what is best for the kids,''
said Fred Williams, deputy state education commissioner. ``Our
hearts go out to the parents, kids, teachers and the school
committee, who had to make a very difficult decision.''
   ``I didn't want to go. I still have one child in college,'' said
Najimy, as friends and distraught parents rallied around him and
several school superintendents called with job offers. ``But what
would you do with the children without teachers?''
   Maintaining the children needed the teachers more, Najimy
suggested last month that Richmond could save about $40,000 by
firing him and paying a teacher an extra $3,000 to run the school.
   ``Building faculty is the hardest thing to do,'' he said at the
time. ``If we lose our teachers, we will never get them back.''
   ``The irony is we had built an award-winning school,'' Najimy
said. Last year, the school was cited by the Massachusetts
Organization for School Improvement and the state Education
Department. Najimy was named a fellow of the Commonwealth Leadership
Academy and commissioned by the education department to conduct a
study of the future of education.
   ``Educators in several states are using my monograph to plan
their programs for the 1990s,'' Najimy said. ``And here I am looking
for a job.''
   A professional Shakespearian company also spent 12 weeks in
residence at the school under a state Arts Council grant. A
student-built nature trail, illustrated with the children's own
poetry, was created with the help of a poet and a master
calligrapher, who brought their art into the classrooms.
   ``I think the thing that makes me the angriest is the hypocrisy
of saying that education is the key to our future at the same time
we are unwilling to give the children the resources to cope with a
legacy of $2 trillion in debt, a polluted environment and other
social problems,'' Najimy said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
