<FIRST>u w AM-SocialSecurity-King     07-14 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Social Security-King,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Social Security Commissioner Nominated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Friday nominated Gwendolyn S.
King, a former aide to Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., to head the Social
Security Administration.
   King, currently an executive with a Washington consulting firm,
had no comment on the announcement except to say that she was
``delighted'' the president had selected her.
   Bush also announced that he will nominate Allan B. Clark Sr. to
be an assistant secretary of veterans affairs. He is now head of a
real estate firm in Austin, Tex.
   The White House announced the nominations from Paris, where Bush
is attending a seven-nation economic summit.
   If confirmed by the Senate, King would succeed Dorcas Hardy as
Social Security commissioner. Hardy, who had lobbied to keep the
job, resigned last month.
   King was senior legislative assistant to Heinz and headed
Pennsylvania's Washington office for Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh when he was governor. She later served under President
Reagan as deputy assistant for intergovernmental affairs.
   She is currently an executive vice president of the Washington
government relations firm of Gogol &amp; Associates.
   King would take over an agency that currently spends some $283
billion a year, only $10 billion or so less than the Defense
Department, the government's biggest spender. The Social Security
Administraion saw its workforce cut about 20 percent during the
Reagan administration, from about 80,000 employees to about 65,000.
   The agency has come under fire from labor and some Democrats in
Congress who say the agency's new services, including a toll-free
telephone information number, have been implemented poorly, and its
service to the public has been deteriorating.
   Hardy, however, says that during her three years she modernized
Social Security's massive computer operations, made information
easier to get and started providing to all workers Social Security
benefit estimates upon request.
   Hardy will leave July 31. She plans to host a weekly syndicated
television program about personal finances.
</TEXT>
