<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 2055EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-ForeignTakeovers     07-14 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Foreign Takeovers,325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rules Proposed for Security Ban on Foreign Takeovers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Proposed rules that would allow President Bush
to plead national security and block takeover of a U.S. firm by
foreigners were published for public comment Friday by the Treasury
Department.
   Sen. James Exon, D-Neb., and Rep. James J. Florio, D-N.J., who
were responsible for parts of the law, praised the proposed
regulations published in the Federal Register. Comments may be
submitted by Sept. 12, although the Treasury said later comments
will be considered if possible.
   The Trade Act, signed by former President Reagan last August,
provides authority for the rules that would allow the president to
block a merger if he has credible evidence that the foreign interest
taking control might act to hurt U.S. security. If he decides on an
investigation, he gets 30 days to begin it, 45 days to complete it
and another 15 days to announce it.
   Florio said the Treasury has interpreted the law broadly to make
sure that it covers different ways that a foreign firm could take
over an American one: a joint venture, buying up the assets, and
defaults on loans as well as just buying a majority interest.
   ``In my view, all methods by which foreign control may be
accomplished must be covered, including proxy solicitations which
are certainly as viable a means of establishing control as equity
ownership,'' he added in a statement.
   A proxy authorizes a person to cast the vote of stock owned by
someone else. If an acquiring company gets enough proxies, it can
take over a firm without paying a premium price for the stock.
   ``I am very pleased with action taken by the secretary of the
Treasury,'' Exon told the Assocated Press in an interview. ``The
regulations carry out the commitment he made to us.''
   Nicholas F. Brady is secretary of the Treasury.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890714-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 2056EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SecretService     07-14 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Secret Service,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secret Service Agent on Administrative Leave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Secret Service officer who admitted a
lobbyist and his party to the White House for a private, late-night
tour is on administrative leave as the agency investigates possible
procedural violations, a spokeswoman said Friday.
   Jane Vezeris said the Secret Service is pursuing its internal
investigation into the activities of Officer Reginald deGueldre
``very aggressively,'' and finds the allegations that deGueldre may
have accepted gifts from the lobbyist ``very concerning.''
   DeGueldre, who has acknowledged giving lobbyist Craig J. Spence a
White House tour on July 3, 1988, around 11 p.m., was placed on
administrative leave with pay recently, but Vezeris said she did not
know the date.
   Spence, who was a registered foreign agent for Japan until 1987,
has been linked by The Washington Times to a homosexual prostitution
ring that is under investigation by U.S. Attorney Jay Stephens. The
prosecutor said he is examining possible credit card fraud in the
ring, which was broken up in February.
   The newspaper said it has obtained copies of vouchers indicating
Spence was a customer.
   Vezeris said the agency's internal probe was taking ``longer that
usual'' because agents did not want to interfere with Stephens'
criminal investigation.
   The Times reported that deGueldre organized at least four private
White House tours for Spence, including one on which two male
prostitutes were in the party.
   DeGueldre also told another Secret Service officer that he
snatched china from the White House, and he told the Times he
accepted an $8,000 gold Rolex watch from Spence.
   Vezeris said the Secret Service doesn't view a private tour as a
``breach of security'' because White House officials and uniformed
officers are permitted to give friends and relatives a peek at the
West Wing, site of the Oval Office.
   But the service wants to determine if deGueldre received
``possible favors'' in return for his hospitality, she said.
DeGueldre did not return a telephone message left on his machine
Friday.
   In an affidavit supporting a search warrant for deGueldre's house
last week, Secret Service special agent Paul Weare said deGueldre
had admitted stealing from the presidential living quarters several
pieces of china dating from the Truman presidency.
   Weare said ``deGueldre admitted ... that he gave one piece of the
china to Craig Spence, who had it prominently displayed at his home
in Washington.''
   DeGueldre has denied committing any thefts or breaking any other
laws or breaching security.
   The Times, in a story published Friday, quoted unidentified
Secret Service officers as saying another uniformed officer who
worked the midnight shift at the White House with deGueldre has been
reassigned. Vezeris said she knew nothing about a second officer.
   Meantime, Rose Zamaria, a White House official, said there has
been no change in policy regarding late night tours of the building
since a memorandum she issued in mid-June.
   In the Bush administration, White House staff members can bring
guests on private tours of the West Wing on Monday, Wednesday and
Friday between 7 p.m. and 10 p.m., after 1 p.m. on Saturday and all
day on Sunday.
</TEXT>
