<SECOND>AM-Helms-PLO,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helms Says No T alks With PLO Terrorists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., offered legislation
on Friday barring the United States from negotiating with the
Palestine Liberation Organization unless President Bush certifies
none of the PLO participants were ever terrorists involved in the
death, injury or kidnapping of an American.
   Helms said his amendment to a pending Statre Department
authorization bill was a reaction to published reports that U.S.
Ambassador Robert Pelletreau has held talks in Tunisia with Abu
Iyad, the PLO's No. 2 official.
   Helms identified Iyad as a key member of the Black September
terrorist group,which murdered a group of athletes at the 1972
Olympic Games in Munich and conducted a number of assasinations and
hijackings, including the murder of Cleo Noel, the U.S. ambassador
to Sudan, in 1973.
   ``This amendment poses a simple clear-cut question: should U.S.
officials negotiate with terrorists responsible for the deaths of
innocent Americans?'' Helms asked.
   The amendment, which will be debated next week, appears intended
at derailing the U.S.-PLO talks begun after PLO Chairman Yasser
Arafat recognized the right of Israel to exist, a condition set by
the United States.
   It was not clear what action the Senate might take or whether the
amendment stands a chance of becoming law.
   ``While the name of Abu Iyad may not be well known to our ears,
the murder of innocent people _ which he directed _ still echoes in
our memory,'' Helms said.
   ``The State Department is involved in negotiations with a man who
murdered Americans,'' Helms said.
   ``Despite Abu Iyad's histopry of crimes against Americans, the
State Department has now endowed upon him the respectibility
inherrent in serving as a negotiating partner with the United
States,'' he said. ``By so doing, it has sent a signal to other
terrorists that violence can pay.''
 
