<HEAD>Accountant Cooperates, Gets Suspended Sentence for Tax Evasion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pentagon Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An accountant who has agreed to give
evidence against his stepfather in the FBI's Pentagon procurement
fraud investigation was given a suspended sentence Friday for tax
evasion.
   Defense attorney F. Joseph Warin said that as a result of his
decision to cooperate, Kenneth F. Brooke had become estranged from
his mother, who is married to defense consultant William M. Galvin.
   Brooke, 40, was given a two-year suspended sentence, fined
$10,000 and placed on two-years' probation for the tax charge that
is unrelated to the government's ``Operation Ill Wind''
investigation of contract fraud.
   Brooke, who has agreed to cooperate with the investigation of
Galvin, could have received a maximum sentence of five years
imprisonment and a $250,000 fine.
   Warin told U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton that Brooke ``has
been required to sever family relationships by virtue of his
cooperation with the government.
   ``He has no relationship with his mother because of the decision
he made to cooperate'' with the investigation of his stepfather,
Warin said.
   Brooke, whose tax conviction related to failure to report income
from real estate deals in Richmond, Va., and Norfolk, Va., had been
employed as an accountant by Galvin, Warin said.
   Galvin has been implicated by others in a scheme to bribe former
assistant Navy secretary Melvyn R. Paisley, who also has not been
charged. Both men, who have not been charged, have denied the
allegations.
