<FIRST>r w AM-HUD-AgentSued     07-14 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Agent Sued,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Sues Texas Agent Accused of Stealing $2.5 Million</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-HUD Probe, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Housing and Urban Development
on Friday filed suit seeking to recover more than $2.5 million a
Texas woman is accused of bilking from the agency and spending on
real estate, cars and guns.
   The woman, Reba Louise Lovell, already is under federal criminal
indictment for allegedly embezzling the money she collected in her
role as a closing agent for HUD's single-family sales and
acquisitions program.
   HUD's civit suit, filed in U.S. District Court in Fort Worth,
names as defendants Ms. Lovell and her company, KenLo Inc. She is
one of 10 closing agents nationwide the agency believes bilked HUD
of about $10 million. The suit against her is the second filed by
HUD in an attempt to recover the money allegedly stolen.
   ``This is part of our ongoing and aggressive effort to recapture
money from those who have done so much harm to the taxpayer adn
those who are in need,'' HUD Secretary Jack Kemp said in a statement
announcing the suit.
   The suit alleges Ms. Lovell diverted for personal use $2.52
million in proceeds from the sale of HUD-owned properties. It
alleges she deposited the funds in personal bank accounts and used
the money to buy real estate, cars and guns. HUD asked that any
property bought with HUD money be declared government property.
   The suit was filed under a law that allows the government to seek
triple damages from fraud, meaning Ms. Lovell could be held liable
for up to $7.5 million. Her attorney did not immediately return a
telephone message seeking comment on the suit.
   Ms. Lovell, 36, of Arlington, Texas, was indicted by a federal
grand jury on June 1 and charged with 55 counts of embezzlement and
24 counts of money-laundering. At the time, prosecutors said
conviction on all counts would carry a maximum sentence of 1,030
years in prison and $25.75 million in fines. HUD suspended its
contract with her after the indictment was returned.
   The indictment said the $2.52 million was divered after Ms.
Lovell, under a contract with the government, served as a closing
agent on the sale of 55 HUD-owned properties in the Forth Worth area
between July and October of last year.
   The indictment alleges that Lovell made 24 deposits of about
$9,900 each to the former M-Bank Fort Worth to avoid federal laws
requiring banks to report transactions of $10,000 or more.
   She was released on personal recognizance after a court apperance
in the criminal case.
</TEXT>
