<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Uprising     07-14 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Uprising,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Soldiers Kill two Young Palestinians, Wound at Least 20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers fired on Palestinian
stone-throwers in the occupied territories Friday, killing two
teen-agers and wounding at least 20, Arabs and Israel radio reported.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, masked men fatally stabbed a
Palestinian suspected of collaborating with Israel, Arab journalists
reported.
   The army confined 150,000 West Bank Palestinians to their homes
in an effort to curtail violence on the second day of a major Moslem
feast.
   In southern Israel, a Jewish man was beaten to death in the town
of Gan Yavne.
   Israel radio said the elderly building contractor was slain by
two Palestinian workers to whom he owned money. The killing raised
anti-Arab emotions in the town, and news reports said residents
gathered in the streets to demand that Palestinian workers be banned
from Gan Yavne.
   Soldiers shot the two Palestinians to death in the Gaza Strip
refugee camps of Khan Yunis and Jabaliya, according to Israel radio
and Arab hospital officials. The victims were identified as Nasser
Soubhi Mussa, 18, of Khan Yunis and Shaher Abu Hayeh, 15, of
Jabaliya, both shot in the chest.
   At least 20 Palestinians were reported wounded in stone-throwing
confrontations with soldiers, most of them in Gaza refugee camps,
Palestinian journalists reported.
   Friday's deaths brought to 563 the number of Palestinians killed
in the 19-month-old uprising against Israeli rule in the West Bank
and Gaza. Most have been shot to death by soldiers, but more than 70
were killed as alleged collaborators. Thirty-five Israelis have been
slain.
   Arab reports said masked Palestinian activists killed Mahmoud
Amasi, 26, in the Gaza Strip town of Rafah. Amasi was a hashish
dealer suspected of collaborating with Israeli security forces, the
reports said.
   The army confirmed the death and said police were investigating.
   Curfews were reported in Nablus, the West Bank's largest city;
the Tulkarem refugee camp, and nearby villages. Soldiers also
blocked some roads from the West Bank to Jerusalem.
   Moslems are observing Eid al-Adha, a four-day feast at the close
of the annual pilgrimage to Mecca.
   In south Lebanon, a member of Israel's surrogate militia was
killed and two were wounded by a mine that exploded near Jezzine,
north of the Israeli ``security zone,'' the army said.
   The predominantly Christian militia, called the South Lebanon
Army, helps Israel patrol the zone, which ranges in depth from 6 to
10 miles along the border.
</TEXT>
