<FIRST>r w AM-Senate-China 1stLd-Writethru a0731 07-14 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-China, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0731,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Urges Economic Sanctions Against China</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   EDs: INSERTS new 5th-7th grafs, bgng, Reacting to, etc., to insert
with White House reaction from Paris
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted 81-10 on Friday to impose
economic sanctions against China and to urge President Bush to take
even harshar measures.
   The legislation was offered by Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell of Maine ``to express to the government of China the
concern which the American people feel about the continuing
prosecution of Chinese students and workers who support the
pro-democracy movement,'' Mitchell said.
   It calls on Bush to make sure the leaders of China understand
``that until they recognize the Chinese people's legitimate desire
for democracy, human rights and justice, that relations between our
two countries will remain strained.''
   The sanctions amendment was attached to pending legislation
authorizing $4.66 billion for the State Department and allied
agencies during the fiscal year beginning next Oct. 1.
   Reacting to the Senate action, White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater told reporters in Paris, ``We feel that the United States
has imposed sanctions that are meaningful and that adequately convey
our sense of condemnation of the events that occurred in China. We
also believe that we need to be mindful of long-term relationships
with that country as we move forward.''
   He said there is a ``fair degree of unanimity'' among the United
States' summit partners on the issue.
   He said the administration would consider the legislation ``but
generally speaking, we think we have taken the right course, that
that has been recognized by other nations of the world. We feel it's
also supported and recognized by the American public.''
   Mitchell noted that while the amendment requires the president to
suspend certain trade programs, it also has a provision which
``gives him the flexibility to cease any suspension or termination
... if he finds it in the security interest of the United States to
do so.''
   The measure adopts several sanctions adopted earlier by the House.
   These include six-month suspensions of trade insurance by the
Overseas Private Investment Corp. and the use of U.S. funds to
support trade with China.
   Other sanctions include the suspension of export of satellites
intended to be launched by China and the suspension of nuclear
cooperation until the president can certify China is not involved in
nuclear proliferation.
   The Senate also adopted a series of non-binding suggestions in
which they urged Bush to take stiffer steps. He should, the Senate
said:
   _Direct the Export-Import Bank to immediately postpone approval
of applications for financing American exports to China.
   _Instruct U.S. representatives at international financial
institutions to oppose all loans to China.
   _Review the advisability of continuing to extend to China
most-favored-nation trade treatment.
   _Review all trade agreements between the two countries.
   _Review commercial agreements governing Chinese-American
cooperation on satellite launches.
   _Review the Chinese-American agreement on the peaceful uses of
atomic energy.
   _Consult with U.S. allies at the upcoming economic summit in
Paris on adopting a collective economic response to repression in
China.
   _Review high technology exports to China.
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas endorsed the
amendment, saying the Chinese government has ``shown no signs of
relenting'' in its persecution of those who took part in or appeared
to encourage the pro-democracy demonstrations.
   ``They are still sliding down a very slippery and dangerous
slope,'' Dole said.
   Those voting against the sanctions amendment were Sens. Kit Bond,
R-Mo.; David Boren, D-Okla.; John Chafee, R-R.I.; Thad Cochran,
R-Miss.; Kent Conrad, D-N.D.; David Durenberger, R-Minn.; Richard
Lugar, R-Ind.; Warren Rudman, R-N.H.; Arlen Specter, R-Pa.; and Ted
Stevens, R-Alaska.
   Those not voting were Sens. William Armstrong, R-Colo.; Dale
Bumpers, D-Ark.; Quentin Burdick, D-N.D.: John C. Danforth, R-Mo.;
James M. Jeffords, R-Vt.; Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.; Spark
Matsunaga, D-Hawaii; Barbara Mikulski, D-Md.; and Alan Simpson,
R-Wyo.
</TEXT>
