<FIRST>r a AM-Turner-Abortion     07-14 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turner-Abortion,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Foes Picket CNN Headquarters Over Documentary</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Kitsie is cq in 6th graf</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angry abortion opponents on Friday urged media
magnate Ted Turner to quit calling them ``bozos'' and other names
and give their cause equal time on his cable network.
   About 10 people picketed Turner's CNN Center in downtown Atlanta
to object to Turner Broadcasting Systems' planned cablecast of a
documentary, ``Abortion For Survival.'' The show, produced from the
point of view of those who favor a woman's right to have an
abortion, is scheduled to be shown on Turner's TBS network next
Thursday.
   The protesters also objected to his labeling anti-abortion forces
``idiots'' and ``bozos'' in a talk with cable operators Wednesday.
   One carried a sign that read, ``I'm no Bozo.''
   The demonstrators demanded that Turner also program an
anti-abortion documentary, ``Eclipse of Reason.'' The film, produced
by Dr. Bernard Nathanson, shows a fetus aborted at 24 weeks.
   TBS spokeswoman Kitsie Bassett Riggall said TBS received a letter
from the National Right to Life requesting the use of of ``Eclipse
of Reason.''
   ``It is under consideration, but no decision has been made,'' she
said.
   Turner announced the program during a meeting of cable
executives. He said that after the program, there would be a
televised debate including Rep. Robert Dornan, R-Calif., an abortion
foe; Faye Wattleton of Planned Parenthood; and Nellie Gray,
president of March for Life.
   ``We'll give the other bozos a chance to talk back,'' Turner
said. ``They look like idiots anyway.''
   Georgia Right to Life spokeswoman Mary Boyert said in a statement
Friday that the group thinks Turner has failed in his responsibility
to be impartial. They also objected to the flippant nature of his
comments.
   ``Abortion is no joke. Babies are dying. It doesn't take much
brains to know that,'' the statement said. ``Ted Turner has thrown
down the gauntlet, and we intend to fight.''
   Ms. Boyert said her group doesn't plan continued focus on Turner,
but wanted him to know they are ``disappointed with the biased
programming.''
   TBS got about 20 calls from viewers Thursday, about half of them
objecting to Turner's comments or the premise of the abortion
program. Spokeswoman Kirsten White said the volume of calls about
doubled Friday, but couldn't provide exact numbers or say what the
callers said.
</TEXT>
