<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0639 07-14 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0639,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian-Christian Artillery Battle over Tanker</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE number of dead and wounded and
with fighting continuing into the night; pickup 6th graf pvs, `A spokesman...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An oil tanker sailed past a Syrian naval
blockade Friday and docked at a Christian port, triggering an
artillery duel between Syrian and Christian gunners that killed
seven people and wounded 12.
   The thud of exploding shells and whooshing sound of rockets
echoed across Beirut as Syrian gunners opened up on the
Christian-controlled coast north of the capital. The fighting
continued late into the night.
   A police spokesman said the unidentified tanker, which arrived at
an undisclosed harbor north of Beirut, was the second to reach the
Christian enclave in the past two days with a cargo of badly needed
fuel.
   On Wednesday, another tanker unloaded gasoline at Byblos port, 18
miles north of the capital.
   The deaths from the artillery duel raised the overall toll to 416
killed and 1,627 wounded since the current confrontation erupted
March 8 between Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun's 20,000
troops and Syria's 40,000-member force in Lebanon.
   A spokesman for Aoun's command, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said a Syrian gunboat intercepted the latest tanker in
Lebanese territorial waters early in the day, searched it for
weapons and ammunition and ``allowed the captain to resume his
voyage.
   ``I don't understand why Syrian gunners shelled the ship after
the Syrian gunboat permitted it to continue,'' said the spokesman,
who refused to give any details about the tanker and its cargo,
citing ``security considerations.''
   He said the Syrians shelled the Christian coast from positions in
Moslem west Beirut and the northern town of Salaata, on the edge of
the 310-square-mile enclave.
   He said Aoun's gunners scored ``several direct hits on Syrian
artillery emplacements in Beirut and the north.'' However, the claim
could not be independently verified.
   Shells exploded near the American University of Beirut in the
city's Moslem sector, witnesses said.
   The Syrian military headquarters in Beirut refused to comment.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named in line with standing
rules, said Syrian barrage concentrated on the 28-mile Christian
stretch of Lebanon's 130-mile Mediterranean coast.
   The Syrians have besieged the Christian enclave since March 12 in
retaliation for a blockade Aoun ordered of illegal ports run by
Syrian-backed militias south of Beirut that he said were depriving
his government of $100 million a year in tax revenue.
   The Syrian navy joined the blockade earlier this month after
Syria claimed Aoun obtained Soviet-designed Frog-7 missiles from its
traditional Arab rival, Iraq. The missiles are capable of hitting
Damascus, the Syrian capital.
   Aoun and his aides have refused to confirm or deny that they have
Frog-7 missiles, but Iraq said Thursday that Aoun has the missiles,
which have a range of more than 40 miles.
   An editorial in the official daily newspaper Al-Thawra,
controlled by President Saddam Hussein's ruling Arab Socialist Baath
party, said Syria was ``expressing fear of missiles received by the
regular Lebanese army.'' It did not elaborate.
   Syria and Iraq are ruled by rival wings of the Baath party.
   Iraq has declared support for Aoun's ``war of liberation''
against Syrian forces which entered Lebanon in 1976 under an Arab
League peacekeeping mandate.
   Aoun and other Christian leaders accuse the Syrians of betraying
their mandate by siding with the Moslems in the 14-year-old civil
war which has killed more than 150,000 people.
</TEXT>
