<DOCNO> AP890714-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 2113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Walesa     07-14 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Walesa,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Will Support Any Communist Presidential Candidate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said Friday
that Poland needs a president immediately to resolve a
constitutional crisis, and he will support anyone the Communist
Party puts up.
   The president is to be elected by a joint vote of the both houses
of the new parliament, in which Solidarity is strongly represented.
   Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, the Communist Party chief, said June 30
he would not run for the new, more powerful presidency because he
was too closely linked with the martial law he imposed in December
1981 to crush Solidarity.
   Under agreements signed in April, the independent labor union was
made legal again and Poland held its freest postwar elections, in
which Solidarity trounced the Communist Party.
   In a statement released by an aide, Walesa said Friday: ``I will
cooperate with any president elected ... no matter if it is Gen.
Jaruzelski, Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak or some other representative'' of
the Communist Party ``in order to solve Polish problems.''
   When Jaruzelski said he would not seek the presidency he
recommended Kiszczak, who is interior minister and negotiated the
April accords with Solidarity, but the party leadership asked him to
reconsider his own candidacy.
   Jaruzelski has re-emerged as a likely candidate, especially after
appearing frequently with George Bush during the American
president's three-day visit.
   Walesa said Poland's domestic and international situation
requires a president, and ``the election ... should be held
immediately.''
   ``Our country faces a great chance, but at the same time we have
a constitutional crisis connected with a delay in filling the
president's office,'' he said. ``Extension of this situation causes
additional dangers.'' Mikolaj Kozakiewicz, speaker of the Sejm, the
former unicameral parliament and now the lower house, said Thursday
the election might take place by July 22, Poland's national day.
   Kozakiewicz said the Bush visit had eased controversy about
Jaruzelski's candidacy, but many Solidarity legislators were jailed
during martial law and have said they will not vote for Jaruzelski.
   Walesa is not a member of the parliament and, in his statement,
did not instruct Solidarity representatives how to vote.
</TEXT>
