<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 2220EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Arrest     07-14 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Arrest,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctor Accused of Threatening Mayor Over Comments About Late Emporer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Friday arrested a doctor accused of
threatening the mayor of Nagasaki after the mayor said the late
Emperor Showa bore responsibility for World War II.
   Shigeru Kajiyama, 62, head of a private hospital in Nagasaki,
sent Mayor Hitoshi Motoshima two letters containing bullets, said
Nagasaki police spokesman Hiroharu Naoe.
   Motoshima told the municipal assembly in December that Emperor
Hirohito, known as Emperor Showa since his death in January, bore
responsibility for World War II.
   More than 70,000 people were killed in the closing days of the
war when the United States dropped an atomic bomb on Nagasaki on
Aug. 9, 1945. Three days earlier, the first such bomb was dropped on
Hiroshima, killing about 140,000.
   Motoshima's comments angered right-wing groups, whose members
paraded in Nagasaki in trucks and used loudspeakers to demand
Motoshima's ouster.
   Kajiyama was a central figure of a group that collected more than
150,000 signatures on a petition demanding the mayor be removed from
office, news reports said.
   Shortly after World War II, Kajiyama was a doctor in Japan's
National Police Reserve, the predecessor of Japan's postwar
military, now known as the Self-Defense Force.
   Naoe said Kajiyama admitted sending Motoshima two anonymous
letters, one on Feb. 22 and another on March 1, threatening to kill
the mayor unless he resigned immediately, police said.
   ``The first one said `If you go to Tokyo (to attend the late
emperor's funeral), you'll be killed,''' Naoe said.
   Emperor Hirohito died on Jan. 7 of cancer at age 87. His state
funeral was held on Feb. 24.
   Naoe declined to discuss the letters further. ``This is sensitive
information for investigation,'' he said.
</TEXT>
