<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1901EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-KurdishShootings     07-14 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kurdish Shootings,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kurdish Leader, Two Others Slain in Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attackers burst into a meeting of Kurdish
activists and fatally shot the leader of an anti-Iranian faction and
two other men, police said Friday. An Iranian diplomat was reported
wounded.
   The Iranian Embassy said Thursday's attack was carried out by
``the enemies of Iran,'' but it did not elaborate in its statement.
   However, Iran's main opposition group, the Iraqi-based Mujahedeen
Khalq, said the killings were carried out by the Iranian government
to crush the Kurdish Democratic Party of Iran.
   Austrian police said the dead included party leader Abdul Rahman
Qassemlou, 59.
   State-run Tehran television, monitored in Cyprus, said Qassemlou
had requested a meeting with Iranian officials to seek Iranian
amnesty for Iraqi Kurds who are being forcibly evacuated from their
homes in northern Iraq. It also said Qassemlou was seeking a
guarantee of safety for himself.
   The Iranian Embassy said one of the topics of discussion was
``requested immunity for the repentant members of the Kurdish
Democratic Party of Iran.''
   The Mujahedeen Khalq said ``Qassemlou has finally fallen victim
to negotiations'' with Iran, which the Mujahedeen have condemned,
according to their telex sent to The Associated Press in Nicosia,
Cyrus.
   Qassemlou's outlawed wing of the Kurdish Democratic Party has
been been fighting Iran for an independent homeland for Iranian
Kurds.
   During Thursday's attack, an Iranian diplomat, who is also a
Kurd, was seriously wounded, said Werner Liebhart, a police chief in
Vienna.
   The Iranian Embassy confirmed that Iranian officials were at the
meeting. It said earlier meetings had ``indicated success was near.''
   Neither Iranian nor Austrian reports cited a motive for the
attack.
   Liebhart said the other two killed were Qassemlou aide Abdullah
Ghaderi-Azar, 37, a Kurd who police said had identification papers
issued by France; and Iraqi-born Fadel Mala Mahmoud Rasoul, 38, who
held Austrian citizenship since 1985.
   The three, who were all shot in the head, were living in Austria
as political exiles. All members of the anti-Iranian party wing are
said to live in exile.
   The wounded diplomat was identified as Mohamed Diafari
Sahraroodi. Police said he was not yet able to give a detailed
account of the attack because he had been shot in the mouth.
   Liebhart said the shooting occurred in the evening inside an
apartment near Vienna's center. The apartment was made available by
an unidentified Austrian woman, he said.
   More than four people apparently took part in the meeting,
Liebhart told reporters.
   Two or three men stormed into the apartment and opened fire
before escaping, he said. Police said the attackers were unknown.
   It was not clear how they gained entry, since the door was not
damaged, the police official said.
   The Kurds are an ethnic minority of 20 million living in Turkey,
Iran, and Iraq and small enclaves of 500,000 each in Syria and the
Soviet Union.
   Qassemlou, who was educated in France, lived there in exile for
several years.
   He fought the Iranian government alongside the Mujahedeen and
other opposition groups in the early 1980s. However, he later
supported negotiations.
   The Kurdish Democratic Party has another wing based in Iran.
Under Iranian sponsorship, it is fighting Iraq for an independent
homeland for Iraqi Kurds.
   The Iraqi government recently has been accused of forcibly
evacuating thousands of Kurds from their homes, razing towns in the
northern Kurdish homeland and resettling Kurds in the south of the
country.
   The government says the resettlement is to improve life for the
impoverished Kurds.
   A short time before Iraq and Iran agreed to their cease-fire, the
Iraqis dropped poison gas on the Kurdish town of Halabja, killing an
estimated 4,000 civilians. The Kurds claim thousands more were
killed in similar chemical weapons attacks last fall.
</TEXT>
