<HEAD>Jordan to Get $97 Million from IMF</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jordan, which owes more than $8 billion, will
get another loan of $97 million, the International Monetary Fund
announced Friday.
   In April at least nine Jordanians were killed in riots brought on
by price increases. The fund called for more austerity: tight
management of demand and a hold-down on government spending.
   The country's income dropped by 4 percent last year. Its
citizens' average income reached a peak of $1,720 dollars in 1982
after increasing for a decade, and has dropped since.
   The fund blamed prolonged recession in the region.
