<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 2132EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AnimalRights     07-14 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Animal Rights,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activist Pleads Guilty to Possessing Pipe Bombs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An animal-rights activist accused of planting a
pipe bomb at a medical supply company that demonstrates equipment on
dogs pleaded guilty Friday to charges of possessing two bombs found
in her apartment.
   Fran Trutt, 34, entered the guilty plea in U.S. District Court.
   She still faces trial in Connecticut on attempted murder charges
stemming from allegations she planted a radio-controlled,
nail-filled pipe bomb outside the Norwalk headquarters of United
States Surgical on Nov. 11.
   The medical supply company uses about 900 dogs a year to show
doctors how to use its surgical staples _ anesthetizing the animals,
operating on them and then destroying them.
   That bomb was found near the parking space used by the company
chairman, Leon Hirsch. Ms. Trutt was arrested before it exploded.
   After her arrest, police searching her New York City apartment
discovered two more pipe bombs in an attache case stashed under a
sink.
   ``I possessed two pipe bombs in my apartment,'' she said quietly
after U.S. District Judge Joseph M. McLaughlin instructed her to
describe the crime.
   She faces up to 10 years in prison and a $250,000 fine when
McLaughlin sentences her Oct. 6.
   Ms. Trutt has been in custody in Connecticut since her arrest
last November. She is scheduled for trial in Connecticut in October,
said her attorney Myron Beldock.
   When the crude bomb was found outside its headquarters, U.S.
Surgical quickly condemned it as an example of the growing
fanaticism of the animal-rights movement.
   However, it later turned out that the company had been watching
Ms. Trutt for some time, and that an undercover agent working for
U.S. Surgical drove Ms. Trutt and her bomb from her home to the
company headquarters.
   The company maintains it was taking sensible measures to protect
itself by monitoring Ms. Trutt. However, her lawyers argue she was
set up by the company and that its agents encouraged Ms. Trutt to
obtain the bombs and even provided money for them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
