<FIRST>u w AM-WanderingPlane-Probes 2ndLd-Writethru   07-14 1206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wandering Plane-Probes, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0769-a0774-a0755,1,010</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot Root Carried Many Guns</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Wandering Plane Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs; new info on FCC activities in 2nd graf and grafs
30-34 bgng: ``Sonrise sent;'' other minor editing and tightening.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three dozen guns, many of them loaded, were
found in April in a search of the plane of Thomas Root, the pilot
who survived an 800-mile flight, bullet wound and crash-landing in
the ocean, officials said Friday.
   In other results of scrutiny of Root's activities, a North
Carolina official said Root was involved in a state investigation
into possible securities law violations, and documents at the
Federal Communications Commission revealed that he repeatedly failed
to comply with deadlines and other requirements in cases before the
commission.
   All of the guns were legal under federal law, and all but one
under state law, which led to a state misdemeanor charge.
   A search of Root's Cessna 210 at the Manassas, Va., Airport on
April 24 by federal and local officials revealed ``about 35 weapons
and silencers and ammunition clips,'' including a machine gun that
had not been registered with Virginia, said a U.S. Customs Official
who consented to an interview on condition that he not be identified.
   Most of the weapons, such as assault-style rifles and three
.357-caliber Magnum pistols, were loaded, the official said.
   In addition, the officials found handcuffs and an electrical stun
gun as well as a five-gallon can of ether, a chemical used in the
refining of cocaine, he said.
   Searchers, helped by a drug-sniffing dog, found no drugs on the
plane.
   During a May 31 interview with Root by Prince William County
Police and a Customs agent, ``by and large he was able to account
for legal possession of those weapons. The bottom line on this, with
the exception of one weapon, a machine gun, most of these weapons
were legal and legally registered.''
   The machine gun had been registered, as required by federal law,
with the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. Virginia
authorities charged Root with a misdemeanor for failing to register
the gun with the state, he said.
   ``Basically, he indicated that he was a gun collector,'' the
official said. But there was no indication from Root on why he kept
the weapons on his plane, which was registered to a Washington-based
company he owns, nor why they were loaded.
   Asked about the ether, Root told the officials that ``it was used
to clean his aircraft, but of course that's not what you use to
clean an aircraft with unless you're going to blow it up,'' the
official laughed.
   Officials did not close the case ``because when you come across
this many weapons ... we always continue to take a look to make sure
no Customs laws have been violated.''
   ``This is weird, to say the least,'' he said.
   The official said all the guns were seized and had not yet been
returned to Root by state authorities.
   The FBI, meanwhile is conducting a preliminary investigation of
what happened on the plane, said spokesman Sean Lemieux.
   ``It's an unusual incident and the FBI has jurisdiction in crimes
aboard aircraft, so the FBI is looking into it to see if there are
any violations of federal criminal statutes,'' Lemieux said.
   Root's plane crash-landed, and he swam to rescuers. Hollywood,
Fla., Police Chief Richard Witt said Root had been shot, the bullet
going through his left rib cage and his colon, leaving his body,
then going through his arm.
   A powder burn indicated Root was shot at close range, the chief
said.
   An investigator for the National Transportation Safety Board,
Andrew Alston, was to interview Root for the first time on Saturday,
said agency spokeswoman Rachel Halterman.
   In North Carolina, Secretary of State Rufus Edmisten said of
Root, ``Our office has spoken to him'' in regard to a securities
probe. ``Obviously he knew he was under investigation,'' Edmisten
said.
   ``The investigation has been focused on Sonrise Management
Services and while he is not employed by them, he has ties to them
and has been an integral part of the investigation,'' Edmisten said.
   Sonrise said in a statement issued in Georgia that Root ``in no
way represents'' the firm. ``The only connection with Mr. Root is
that he represents certain entities which also number among our
clientele,'' said the firm.
   ``SMS is in the business of helping individuals and other
associations secure FCC licenses to open and operate radio
stations,'' Edmisten said. ``A very substantial part of their
business is done in North Carolina.''
   Edmisten said Root was the attorney for investment partnerships
formed by Sonrise.
   Sonrise Properties was competing with Rocky Mount, N.C., radio
station WCEC for a new FM station, said WCEC owner Joe Warner. Root
also was majority owner of radio station WSWR in Shelby, Ohio.
   On Thursday, Root was flying to Rocky Mount to meet a client,
Nancy Mooring, who is managing partner of a group that has applied
for a license to operate an FM radio station here, she said.
   Root was supposed to meet her at Rocky Mount-Wilson Airport but
never showed up, she said Friday.
   Edmisten said Sonshine would form a group of investors and ``a
legal entity, a partnership of some kind, is formed, and that
partnership makes an application to the FCC for a broadcast license.
Mr. Root then becomes the attorney for the partnership or group.''
   ``There are some allegations that the way it's set up is a way to
avoid securities laws,'' Edmisten said.
   Sonrise sent out a recent notice to a client listing several
instances involving Root that it said ``caused us great concern''
and offering to pay the costs if the client opted to select a
different lawyer.
   Sonrise said that the FCC has stated that Root in at least four
cases ``has failed to honor important procedural dates including
failure to appear for a deposition and flagrant default with regard
to answering interrogatories.''
   Root failed to appear for a required desposition involving
Timothy FM Limited Partnership, which he represented in a bid to
obtain a broadcast license in Charlottesville, Va., FCC documents
show.
   Just 45 minutes before his scheduled appearance under subpoena,
Root submitted via facsimile a motion purporting to dismiss
Timothy's application for the license, which also was being sought
by McClenahan Broadcasting Inc.
   FCC administrative law judge Joseph Chachkin wrote in his order
dismissing Timothy's application: ``Root's failure to provide
earlier notice of his intention not to appear for deposition,
requiring McClenahan to pay the costs of a court reporters, cannot
be condoned.''
   In Washington, Ms. Halterman of the National Transportation
Safety Board said investigators ``have not come to any conclusions
and have not ruled out anything at all.''
   She said the agency's investigators had ordered independent
tissue examination to check a police and FBI conclusion that Root
suffered a single-bullet gunshot wound. Blood tests were also being
taken to check for drugs or carbon monoxide.
   In Oklahoma City, Federal Aviation Administration records showed
that Root has had a private pilot's license since 1970, when he was
17. Linda Whitfield of the Airman and Aircraft Certification Branch
said his record as a pilot was clean, with no incidents, accidents
or enforcements.
</TEXT>
