<FIRST>u i AM-Peru 1stLd-Writethru a0720 07-14 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0720,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Writer Vargas Llosa Returns to Run for President</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with further comment from Vargas
Llosa, details of Peru's economic, social problems; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Novelist Mario Vargas Llosa returned Friday
from Spain to resume his presidential candidacy, 23 days after
quitting the race in a dispute with members of his coalition.
   Hundreds of supporters waving flags and handkerchiefs greeted him
with shouts of ``President Mario'' as he stepped off the plane.
   Vargas Llosa criticized the ``outdated, irresponsible and
demagogic politics that have characterized Peru in recent years''
and that have been rejected by the ``vast majority'' of Peruvians,
who are to vote for president next spring.
   He rode in a motorcade to his seaside home in a Lima suburb,
where he spoke to supporters from his balcony.
   ``In this moment, the only priority is the salvation of our
fatherland, stopping its fall into impoverishment, incompetence and
self-destruction,'' Vargas Llosa told the crowd.
   Vargas Llosa had sent a letter to party leaders in the Democratic
Front when he quit the race June 22, saying he was dropping out
because of ``petty and mediocre'' motives of some in the party.
   The leaders in the center-right coalition had disagreed over
whether each party should field its own candidates in November's
municipal elections.
   Vargas Llosa said he could not be a candidate for the coalition
without the united support of the parties. He said that support
would be impossible if the parties had to battle each other in the
local elections.
   The writer resumed his candidacy July 2 after the parties agreed
to nominate single candidates representing the front in the
elections, which are expected to be a test run for the presidential
election, tentatively scheduled for April 1990.
   The Democratic Front is dominated by Vargas Llosa's Liberty
Movement, former President Fernando Belaunde Terry's centrist
Popular Action Party and the conservative Popular Christian Party.
   Recent polls show the novelist comfortably leading his closest
rival, former socialist Lima Mayor Alfonso Barrantes, candidate of a
leftist coalition.
   Luis Alva Castro, the candidate of the governing center-left
Aprista party, is given little chance of winning because of voter
discontent with President Alan Garcia's administration.
   Vargas Llosa is basing his campaign on radical, neo-liberal
policies to reduce government intervention in the economy and to
reduce the bloated bureaucracy.
   The ideas are popular with business and the middle class, whose
incomes are being ravaged by inflation that reached 1,722 percent
last year and is expected to exceed 6,000 percent this year.
   Peru has stopped payments on its $16.5 billion foreign debt, and
has been cut off by the International Monetary Fund and the World
Bank.
   The country is also facing a leftist insurgency that has left
15,000 people dead and caused $10 billion in damages, according to
government figures.
   Vargas Llosa, often mentioned as a candidate for the Nobel Prize
in literature, had gone to Italy to receive a literary award. He
then traveled to France and Spain, where he said his ideas for
dealing with Peru's problems were widely supported.
   But his on-again, off-again candidacy has caused some analysts to
question whether he can take the strain of a long campaign.
   ``Quitting once is a tragedy,'' said a Democratic Front official
who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``But quitting twice would be a
comedy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
