<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-14 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rains Inundate Much of the Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms drenched central Oklahoma, Louisiana and northwest
Texas on Friday, forcing people from their houses, flooding a
nursing home and washing tombstones from cemetery plots.
   Most of the streets in Sulphur Springs, Texas, became impassable
when 1 to 1{ inches fell in about 30 minutes. Some police
encountered water as high as the hoods of their car.
   Showers and thunderstorms also continued across much of Oklahoma
and northern Texas on Friday. Over 2 inches of rain fell around
midday in portions of Payne County, Okla.
   In southern Oklahoma, high water from torrential rains
temporarily blocked a highway south of Durant and inundated a
nursing home in Calera.
   The storm dumped 6 inches of rain in the Durant area within a few
hours. In Calera, volunteers sandbagged doors of the Calera Manor
nursing home after heavy rain sent flood water surging into the
low-lying area.
   Before the sandbags were in place, 5 to 6 inches of water flooded
most of the building, officials said. No residents were evacuated
because officials feared traveling on the flooded roads would be
more dangerous.
   In Louisiana, 8 inches of rain fell in parts of northern
Lafayette and Vermilion parishes early Friday.
   In Opelousas, La., the heavy rain forced at least 100 people out
of their homes and moved about a half-dozen tombstones from their
cemetery plots.
   Thunderstorms were widespread across the Gulf Coast states and
the Florida peninsula. A thunderstorm in the southern suburbs of
Birmingham, Ala., brought almost 1 inch of rain in 40 minutes.
   Thunderstorms developed rapidly Friday afternoon over the
foothills of the central and southern Rockies and in southern
Nebraska.
   Showers and thunderstorms also hit parts of New England and
eastern New York due to an upper level trough of low pressure.
   Skies were mostly sunny west of the Rockies.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 57
degrees at Monterey, Calif., to 112 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.
   The forecast for Saturday called for showers and thunderstorms
scattered from the Carolinas across the lower Mississippi Valley to
much of the Great Lakes; numerous showers and thunderstorms from
Kansas across northeast Texas and the central Gulf Coast to northern
Florida; and widely scattered thunderstorms over eastern Washington,
Idaho and western Montana.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s from Nebraska and
South Dakota across Iowa, the Great Lakes and the upper Ohio Valley
to New England; in the 70s over the Pacific Northwest and along the
California coast; 100 degrees over south central and southwest
Texas, southern New Mexico and interior valleys of California;
between 100 to 115 degrees in the desert Southwest; and in the 80s
and 90s throughout the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
