<FIRST>r a AM-CocaineSentence 1stLd-Writethru a0672 07-14 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine Sentence, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0672,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Ordered Not To Marry, Have Children For 4 Years As Part of Drug
Sentence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Bartholomew Superior...', to CORRECT to Axsom
fathering child sted Dillon. SUBS 7th graf, `Monroe didn't...', to RESTORE
dropped word `he.'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEN KUSMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who pleaded guilty to dealing in
cocaine has been forbidden to marry or father children for four
years, but he isn't about to appeal.
   He and his attorney consider the sentence _ handed down during a
temporary moratorium that bars overcrowded state prisons from
accepting new inmates _ a bargain.
   Michael Axsom, 28, of Columbus, will remain confined to his home
except during working hours under a home detention provision in the
sentence. He also must perform 160 hours of community service.
   ``The judge said, `I don't know if this is constitutional or
not,''' Indianapolis attorney Stephen Dillon said Friday. ``And he
looked at me and I shook my head no, and then he turned to my client
and said, `But it's your choice.'''
   Bartholomew Superior Court Judge Chris Monroe, in pronouncing
sentence Monday in Columbus, 60 miles south of Indianapolis, cited
what he called Axsom's history of instability. The judge said Axsom
fathered a child several years ago whom he is not supporting.
   ``I'm going to order that you not get married and also that you
not father any children during that time,'' the judge told Axsom.
``That may be an improper imposition on your rights, but I could
send you to prison.''
   Monroe didn't respond to a telephone request for comment Friday.
Axsom didn't answer either, and Dillon said he was out getting the
telephone he'll need so authorities can make sure he's home when
he's supposed to be.
   ``At this point we don't intend to appeal,'' Dillon said. ``He's
happy he isn't going to prison. The judge could have given him 10
years in prison.''
   Acting under federal court orders to ease prison crowding, the
state imposed a five-day moratorium on accepting new inmates in its
prisons Monday.
   Axsom was charged with two counts of dealing in cocaine, a felony
that could have brought him 40 years in prison, Dillon said. The
defense agreed to plead guilty to one count if the prosecution
dropped the other count and made no sentencing recommendation.

</TEXT>
