<FIRST>u w AM-WanderingPlane-FCC     07-14 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wandering Plane-FCC,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Failed to Comply with FCC Deadlines</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Wandering Plane, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas L. Root, the communications lawyer
pulled from Bahamian waters in a dramatic rescue, repeatedly failed
to comply with deadlines and other requirements in cases before the
Federal Communications Commission, according to documents released
Friday.
   Root also represented numerous clients of a Georgia-based company
that another broadcast firm labeled a ``notorious application mill''
for FM broadcast licenses that allegedly has bilked hundreds of
individuals of their investments.
   The firm, Sonrise Management Services Inc., a month ago
encouraged clients to stop doing business with Root, offering to
cover their initial retainer fee if they switched lawyers. The firm
said that ``in at least four occasions'' he had failed to honor
important procedural dates'' at the FCC.
   Two communications lawyers who had dealings with Root said he was
known to have filed numerous license applications at the FCC that
were rejected or dropped because of misrepresentations, missed
deadlines, and other problems.
   ``Lots of people in the (FCC's) FM branch has got a Tom Root
story,'' said communications attorney Barry Wood. ``He was hard
working but he was overwhelmed by the number of cases he had.''
   Police in Florida disclosed Friday that Root suffered a gunshot
wound, apparently during his 800-mile, unconscious flight that ended
with a crash in the Bahamas and rescue at sea. Root told his
brother-in-law the wound wasn't self-inflicted.
   In one instance of a missed appearance involving his law
practice, Root failed to appear for a required deposition involving
Timothy FM Limited Partnership, which he represented in a bid to
obtain a broadcast license in Charlottesville, Va., FCC documents
show.
   Just 45 minutes before his scheduled appearance under subpoena,
Root submitted via facsimile a motion purporting to dismiss
Timothy's application for the license, which also was being sought
by McClenahan Broadcasting Inc.
   FCC administrative law Judge Joseph Chachkin wrote in his order
dismissing Timothy's application: ``Root's failure to provide
earlier notice of his intention not to appear for deposition,
requiring McClenahan to pay the costs of a court reporter, can not
be condoned.''
   McClenahan, in a filing before the FCC, charged that Timothy was
in fact controlled by Sonrise, of Columbus, Ga., which it said was
``notorious in FCC comparative hearing cases.''
   Sonrise _ which advertises itself as offering ``Management with a
Christian Ethic'' _ issued a statement Friday denying Root served as
its legal counsel. It said Root ``represents certain entities which
also number among our clientele.''
   Officials in North Carolina said Friday that Sonrise was being
investigated for possible securities law violations and that Root
was part of that probe.
   ``The investigation has been focused on Sonrise Management
Services and while he is not employed by them, he has ties to them
and has been an integral part of the investigation,'' said Secretary
of State Rufus Edmisten.
   Sonrise, in its statment, said it never has been found guilty of
any securities violation and that it is working with North Carolina
officials to reach ``an amicable resolution'' of the state's
concerns.
</TEXT>
