<FIRST>r i AM-Lesotho     07-14 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lesotho,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Announce Inquiry Into Shooting Death Linked to Military Ruler</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MASERU, Lesotho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney-general's office Friday
announced a judicial inquiry into a shooting death that foreign news
reports linked to the military ruler of this small African kingdom.
   Student George Ramone, 20, was shot to death last December at the
Lesotho Agricultural College. Despite his parents' pleas, no inquest
or inquiry was held, and no one was arrested or charged.
   Early in July, the London Observer, The Washington Post and
several South African newspapers carried reports saying Maj. Gen.
Justin Metsing Lekhanya, 51, leader of a six-man military tribunal,
was alleged to have shot Ramone.
   The reports said Lekhanya's bodyguard told police he had shot the
student to stop an attempted rape, but that Lekhanya made a
subsequent statement to the ruling military council saying he
actually had done the shooting while ``on patrol'' on the campus.
   The alleged rape victim, reported to be an employee of a lecturer
at the university, has made no comment.
   The Lesotho government and the local press have remained silent
about the case, although the foreign newspapers freely circulated in
this country surrounded by South Africa.
   The members of the military council, who took power in a Jauary
1986 coup that toppled left-wing dictator Leabua Jonathan, have held
several lengthy, closed meetings on the subject, according to
sources close to the government.
   The attorney-general's announcement Friday made no mention of
Lekhanya, but referred to the foreign newspaper reports.
   Ramone's parents said the judicial inquiry was to be held July 30.
</TEXT>
