<FIRST>r a AM-FireRdp     07-14 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fire Rdp,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Fire Near Containment; Lightning Threatens More Blazes
in West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters predicted victory over a big blaze on the scenic
California coast Friday, as smaller wildfires burned in central
Arizona and elsewhere in the West.
   Lightning was expected in a wide swath from Idaho to Arizona,
bringing the threat of more lightning-sparked fires, according to
the federal Interagency Fire Center in Boise, Idaho.
   ``The fires have decreased with the humidity,'' said Reed Jarvis,
spokesman at the center. ``But the prognosis is for light activity
due to lightning.''
   A ``red flag'' warning was issued for the eastern slopes of the
Cascade range in Washington because of the lightning threat, he said.
   The largest blaze still out of control was at Big Sur, on the
northern California coast south of Monterrey.
   The 6-day-old arson blaze had scorched 3,000 acres of brush and
timber, but more than 1,500 firefighters made headway Friday, their
work made easier because winds were light. The fire was 70 percent
contained and crews hoped to get it fully contained by nightfall,
said Bill Jones, spokesman for the California Department of Forestry.
   California Gov. George Deumejian has offered a $50,000 reward for
information on whoever started the fire, which has done an estimated
$1.4 million damage to timber and cost $1.3 million to fight.
   A 3,000-acre brush fire ignited by tracer rounds at the Marines'
Camp Pendleton was contained Friday, said a base spokeswoman, Cpl.
Lorna Shryock.
   In central Arizona, a lightning-sparked timber blaze in Prescott
National Forest that was considered contained Monday flared up, and
had grown to 700 acres by Friday, said Forest Service spokesman
Steve Walker. About 120 firefighters battled the fire, and experts
didn't know when it would be contained.
   In the Tonto National Forest to the east, 250 firefighters
attacked a ``sleeper'' fire that started last weekend and stayed
small and unnoticed, said Forest Service spokesman Jim Payne. That
blaze had burned 150 acres of timber by Friday, he said, and ``it
has the potential to get much larger.''
   Meanwhile, outside Silver City, N.M., 565 endangered Gila trout
scooped from streams choked with fire-generated ash adjusted to
temporary quarters at the Mescalero Fish Hatchery.
   ``They're swimming,'' said Barbara Giesecke, U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service assistant manager of the hatchery. ``They seem to
be doing fairly good this morning.''
   The fire, which burned 10,000 acres of timber and brush northeast
of Silver City, was contained Monday. But the ash continued to
settle.
   The trout will stay at the hatchery until the water level in
their home creek returns to safe levels, and the ash _ which cuts
the water's oxygen-carrying capacity and raises its alkalinity _
gets clear enough for safety.
</TEXT>
