<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 2009EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Iran     07-14 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Iran,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Making Progress on Compensation Concerning Iran Air Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is prepared to announce
a compensation offer early next week for families of the non-Iranian
victims on the Iran Air flight shot down by a U.S. warship a year
ago, officials said Friday.
   All but 40 of the 290 people who died were Iranian. The United
States has said it would pay compensation to all families, but the
Iranian government has refused to provide details about its citizens
who died, such as their ages.
   The 40 non-Iranians were Indians, Pakistanis, Koreans, Japanese
and citizens of several Arab countries.
   The U.S. government has said it will not pay the Iranian
government directly, and Iran has called that position ``not
acceptable.''
   In civil lawsuits arising from crash deaths in the United States,
courts generally award compensation based on the lost earnings of a
family member. Thus families of people who die early in lucrative
careers usually win larger awards than families of retired people.
It is not known whether such an approach would be followed in the
government's compensation offer.
   The officials, who asked not to be identified, were unable to
provide figures on the compensation package they expect but said a
formal announcement was expected early next week.
   The absence of diplomatic relations, broken nine years ago when
hostages were seized in the U.S. Embassy in Tehran, has complicated
efforts to arrange payments for the Iranian victims.
   Testifying on the issue earlier this week, Assistant Secretary of
State John Kelly said that the administration hopes to be able to
resolve the problems concerning compensation for the families of
Iranian victims by working through third countries and
non-governmental organizations such as the Red Cross.
   The Airbus A300 plane was on a flight from Bandar Abbas to Dubai
when the USS Vincennes, mistaking it for a hostile fighter about to
attack, shot it down with a missile.
   Iran, which seeks compensation for the loss of the plane, has
sued the United States in the World Court over the incident, and
relatives of some victims have sued the manufacturer of the
Vincennes radar system, General Electric Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
