<FIRST>u a AM-WanderingPlane 2ndLd-Writethru a0748 07-14 1090</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wandering Plane, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0748,1119</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Miracle' Pilot Was Shot, Authorities Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH5</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf, `The FBI..., with five grafs to UPDATE with
three dozen guns found in Root's plane in April. Picks up 12th graf, `Other
federal...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police disclosed Friday that
attorney-pilot Thomas Root had a gunshot wound when he was rescued
in the Bahamas after his amazing 800-mile, unconscious flight down
the East Coast.
   ``It was unquestionably a gunshot wound,'' said Hollywood Police
Chief Richard Witt, who added that a powder burn indicated the shot
was fired at close range and was possibly self-inflicted.
   Root said the wound wasn't self-inflicted, and may have occurred
on impact when his plane plunged into the Atlantic Ocean, according
to his brother-in-law, Brett Geer. Root, who is a gun collector, had
a .32-caliber handgun with him in the cockpit, Geer said.
   Investigators said there was no evidence that anybody else was in
the plane.
   Root, 36, remained under heavy sedation at Memorial Hospital in
Hollywood. Hospital spokeswoman Cynthia Wine said he was improving
and was listed in stable condition.
   Witt said surgeons had found a wound to Root's abdomen, and
determined that a bullet passed through his colon, exited, struck
him in the left arm and exited again.
   In Washington on Friday, a U.S. Customs official said authorities
found three dozen guns, many of them loaded, in a search of Root's
plane last April. All of the guns were legal under federal law, and
all but one under state law, which led to a state misdemeanor charge.
   A search of Root's plane at the Manassas, Va., Airport revealed
``about 35 weapons and silencers and ammunition clips,'' including a
machine gun that had not been registered with Virginia, said a
customs official who consented to an interview on condition that he
not be identified.
   Most of the weapons, such as assault-style rifles and three
.357-caliber Magnum pistols, were loaded, the official said.
   During an interview with Prince William County Police and a
Customs agent, Root ``was able to account for legal possession of
those weapons. The bottom line on this, with the exception of one
weapon, a machine gun, most of these weapons were legal and legally
registered.''
   Also Friday, the FBI moved into the case because of the reported
gunshot wound, spokesman Paul Miller said, and a National
Transportation Safety Board air safety investigator came to the
hospital.
   Other federal investigators scattered to seek information on Root
ranging from his financial situation to his psychological condition,
his physical fitness, his flying ability and his guns, the NTSB
investigator said.
   With Root under sedation and his single-engine Cessna believed to
be at the bottom of Bahamian waters more than a mile deep,
authorities turned their attention to ``multiple phone calls'' from
people in several states making ``various allegations that have not
been confirmed,'' said Andrew Alston, the NTSB investigator.
   He declined to give details, but said they came from private
citizens and government agencies on topics that included Root's
finances and his pilot ability.
   ``There are many questions I'll be asking,'' said Alston, who
delayed until Saturday efforts to interview Root. ``We're not going
to try to bother him today.''
   In North Carolina, Secretary of State Rufus Edmisten said his
office has been investigating security fraud allegations against a
company with which Root was involved.
   Root acted as attorney for partnerships formed by the company,
Sonrise Management Services, which helps other organizations secure
Federal Communications Commission licenses to operate radio
stations. Edmisten said there are allegations that the company was
set up in a way that allowed it to avoid securities laws.
   ``You know these are only allegations,'' he added. ``This is just
heightened because Mr. Root went down in the big waters. ...
Obviously he knew he was under investigation. Our office has spoken
with him.''
   Root's wife, Kathy, 35, planned to visit her husband Friday. On
Thursday, she said she told hospital officials to send her husband
the message: ``Root, you really did it this time.''
   She told reporters Thursday night he had suffered a fainting
spell about two months ago. She also said he had often flown private
planes on business trips.
   Geer, 34, who lives in St. Petersburg, Fla., said he visited Root
Thursday night and again Friday, when the pilot was sitting up in
the chair in his hospital room.
   ``One thing he said was, `Did this get on the news last night?'
   ``I think that's the understatement of the day,'' said Geer.
   Alston said he hoped to interview Root's relatives.
   He said the NTSB couldn't confirm there was a gunshot wound but
said a tissue sample from the burned area, blood samples and a
``very, very small'' metal fragment taken from Root would be
analyzed in federal laboratories.
   ``It's pretty amazing, I agree with that,'' Alston said of Root's
journey on autopilot while shadowed by military and Coast Guard
planes, and his survival and rescue by Air Force parachute rescuers.
   Authorities earlier had speculated that Root may have had a heart
attack or inhaled carbon monoxide. Witt said Root could have been
shot before takeoff, but the wound is believed to have occurred in
the air.
   Alston said Root's radio transmissions with control towers had
been normal until he began heading past his North Carolina
destination and into a warning area, probably a military restricted
zone. Root reported that he was having difficulty breathing, and
then radio contact ceased. Military pilots reported seeing the pilot
slumped over the controls.
   They didn't see anyone else aboard, said Federal Aviation
Administration spokesman Fred Farrar.
   Root's odyssey started on a 6:30 a.m. flight from Washington to
Rocky Mount, N.C., and ended when his out-of-fuel plane crashed into
Bahamian waters at 12:20 p.m. Alston said there were no plans to try
to raise the plane.
   For nearly four hours, military jets shadowed the Cessna 210
Centurion as it traveled down the East Coast.
   After the plane crashed, Root emerged wearing only pants and
socks and swam clear of the craft minutes before it sank.
   ``It was a sight to see,'' said Air Force Staff Sgt. Scott Tracy,
whose parachute rescue team jumped 3,000 feet in 30 seconds to
rescue Root.
   Alston said the Bahamian government has authority over the case
but has asked the NTSB to run the investigation.
   Ms. Wine, the hospital spokeswoman, said Root's family requested
no information be released on the exact extent of his injuries. Root
underwent 90 minutes of exploratory surgery Thursday.
</TEXT>
