<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Priest     07-14 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Priest,0520</SECOND>
<UNK>Autopsy Shows Priest Was Injured, but Not Cause of Death</UNK>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An autopsy conducted Friday determined that
a priest found dead in northern Poland suffered a fractured rib and
sternum and had a high level of alcohol in his blood, the state news
agency said.
   The cause of death was not determined, however, PAP said.
   PAP said the Rev. Sylwester Zych's injuries could have resulted
when vacationers found him at a bus stop in the Baltic resort of
Krynica Morska early Wednesday and tried to revive him.
   Zych, 39, was the third Roman Catholic Polish priest to die in
unusual circumstances in the last six months.
   Unlike the other priests, Zych was not known as an active
supporter of the Polish opposition, although he had served a prison
term for harboring a policeman's killer.
   At the time of his death Zych had been serving as a chaplain in
Olsztyn province, a priest at the Roman Catholic Episcopate in
Warsaw said Friday.
   According to the autopsy, the level of alcohol in Zych's blood
and urine was several times the legal standard for drunkenness, the
agency said.
   ``The post-mortem didn't show any injuries that could be the
direct reasons of Zych's death,'' PAP said.
   ``The final reason of ... death will be established only after
research, which will be made at the same institute, and after a
toxicology test made a specialized institute in Krakow,'' the agency
said.
   Representatives of the Gdansk Roman Catholic Curia and
independent lawyers were present at the autopsy, along with a
Solidarity parliament deputy.
   Zych had been vacationing at the parish of his former prison
chaplain in Braniewo, about 60 miles east of Krynica Morska, and had
dropped from sight on Sunday, according to the Solidarity
Information Service in Warsaw.
   Malgorzata Zajaczkowski, a spokeswoman for the service, said the
chaplain _ identified only as the Rev. Brandys _ read a newspaper
item about the discovery of an unindentified corpse and was able to
identify the body. The service said the body was not dressed in
clerical clothing and had no money or documents on it.
   Zych was sentenced in 1982 to 3{ years in prison for providing
shelter to a young man who had shot and killed a policeman during a
scuffle on a tram car in Warsaw three months after martial law was
imposed in December 1981.
   Zych was arrested in March 1982, several weeks after the
officer's slaying. The two men convicted of the killing were
released from prison in December 1987.
   In January, the Rev. Stefan Niedzielak, a Solidarity supporter,
was found dead of a broken neck in his Warsaw rectory. The case has
not been solved.
   In February, another opposition supporter, the Rev. Stanislaw
Suchowolec, was found dead after fire swept his home in the city of
Bialystok, about 120 miles northeast of Warsaw. An investigation
concluded the fire was an accident.
   Suchowolec was a friend of the late Rev. Jerzy Popieluszko, who
was murdered by security police in October 1984.
</TEXT>
