<FIRST>r a AM-PlaneCrash     07-14 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Crash,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Plane Crashes Into Factory, Three Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROMEOVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small plane crashed into a factory and
burst into flames Friday shortly after takeoff, killing all three
people on board, authorities said.
   Two people on the ground were injured, one seriously, when the
plane hit a loading dock area of the factory.
   The single-engine Cessna 177 took off from Lewis University
Airport which serves the Joliet-Lockport area, said Federal Aviation
Adminstration spokesman Mort Edelstein.
   ``It appeared on takeoff to be unstable and was moving at a low
rate toward its climb. Suddenly it took a left turn, went down
behind trees, struck a building and exploded into flames,'' he said.
   Authorities said witnesses indicated the engine of the aircraft
was running, but appeared to be developing little power.
   Investigators of the National Transporation Safety Board went to
the site about 25 miles southwest of Chicago to determine the cause
of the accident.
   A spokeswoman for the Will County Coroner's office, who refused
to identify herself, said it was unlikely the bodies would be
identified before Saturday.
   The plane crashed into the Walco Tool and Engineering Co.
building where about 50 people were working. One of the injured
workers was treated and released. The second, Dwayne Tieman, 26, of
Lockport, was in serious condition at Loyola University Medical
Center with burns.
