<SECOND>AM-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0777,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama's Defense Forces Reject Pressure About Noriega</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: FIXES typo in 2nd graf; pickup 3rd graf, `Panama today...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military, run by Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega, told the United States and Organization of American
States once again Friday that pressure to remove him as Panama's de
facto ruler will not succeed.
   The rejection was contained in a statement read at a ceremony
marking the bicentennial of the French revolution.
   ``Panama today, like France did yesterday, is struggling
stoically against aggression, intolerance and lack of
understanding,'' it said. ``Our objectives are sovereignty and
self-determination, the right to choose and decide what we want,
when we want it and who we want it with.
   ``We take advantage of this revolutionary celebration to exhort
all those living in this isthmus to end the fight between brothers
and ... join in peace and national concord, which should be our
permanent crusade.''
   Also Friday, OAS mediators began another round of talks with
Panamanian government and opposition leaders, and Bernard Aronson,
new U.S. assistant undersecretary of state for inter-American
affairs, discussed regional issues with Central American leaders.
   Capt. Lim Yueng, spokesman for the Panama Defense Forces, read
the statement at the ceremony in the French Cemetery by the Panama
Canal. The ceremony also honored Frenchmen and people of other
nationalities who died building the waterway 74 years ago.
   Among those present was Arnold Small, 99, one of the few
surviving canal construction workers.
   Friday's statement was one of several rejections by the Defense
Forces of Noriega's removal. The OAS mission was appointed after
Noriega annulled the May 7 presidential elections, which
international observers said opposition candidates won by a 3-1
margin.
   The OAS has been trying to arrange three-way talks among the
Defense Forces, government parties and opposition leaders to resolve
the political crisis.
   Noriega was indicted by federal grand juries in Florida in
February 1988 on charges of drug trafficking and money laundering.
U.S. pressure to get him out has included freezing Panamanian assets
in American banks and other economic sanctions.
   Aronson is consulting with the presidents of Guatemala, Honduras,
El Salvador and Costa Rica on the Panamanian situation and
Nicaragua's plans for national elections Feb. 25.
   He met President Jose Azcona Hoyo of Honduras in Tegucigalpa on
Friday.
   In Managua, Vice President Sergio Ramirez of Nicaragua said he
had met with Noriega in Panama this week about a Panamanian proposal
for breaking the political deadlock.
   Ramirez said it involved ``organizing as of September a
government of national unity with opposition participation, a
government that will be in charge of preparing new elections.''
   ``We are interested that the situation in Panama finds a way out
... because Panama affects the entire Central American region,'' he
told reporters.
</TEXT>
