<FIRST>r e BC-MostlyMozart     07-14 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mostly Mozart,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Perlman and Kalichstein Play at Mostly Mozart</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Violinist Itzhak Perlman kicked off this summer's
Mostly Mozart Festival at Lincoln Center.
   He played two violin concerti, by Mozart and Bach, on opening
night with the festival's orchestra and conductor Gerard Schwarz.
They repeated the program the second night, Tuesday, which was
televised.
   And on Wednesday the audience at Avery Fisher Hall heard even
more of Perlman when he and pianist Joseph Kalichstein played four
sonatas for violin and piano. This third Mostly Mozart evening was
Entirely Mozart and wonderful.
   Kalichstein often plays chamber music with violinist Jaime Laredo
and cellist Sharon Robinson and is known for playig 19th century
music.
   Kalichstein sounded like a Mozart specialist on Wednesday. His
chords were clean. Both played with dazzling timing. When the two
instruments held a dialogue or echoed each other, the timing was
perfect.
   The beautiful tone, and varieties of tone, that Perlman gets from
the violin is well known. Kalichstein's tone also is splendid and he
wasn't afraid to create enough volume occasionally to swamp the
violin. Neither created a thin sound. They proved that sound can be
both lush and appropriately contained.
   The sonatas played were ``G major,'' for which the composer
played violin at the 1781 premiere, ``D major'' and ``E minor'' from
1778 and ``A major'' from 1787.
   While fast passages, especially the last movement of the ``A
major,'' which Mozart composed four years before he died, showed the
two musicians' virtuosity most excitingly, we most enjoyed the
andante movements with their beautiful melodies.
   And in Perlman and Kalichstein, the Mostly Mozart Festival found
the men to reach and calm the listener's soul in playing them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
