<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian company rumored to be trying to corner
the soybean market has asked a federal judge to block a Chicago
Board of Trade order that would force it to sell a huge quantity of
soybean futures.
   The lawsuit filed Thursday by Ferruzzi Trading International SA
and Ferruzzi USA Inc., both subsidiaries of Ferruzzi Finanziara SpA,
seeks a temporary restraining order and a permanent injunction
against the exchange's directive.
   The suit claims Ferruzzi had been irreparably injured by the
Board of Trade's order and says the directive would diminish
confidence in the market and hurt U.S. farmers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BAT Industries PLC has abandoned a $400 million
note issue because of what it called market disruption caused by a
hostile $21 billion takeover bid from an investor group led by Sir
James Goldsmith.
   The issue, set for completion Monday, would have been one of the
biggest Eurobond offerings ever by a non-U.S. company. The
London-based conglomerate said it withdrew the issue Thursday to
protect investors against substantial possible losses from ``the
hostile and highly leveraged nature of the bid.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House-Senate conference trying to craft a
savings and loan bailout bill deadlocked in procedural limbo after
Senate negotiators proposed a comprehensive compromise.
   The leader of the five-member Senate team suprised many House
members Thursday by delivering an outline of the Senate proposal and
asking them to consider it overnight.
   But the 94-member House delegation has been unable to respond
because its leader has divided the delegation into platoons of 20 or
30 members, each with jurisdiction over part of the bill. House
delegates voted to put the Senate offer aside and proceeded to try
to tackle the massive S&amp;L bill issue by issue.
</TEXT>
