<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 0712EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ComputerConference     07-14 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Computer Conference,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conference Kicks Off 2-Year Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As much as 10 percent of the world's gross
national product may be spent on computers and computer-related
equipment by the year 2000, says the chairman of a House
telecommunications subcommittee.
   Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., said Thursday at a Capitol Hill
conference launching a two-year project by the Congressional
Institute for the Future that computers will become an integral part
of human life.
   ``Retail products, financial services, health care, basic
research and development, basic education, worker retraining and
even prison security _ all of these areas of service could be
revolutionized by coming changes in information industries,'' said
Markey, chairman of the Energy and Commerce subcommittee on
telecommunications and finance.
   The project, ``Challenging the Information Age,'' is being
undertaken by the non-profit educational organization that involves
members of Congress, industry executives and other private-sector
policy leaders.
   Thursday's conference included demonstrations of high-tech
products, including a supercomputer, interactive videodisc systems
for storage and rapid retrieval of massive amounts of data, and
electronic networks to provide information to schools and
individuals.
   ``The future implications of issues and choices to be examined by
the institute's information age project are enormous,'' Markey said.
``Forecasters suggest that in the year 2000, 8 to 10 percent of the
world's GNP will be expended on telecommunications products and
hardware.''
   Markey said industrialized nations, including Japan and West
Germany, will battle for the lion's share of the market. Japan, he
said, already is predicting that telecommunications products soon
will make up a fifth of its GNP.
</TEXT>
