<DOCNO> AP890714-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 0713EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-WallStreetRebound Bjt   07-14 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Rebound, Bjt,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brokerages Expected To Post Strong Quarter As Retail Activity Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Declining interest rates and increased stock
activity have boosted activity at Wall Street's investment houses,
which have struggled in an industrywide recession that has included
layoffs and restructuring.
   Much of the renewed optimism, which should be reflected in
improved second-quarter profits at major brokerages, is based on a
return of individual investors to a stock market tarnished by the
October 1987 crash.
   ``We see much more interest in individual securities, whether
stocks or bonds, which obviously would bode well for the industry,''
John Markese, research director for the 110,000-member American
Association of Individual Investors in Chicago, said Thursday.
   A rise in June in merger activity and in fees generated by
underwriting new issues of stocks and bonds _ two key indicators of
Wall Street's health _ should lift industry profits compared with
the first quarter, when some firms lost money, analysts said.
   ``Without a doubt it's going to be one of the better quarters for
the industry,'' said Brenda Davis McCoy, an analyst with PaineWebber
Inc.
   Salomon Inc., parent of Salomon Bros., earlier this week
announced that its second-quarter earnings would be the company's
best ever, exceeding the $190 million earned in the first quarter of
1986.
   John H. Gutfreund, Salomon's chairman and chief executive, said
the first half of 1989 for the firm would be ``only modestly below''
that of first-half 1988, when it made $253 million, or $1.68 a
share, on revenue of $3.04 billion.
   Earnings forecasts for other firms also are optimistic: 40 cents
to 50 cents a share for Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., compared with 31 cents
a share in the first quarter; $2.60 a share for Morgan Stanley Group
Inc., up from $2.02 for January to March; and about 50 cents a share
for Shearson Lehman Hutton Holdings Inc. after nine months of losses.
   But analysts caution that profit levels aren't even close to the
boom times that preceded the stock market crash and say many of the
factors that led to thousands of layoffs and retrenchment on Wall
Street remain.
   ``You can't just throw up your hands and say we've turned,'' said
Lawrence Eckenfelder, a securities industry analyst with Prudential
Bache Securities Inc. ``We may still be in a recession three months
from now on the Street.''
   The expected improved results are being attributed to a steady
decline in short-term interest rates that has prompted some
investors to transfer money from money market funds and bank
certificates of deposit to investments with higher returns,
generating more trading profit for the firms.
   For instance, the Treasury's one-year bill had a yield of 8.10
percent at the end of June compared with 9.58 percent at the end of
March. Some money market interest rates, which fetched over 10
percent earlier this year, recently dipped below 8 percent.
   Declining interest rates mean investment banks pay less to borrow
money to finance inventories of fixed-income securities. Also,
brokerages typically receive much higher commissions on investment
vehicles other than CDs and money markets, including retail trades.
   Higher stock trading volume also means more commission business.
The NYSE's average daily volume in June was 180.3 million, the
highest in a year and third-highest in any month since October 1987.
   Merger and acquisitions and securities underwriting activity both
jumped in June, providing additional fuel to the strong quarter,
statistics show.
   The total value of announced acquisitions in June was $37.7
billion, the second-best month this year, according to Securities
Data Co., which tracks industry data. Analysts forecast a continued
rise in merger activity if interest rates stay down.
   Fees generated from initial public offerings of stock _
considered a sign of companies' confidence in whether investors are
buying stock _ totaled $1.63 billion in June, up from $261 million
in April, Securities Data reported.
   But the industry isn't in clover yet.
   ``I don't think the public is yet of the psychology or philosophy
that they are going to miss something big and are ready to jump into
the stock market,'' said Jack Barbanel, a senior vice president of
Gruntal &amp; Co., a midsized Manhattan investment firm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890714-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 0555EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Britain-BAT Bjt   07-14 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-BAT, Bjt,0696</SECOND>
<HEAD>BAT War Underscores American Dominance of Takeover Battles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The takeover battle for tobacco-retailing giant BAT
Industries PLC is developing into a U.S.-style fight, underscoring
the American dominance of the worldwide corporate buyout scene.
   The hostile, $21 billion offer from an investor group led by
Anglo-French financier Sir James Goldsmith certainly is
American-sized.
   It would be the second-largest takeover in the world after the
record $25 billion purchase of U.S.-based RJR Nabisco Inc. by the
New York investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. earlier this
year. It would be four times the size of the previous biggest
British bid.
   The bidders offer no cash and instead are using an American
financing technique not readily accepted on this side of the
Atlantic: junk bonds.
   Both sides have lined up U.S. soldiers: leading American
investment bankers. In addition, many of the battles are expected to
take place on U.S. soil: in American courts and before U.S.
insurance regulators, due to BAT's ownership of American insurance
companies.
   ``If you're sitting there as an aggressor trying to figure out
what the defensive strategy would be, you would figure they would
use American advisers and you would try to cut them off at the pass
and get the best ones,'' said Clive Sherling, a director of the
London buyout firm Alan Patricof Associates Ltd.
   London-based BAT, a diversified conglomerate, has wide-ranging
interests in the United States. It owns Brown and Williamson Tobacco
Corp., Farmers Insurance Group Inc. and the Saks Fifth Avenue and
Marshall Field's department stores.
   Forty-one percent of BAT's pre-tax profit and 30 percent of its
revenue came from North America last year.
   The bidding group, which includes British investor Jacob
Rothschild and Kerry Packer, an Australian entrepreneur, launched
the bid Tuesday through a newly formed company, Hoylake Investments
PLC. BAT immediately rejected it.
   On Thursday, BAT said it dropped a planned $400 million note
issue, which was to have been completed Monday. It would have been
one of the biggest Eurobond offerings ever by a non-American company.
   ``The issue has been withdrawn following the disruption of the
market for these securities as a result of the Hoylake bid,'' BAT
said in a statement.
   It said it wanted to protect investors, who it said would have
faced substantial losses because of ``the hostile and highly
leveraged nature of the bid.''
   ``Now that BAT is under siege,'' said Kevin Phillips, an analyst
with the London investment firm Kleinwort Benson Ltd., ``they are
merely taking a prudent route.''
   BAT's shares fell 15 pence, or about 24 cents, to finish at 862
pence, or $14.05, Thursday on London's Stock Exchange. The bidding
group's offering price is 850 pence, or $13.86 a share.
   Junk bonds, such as the ones the Goldsmith group is offering, are
not as widely used or accepted in Britain, where high-debt ventures
are less common. Junk bonds are high-yield, high-risk securities.
   Also new to the relatively staid British takeover scene would be
the breakup of such a large company. Goldsmith said he wanted to
``unbundle'' BAT by selling its non-tobacco interests.
   In the BAT war, the offense has lined up U.S. junk bond pioneers
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and Bankers Trust Co.'s financing pros.
Its legal advisers include Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher and Flom, a
U.S. law firm on the takeover forefront.
   The defense quickly enlisted Goldman Sachs and Co. and Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. to help Lazard Brothers and Co. plot its
strategy. All three are American brokerages.
   American investment firms, which are particularly aggressive,
have been leaders in developing sophisticated takeover and
anti-takeover techniques.
   BAT's defense likely would be a management buyout, said Sherling.
``I'm sure that it would be led from the States and therefore by
having American advisers they would have a more direct line to the
cash.''
   Of course, Americans don't have the lock on the takeover market.
Both sides' armies include powerful British firms. BAT has S.G.
Warburg and Co. The bidders have James Capel and Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890714-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 0825EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CM&amp;WBailout     07-14 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CM&amp;W Bailout,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects Bank Motion to Close Railroad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge has rejected a
creditor's motion to close the financially troubled Chicago,
Missouri and Western Railway.
   The motion by Citicorp North America and Heller Financial Inc.
was denied Thursday on procedural grounds by U.S. Bankruptcy Court
Judge John D. Schwartz, said Daniel Murray, the court-appointed
trustee for CM&amp;W.
   In their motion, the creditors had sought to close the CM&amp;W on
the grounds that it is continuing to lose money and has no
reasonable prospects of reorganization.
   Last Friday, though, Murray announced that the New York
investment firm of Wertheim Schroder &amp; Co. had agreed to buy the
CM&amp;W for $35 million and assume the loans it had taken from the
state.
   The deal, which should be closed in September, is going ahead,
Murray said Thursday.
   Neal Wolf, attorney for Citicorp and Heller, said the creditors
were considering ``a variety of alternatives'' in response to
Schwartz's ruling, but he would not elaborate.
   He did say, however, that the creditors were opposed to the deal
with Wertheim Schroder as it now stands.
   Schwartz also ruled Thursday that the railroad may continue to
use revenues until Aug. 31 to pay for operations, and that CM&amp;W may
draw more loans from the Illinois Development Finance Authority,
Murray said.
   Wolf said the creditors planned to appeal the latter decision.
   CM&amp;W operates along 632 miles of track between Kansas City and
Joliet, Ill., and carries Amtrak passenger trains between Chicago
and St. Louis.
   The railroad filed for reorganization under federal bankruptcy
laws in April 1988.
</TEXT>
