<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 0827EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BCBritain-Inflation     07-14 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>BCBritain-Inflation,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Annual Rate Holds Steady at 8.3 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain'a annual inflation rate held steady at 8.3
percent in June, and may have reached its peak, the government
announced Friday.
   Britain's retail price index rose 0.3 percent in June from May,
the Department of Employment said Friday. Market forecasts had
called for a 0.5 percent gain.
   The index, which uses a January 1987 base of 100, stood at 115.4
in June, compared with 115 in May and 106.6 in June 1988.
   ``Inflation may now have reached its peak,'' said Employment
Secretary Norman Fowler. ``It is set to fall as the measures taken
by the chancellor begin to work through.''
   Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson has pushed up interest
rates 10 times _ to 14 percent from 7.5 percent a year ago _ in an
effort to combat Britain's resurgent inflation. The annual inflation
rate stood at 4.6 percent in June 1988.
   If mortgage interest payments were excluded, the latest inflation
rate would have been 5.9 percent in June, Folower said, This
compared with May's 6-percent rate, excluding such payments.
   The June rise in the index reflected higher prices for food,
catering, alcoholic drinks and motor vehicles, the department said.
The increase also reflected a continuing rise in housing costs, it
said.
</TEXT>
