<FIRST>u f PM-Autorecall     07-14 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto recall,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM Recalls Nearly 1.8 Million Large Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. has recalled nearly 1.8
million of its full-sized and luxury cars because of a problem with
an automatic cruise control that could hold the throttle partly
open, hampering a driver's effort to slow down.
   The automaker took the action Thursday after the National Highway
Traffic and Safety Administration last March began a formal
investigation into the problem which could have led to a
government-ordered recall.
   GM and NHTSA said the problem is not related to so-called
``sudden acceleration,'' which some had alleged was linked to cruise
control mechanisms.
   Nineteen models built between 1984 and 1988 are involved in the
recall.
   They include 1.73 million cars with 5-liter gasoline engines and
about 18,000 cars with 4.3- and 5.7-liter diesel engines with Cruise
Control III systems.
   NHTSA said it has received 354 complaints from owners of the
vehicles, including 28 crashes and 13 injuries allegedly resulting
from the problem. GM said it was not aware of any accidents or
injuries as a result of the problem.
   ``There may be an honest difference of opinion regarding what is
the potential problem,'' said GM spokesman Tom Pyden, ``but we are
cooperating fully with NHTSA and we're moving forward to address our
customer needs.''
   GM and the agency said the problem stems from a small plastic
ring which can slip out of place, causing the throttle to remain
partially open while at highway speeds, making it difficult for the
driver to slow down.
   Owners will be notified by mail and repairs will be performed at
no cost to the customer.
   Models included in the recall are:
   _Oldsmobile Delta 88, 98 Regency, Custom Cruiser, Cutlass Supreme
and Toronado.
   _Buick LeSabre, Electra Park Avenue, Estate Wagon, Rivera and
Regal.
   _Pontiac Bonneville G, Parisienne and Grand Prix.
   _Chevrolet Caprice and Monte Carlo.
   _Cadillac Brougham, El Dorado and Seville.
</TEXT>
