<FIRST>r f PM-MexicanDebt 1stLd-Writethru f0019 07-14 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexican Debt, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0019,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede NEW YORK</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Administration Offers Mexico Temporary Loan</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: New thruout to UPDATE with Sununu comment; No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration has offered Mexico a
temporary loan of $1 billion to $2 billion to help bring to a close
an agreement with U.S. banks on debt restructuring, U.S. officials
said today.
   White House Chief of Staff John Sununu said Mexican and bank
negotiators were ``very close'' on terms for an agreement. The loan
is contingent on an accord between the country and its creditors to
reduce and rearrange $54 billion in existing loans.
   However, some outstanding issues remain and no deal is in sight,
Sununu said.
   ``The quality of the solution is more important than the
timetable,'' the White House official told reporters a few hours
before the opening of the economic summit here.
   According to Sununu, Mexican officials want to ``get it done
correctly rather than trying to rush it.''
   The New York Times reported in today's editions that the United
States sought to sweeten such a deal between Mexico and the banks by
providing a so-called bridge loan.
   ``We are ready to do that if it is what is necessary in order to
complete the agreement ...,'' Sununu said in confirming the report.
   President Bush met this morning with with Mexican President
Carlos Salinas de Gortari. The two are attending the 200th
anniversary celebration of the French Revolution.
   Such loans are sometimes used to assist a country hampered by
paperwork delays following debtor loan negotiations with foreign
bank creditors. More than half of Mexico's total foreign debt is
owed to commercial banks, many of them in the United States.
   The Mexican government has said it would want to reach such an
agreement before accepting new loans. The United States has
indicated it would like to wrap up an accord as soon as possible, a
sign to the other summit nations that it has adopted a new approach
on the debt.
   Sununu stressed that ``there is no requirement to leave the
summit ... with an agreement'' and that an artificial deadline might
hurt the quality of the final agreement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
