<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-14 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Dip Following Ferruzzi Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices fell in early trading today
on the Chicago Board of Trade following a federal court ruling
upholding an exchange order requiring traders to reduce their
holdings in the July soybean contract.
   Other grain futures markets showed no clear direction.
   Two subsidiaries of the Italian agribusiness firm Ferruzzi
Finanziara SpA filed a lawsuit Thursday seeking to block the Board
of Trade's emergency order, which Ferruzzi claimed was aimed at
weakening its market position.
   Ferruzzi has denied it tried to corner the soybean market.
   The Board of Trade said it issued the directive Tuesday to ensure
an orderly expiration of the July contract, which goes off the board
next Thursday. The exchange said that without the forced liquidation
of positions, there might not have been enough deliverable soybeans
to satisfy all the July contracts.
   U.S. District Judge James Zagel denied Ferruzzi's request to
block the order, saying the potential harm to public confidence in
the Board of Trade would surpass any monetary loss by Ferruzzi.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent lower to } cent higher with
the contract for delivery in July at $3.91{ a bushel; corn was
unchanged to \ cent lower with July at $2.56\ a bushel; oats were
unchanged to { cent higher with July at $1.48\ a bushel; soybeans
were 1} cents to 7{ cents lower with July at $6.90 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were stronger in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent lower to .13 cent higher with August at
71.97 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .10 cent
higher with August at 82.95 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent
to .45 cent higher with July at 47.32 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were unchanged to .45 cent higher with July at 29.40 cents a
pound.
   Cattle futures settled higher on Thursday while pork futures were
mixed.
</TEXT>
