<FIRST>r f BC-FirstCity-Bids     07-14 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-First City-Bids,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>First City Bows Out Of TAB-NBC Bidding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First City Bancorp. of Texas says it has withdrawn
its bid to purchase the state's two largest remaining ailing banks.
   Instead, the Houston-based bank holding company said it would
concentrate on efforts to buy out the 18 percent interest the
federal government still holds in First City.
   First City, itself the recipient last year of $1 billion in
federal aid, was one of a group of bidders for Fort Worth-based
Texas American Bancshares Inc. and San Antonio's National Bancshares
Corp. of Texas, which together have about $7 billion in assets.
   In addition, First City had sought the 20 failed former MCorp
banks which were awarded to Banc One Corp. of Columbus, Ohio, late
last month.
   Regulators said at the time that any bank that had received
federal assistance would be at a disadvantage in buying other banks.
   Last week First City said it was seeking ways to buy out the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.'s 18 percent interest, estimated by
some analysts at about $70 million.
   First City spokesman Jim Day said Thursday bowing out of the
Texas American and National Bancshares bidding ``may speed our
negotiations with the FDIC on its ownership stake.''
   Known bidders remaining in the bidding for the two banks include
Security Pacific Corp. of Los Angeles; a partnership of Norwest
Corp. and investor Carl Pohlad; Ronald Steinhart, head of
Dallas-based TexOp Bancshares Inc.; and Equimark Corp. of Pittsburgh.
</TEXT>
