<FIRST>r f PM-Chrysler-Repossessions     07-14 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chrysler-Repossessions,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Class-action Suit Filed, Alleging Owners Not Given Adequate Warnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Credit Corp. employees violated
state law by repossessing up to 1,300 cars and trucks without giving
owners adequate warning that they missed their payments, a lawsuit
contends.
   The class-action lawsuit filed by the state consumer advocate
charges that Chrysler Credit Corp. employees ignored a state law
that requires written notice explaining to a car or truck owner that
he has a 20-day grace period to make good on a missed payment before
the vehicle is repossessed.
   Vehicles were sometimes repossessed with little more than a
telephone call to warn owners that they missed payments, state
Consumer Advocate Steve Hamm said in his suit filed Thursday in
Richland County Circuit Court.
   The suit also alleges that employees of the Detroit-based finance
company deliberately flouted the consumer-protection law and
sometimes faked office records to make it appear that they had not.
   Hamm said it appeared that the consumer-protection law was
skirted so employees could cut down on paperwork.
   Chrysler Credit is investigating the allegations and will
cooperate, a spokesman said.
   Chrysler spokesman Bob Heath said the company contacted Hamm's
office after an employee in South Carolina complained in May about
the way some repossessions were being handled.
   The lawsuit asks that a judge forbid Chrysler Credit's South
Carolina employees from continuing to break the consumer-protection
law, even though Heath said the company has stopped the violations.
   The lawsuit also seeks some kind of ``adjustment'' for the owners
of the 1,200 to 1,300 vehicles that Hamm claims were illegally
repossessed over the last five or six years. Hamm said he did not
know what form the ``adjustment'' would take.
   Chrysler Credit will ``do whatever we have to do to try to reach
a fair and equitable settlement,'' Heath said.
   Chrysler Credit has offices in Richland, Greenville and
Charleston counties, but Hamm and Heath said the problems were
centered in the Columbia office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
