<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1320EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-US-EuropePork     07-14 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Europe Pork,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. to Lift Punitive Fee on European Hams</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is lifting its punitive 100
percent tariff on bone-in hams from the 12 European Economic
Community nations because they have allowed the shipment of some
U.S. meat not treated with hormones, U.S. Trade Representative Carla
Hills said Friday.
   The amount involved is small _ the Europeans have been shipping
only about $300,000 worth of the hams annually _ but it is an easing
of a conflict between the United States and the community over
hormones in meat.
   The move followed the acceptance by the community of a small
quantity of veal offals (variety meats) from the United States.
   ``We continue to believe that the EC's ban on meat produced with
hormones is entirely unjustified,'' Ms. Hills said in a statement.
   The community banned from Jan. 1 the sale of meat from animals
treated with hormones to fatten them. In retaliation, the Reagan
administration imposed an extra 100 percent tariff on European
shipments to the United States of products with a value roughly
equivalent to the U.S. meat exports halted by the ban. One of the
products was bone-in ham.
   A joint European-American task force agreed in May on shipping
U.S. meat not treated with hormones, and to reduce U.S. retaliation
to the extent that American meat could be sold.
</TEXT>
