<FIRST>u f PM-RetailSales 1stLd-Writethru f0036 07-14 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retail Sales, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0036,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retail Sales Plummet in June</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To reflect Commerce Department CORRECTION, make lead read first
monthly back-to-back drop in nearly two years, and change 3rd graf to read
first consecutive monthly decline since 1987.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales fell 0.4 percent in June _ their
first monthly back-to-back drop in nearly two years _ as consumer
spending remained sluggish, particularly for cars and other more
costly durable goods, the government reported today.
   The Commerce Department said sales dropped to a seasonally
adjusted $140.8 billion last month following a 0.1 percent decline
in May. The May figure was revised downward from an 0.1 percent
increase originally reported last month. Sales had risen 0.4 percent
in April and 0.1 percent in March.
   It was the first consecutive monthly decline since 1987 when
sales fell 0.8 percent in September and 0.9 percent in October.
   Retail spending accounts for about one-third of economic activity
and is closely watched as a measure of the overall economy. Economic
growth has been slowing recently, prompting concern that Federal
Reserve efforts to contain inflation could move the economy into a
recession instead of the ``soft-landing'' it seeks.
   Spending on durable goods _ big ticket items such as cars and
home appliances that are expected to last more than three years _
has been particularly affected by the Fed's credit-tightening
measures.
   The Commerce Department said durable goods sales were off 1.3
percent in June after falling 0.5 percent in May and rising 1.8
percent in April.
   Auto sales plummeted 2.0 percent in June after falling 1.8
percent in May. It was the biggest drop in auto sales since a 4
percent decline in October 1987. Sales had risen 2.0 percent in
April _ a month of large dealer incentives.
   Autos represent about 20 percent of total retail sales.
   Excluding the automotive category, overall retail sales rose 0.1
percent, following hikes of 0.4 percent in May and 1.2 percent in
April.
   Sales of home furnishings fell 0.1 percent after rising 1.1
percent in May.
   Sales of non-durable goods rose 0.2 percent last month, the same
increase as in May. They had risen 0.6 percent in April.
   Department store and other general merchandise spending was up
2.1 percent.
   Also showing increased sales in the non-durable category was
apparel sales, up 1.9 percent.
   Non-durable categories posting declines included: food stores,
down 0.7 percent; gasoline stations, down 0.5 percent; restaurants
and bars, down 0.2 percent and drug stores, off 0.3 percent.
   For the three months from April through June, overall retail
sales were up 5.3 percent from the same period in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890714-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1324EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-SoybeanCorner 2ndLd-Writethru   07-14 0824</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soybean Corner, 2nd Ld-Writethru,f0059,0846</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ferruzzi Says It Will Sue CBOT to Recover Damages</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 new grafs with Ferruzzi saying it will sue to recover
losses due to liquidation order. Picks up 4th graf pvs: ``U.S. District
...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian agribusiness firm said today it will go
to court to recover losses resulting from an order by the Chicago
Board of Trade forcing soybean traders from holding positions
potentially large enough to corner the market.
   Raul Gardini, chairman of Ferruzzi Finanzaria SpA, made the
announcement in Milan. He reiterated the company's position that the
accumulation of soybean contracts was legal, adding, ``Ferruzzi and
all major world traders are convinced that the board made a mistake
and has to suffer the consequences.''
   Ferruzzi didn't specify the amount of losses suffered as a result
of the board's order.
   But it said damages could be calculated in part as the difference
between the closing market price of $7.26 a bushel on Tuesday, when
the CBOT issued its order, and the price during the days through
July 20, when all soybean traders must reduce their holdings to a
maximum 1 million bushels.
   A spokesman said the suit probably would be filed in Chicago, but
did not give a timetable. The company also indicated it might seek
compensation for unrealized profits as well as damage to its
reputation.
   One day earlier, a federal judge denied a request by two Ferruzzi
subsidiaries _ Ferruzzi Trading International SA and Ferruzzi USA
Inc. _ for a restraining order and a permanent injunction ending the
BOT's directive.
   Published reports have said the Ferruzzi was the object of the
directive.
   U.S. District Judge James Zagel on Thursday denied the injunction
request, saying the harm to public confidence in the Board of Trade
from the injunction would surpass any monetary loss by Ferruzzi.
   ``If I grant a temporary restraining order in this case and it
turns out to be a mistake, (then) a possible default in the market,
a loss of confidence in the market could be a consequence,'' Zagel
said.
   CBOT Karsten Mahlmann said Zagel's decision ``reaffirms that the
Board of Trade has the authority to ensure the orderliness of the
market and to effect the orderly liquidation of the July soybean
contract.''
   Soybean futures prices fell in early trading today in reaction to
Zagel's ruling. The July contract opened at $6.90 a bushel, 7{ cents
below Thursday's settlement price.
   On Tuesday, the Board of Trade, the world's largest market for
grain and soybean futures, issued an emergency order requiring any
player holding obligations to receive or deliver more than 3 million
bushels of soybeans for July delivery to reduce those holdings to 1
million bushels by the end of trading next Thursday, when the July
contract expires.
   In issuing the order, the exchange cited federal regulations that
allow it to take such action to ensure the orderly expiration of a
futures contract.
   Ferruzzi's lawsuit claimed it had been irreparably injured by the
order, which it said would diminish confidence in the market and
hurt U.S. farmers.
   In arguments before Zagel, Ferruzzi lawyer James Fox said the
Board of Trade acted ``arbitrarily and capriciously'' and in bad
faith when it issued the order.
   Fox noted that the exchange ignored the fact that the market has
been trading in a very narrow range in recent weeks, an indication
that there was no squeeze or cornering of the market.
   John E. Angle, an attorney for the CBOT, argued that there ``is
absolutely nothing in the record to show this action resulted from
bad faith tantamount to fraud on the part of the CBOT.''
   Angle said Ferruzzi could appeal the emergency order to the
Commodity Futures Trading Commission, which regulates the CBOT.
   Although he refused to grant an injunction, Zagel said the CBOT's
action may not have been totally defensible. He said Ferruzzi could
sue and be adequately compensated for any loss in monetary damages
if it proves its case.
   Fox, said he did not know whether the Italian firm would pursue
the lawsuit or seek monetary damages. Zagel told attorneys for the
CBOT to file a motion to dismiss the lawsuit by Tuesday, with a
response due July 24.
   During the hearing before Zagel, Fox said the emergency order
forced the Italian firm to reduce its holdings of July soybean
contracts by 20 percent on Wednesday and another 20 percent Thursday.
   In related developments, the American Soybean Association called
for an investigation of the Board of Trade's directive and the
Minnesota agriculture commissioner asked the FBI to check whether
Board of Trade officials may have benefited from the effects of the
order.
   Soybean futures gained Thursday on news that Ferruzzi had
requested the restraining order, with the July contract closing up
10 cents at $6.96 a bushel. The market closed at $7.26 a bushel
Tuesday before the CBOT liquidation order took effect.
</TEXT>
