<DOCNO> AP890714-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1500EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Britain-BAT Bjt   07-14 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-BAT, Bjt,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>BAT Offer Pulls London's Stock Market Out of The Doldrums</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hostile $21 billion bid for BAT Industries PLC
has pulled London's stock market out of its recent doldrums by
sparking speculation about which companies might be the next targets
of takeovers.
   Share prices have jumped to post-crash highs and trading volume
has soared on the London Stock Exchange as investors have scrambled
to place their bets.
   ``You've got bid fever,'' said Jeffrey Thompson, chief equity
strategist at the London investment firm Barclays de Zoete Wedd Ltd.
The market is ``sizing up every possible target however remote, and
taking it higher.''
   But analysts said the euphoria could be short-lived.
   Still, the activity was raising hopes that business in general
would pick up in the City of London, the financial district,
bringing in more fees and commissions. Investment firms have been
feeling the squeeze since the October 1987 stock market crash and
following the so-called Big Bang deregulation of Britain's financial
markets nearly three years ago.
   No one, however, was saying that this sudden takeover speculation
was going to be the City's cure-all.
   ``All the stockbroking houses have tremendous cost problems. It's
going to take more of a surge than we've seen to overcome them,''
said an analyst who did not want to be identified.
   ``Competition is pretty fierce,'' she said, ``You will have to
have some people drop out.''
   Martin Hughes, a banking analyst with the London investment firm
Laing and Cruickshank, said the excitement ``delays a clean-out of
the City.''
   On Friday, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
gained 15.7 points, or 0.7 percent, to finish at 2,273.7, a
post-crash high. The index has risen 78.5 points, or 3.6 percent,
since the market closed on Monday, the day before the bid for BAT
Industries was announced.
   Volume amounted to a healthy 771.8 million shares on Friday. By
comparison, June's average daily volume was 410 million shares.
   The hostile bid for the diversified British conglomerate was made
by an investment group made up of Anglo-French financier Sir James
Goldsmith, British merchant banker Jacob Rothschild and Australian
entrepreneur Kerry Packer. They want to break up BAT and sell off
its non-tobacco interests: financial services, retailing and paper.
   Suddenly anything was possible on this side of the Atlantic and
the City buzzed with names of other potential targets.
   They included:
   _Cadbury Schweppes PLC, the confectionery and soft drinks group
   _Trafalgar House PLC, a shipping group
   _Allied-Lyons PLC, the liquor company
   _Hotel operator Trusthouse Forte PLC
   _Sears PLC, a retailer not related to the similarly named U.S.
company
   _Grand Metropolitan PLC, a liquor, foods and retailing company.
   London's market has been languishing since the stock market
crash, plagued by weak prices and low trading volume. It has not
recovered from the crash as well as the other major markets.
   British and foreign investment firms, which had geared up so
eagerly for Big Bang, have found it extremely difficult to make
profits. Commissions have declined because of the larger number of
players vying for shrinking business.
   Firms have withdrawn from certain activities, like making markets
in stocks and bonds, which had been opened up to them under Big
Bang. They also have sought to cut their costs by cutting back staff
and salaries.
   Thompson said that despite the pickup in recent activity, ``We
retain our cautious stance on the market.''
   ``The nature of bid activity is that once that the action and the
excitement is out of the way, the market tends to sag back,'' he
said. ``Certain stocks are vulnerable in the shorter-term unless
another megabid appears in the next few weeks to keep the momentum
going.''
   The strategist added that profit-taking could accelerate, a
development that could depress prices.
</TEXT>
