<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   07-14 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Gain; Focus Shifts Back To Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed moderately
higher Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade on bullish weather
forecasts and indications of Soviet purchases of South American
soybean meal.
   Soybean traders shifted their attention back to supply-and-demand
factors after focusing for several days on an exchange order
requiring traders to reduce their holdings in the July soybean
contract.
   Soybean prices had fallen in early trading following a federal
court ruling upholding the exchange's emergency order, which was
issued Tuesday.
   Two subsidiaries of the Italian agribusiness firm Ferruzzi
Finanziara SpA were denied their request for an injunction blocking
the Board of Trade's order, which Ferruzzi claimed was aimed at
weakening its market position.
   By closing time, analysts said the market was reacting more to
forecasts for warmer temperatures and perhaps less rain than farmers
need in the Corn Belt.
   ``Overall, the market acted pretty well today and I think the
weather was more of a factor,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader
with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   At the close, wheat futures were 1 cent to 4\ cents higher with
the contract for delivery in July at $3.95 a bushel; corn was { cent
to 3\ cents higher with July at $2.59{ a bushel; oats were 1{ cents
to 2} cents higher with July at $1.50 a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent
to 12{ cents higher with July at $7.05 a bushel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
