<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1955EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-McDonald's-Pizza     07-14 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McDonald's-Pizza,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>McDonald's Tests Offering Pizza</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OWENSBORO, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The same people who brought you McNuggets
and McRibs are testing a new product _ ``McPizza.''
   McDonald's Corp., which operates the nation's largest fast-food
restaurant chain, will begin test marketing its 14-inch traditional
pizzas at four stores in Owensboro within about 60 days, a spokesman
said.
   A new McDonald's in Evansville, Ind., on Monday became the first
in the country to test the pizza, said Steve Cross, operations
manager for the company's Evansville market.
   The four stores in Owensboro are undergoing construction to
enlarge the kitchens to allow room for forced hot air ovens and
windows that let people watch the pizza being made.
   Many restaurants serve pizza in 30 minutes. McDonald's will serve
a pizza in five minutes, Cross said.
   The pizza will have a thin crust and come in four varieties _
cheese, pepperoni, sausage and deluxe. Employees will be trained to
make the pizzas in the restaurants.
   Melissa Oakley, spokeswoman at the company's headquarters in Oak
Brook, Ill., said it's too early to know whether pizza will become a
regular feature.
   ``McDonald's is excited with the idea of pizza,'' she said.
``It's a big business out there, and we're ready to get a piece of
that pie.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
