<FIRST>r f AM-Massachusetts-BondRating 1stLd-Writethru   07-14 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Massachusetts-Bond Rating, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0200,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Agency Cuts Massachusetts Credit Rating Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, Saying it ... to CORRECT to show temporary
tax hike only deals with fiscal 1989 and medicaid bills. Picks up 9th graf
pvs, Standard &amp; ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citing financial disarray in Massachusetts
government, a major bond rating agency cut the state's credit rating
Friday for the second time this year, a move that could add millions
to borrowing costs.
   The decision by Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. to downgrade
Massachusetts bonds from AA- to A represents a harsh assessment of
the fiscal policies of Gov. Michael S. Dukakis and the state
Legislature.
   ``The state's economy remains strong, while debt and fiscal
management display serious weaknesses,'' the agency said.
   ``The low state general obligation rating reflects S&amp;P's
continuing concern about the willingness of the state to adhere to
sound fiscal practices and timely financial decision making,'' it
added.
   Calls made to Dukakis' office were not immediately returned
Friday and a spokesman for state Administration and Finance
Secretary Edward Lashman said there would be no comment.
   Standard &amp; Poor's ratings are a measure of the risk associated
with buying the state's bonds. The lower the rating, the higher the
interest rate the state must offer investors to entice them to buy
Massachusetts bonds.
   The state treasurer's office estimates that the latest downgrade
will cost the commonwealth about $2 million in interest payments
over the next 12 months. But the combined cost of all the downgrades
this year will be at least $20 million, said Deputy State Treasurer
Cathy Sheppard.
   Massachusetts ended its last fiscal year on June 30 with a
deficit and unpaid Medicaid bills expected to total between $450
million and $500 million.
   Saying it was ``the worst thing I've ever had to do in my
political career,'' Dukakis on Thursday announced $491 million in
cuts from the state's current budget. At the same time, the
Legislature voted to raise the state income tax by 15 percent for 18
months to cover the deficit from the past fiscal year and pay old
Medicaid bills.
   Standard &amp; Poor's said it was assessing the viability of the
governor's budget package but was uncertain of the legislature's
response. Democratic leaders in the state House of Representatives
have said they will move to override the governor's veto of $210
million in state aid to cities and towns.
   ``With a number of issues still unresolved, such as the amount of
local aid and the tax package, S&amp;P again observes a lack of timely
financial decision making,'' the agency said.
   S&amp;P had previously downgraded Massachusetts bonds from AA to
AA-in early June. Moody's Investor Services, another major bond
rating agency, also cut its rating last month.
   S&amp;P's downgrading applies to $4.8 billion of Massachusetts
general obligation bonds and $1.4 billion in bonds issued by various
state agencies. In addition, $757 million of general obligation
notes and $710 million of various agencies' notes were lowered from
SP1+ to SP1.
</TEXT>
