<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1705EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     07-14 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Petroluem Prices Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures finished lower Friday in a light,
lackluster session with the heaviest selling in the gasoline trading
pits.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the August contract for West
Texas Intermediate, which rose 20 cents on Thursday, lost 3 cents to
settle at $20.32 per 42-gallon barrel. Most other contract months of
the benchmark U.S. grade of crude posted slightly bigger declines.
   Refined petroleum products traded on the exchange turned in
similar performances.
   The August contract for home heating oil slid 0.11 cent to 49.33
cents a gallon, after rising 0.50 cent on Thursday. Contracts for
delivery in more distant months settled with minor losses and gains.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for August delivery dropped 0.62 cent
to 56.84 a gallon, erasing much of the combined gain of 0.84 cent
over the previous two sessions. Smaller declines were posted by
other gas contract months.
   John H. O'Connell, an assistant vice president at Refco Inc.,
said there wasn't any overwhelmingly bearish news to account for the
downturn in prices.
   A report circulating in the market that Kuwait might not reduce
its oil production as much as previously indicated was the only
disturbing factor for oil traders, O'Connell said.
   Otherwise, he said, prices may have sagged in the absence of many
traders willing to support them with new buying before the weekend.
   ``It's Friday afternoon in July, there's not a lot of people
around,'' said O'Connell.
</TEXT>
