<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     07-14 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises Despite Bearish Economic Data</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede: LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained ground Friday against all major
currencies except the Canadian dollar in defiance of a slew of
statistics that indicated the economy is cooling off.
   Gold prices fell sharply. On the Commodity Exchange in New York,
gold bullion for current delivery fell $6.20 a troy ounce to
$370.80. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a bid of $370.50
for an ounce of bullion at 4 p.m. EDT, down from Thursday's late bid
of $375.50.
   Four sets of economic figures for June painted a picture of a
sluggish economy: producer prices fell 0.1 percent, retail sales
fell 0.4 percent, industrial production declined 0.2 percent, and
the nation's factories, utilities and mines operated at a seasonally
adjusted capacity of 83.5 percent, down from 83.8 percent in May.
   Typically such news would send the dollar lower on speculation
that the Federal Reserve would continue easing its hold on interest
rates. But dealers said the fact that the dollar didn't fall much
immediately after the figures were released encouraged players to
buy the currency.
   ``It's the old story of selling on the rumor and buying on the
fact,'' said Stephen Flanagan, a vice president at Manufacturers
Hanover Trust Co.
   Traders sold dollars throughout the week on the expectation that
the numbers would be weak. ``When they came out and they were weak,
everybody was looking to buy back dollars at the same time,''
Flanagan said.
   Trading was volatile and heavy, dealers said.
   Jack Barbanel, a senior vice president at Gruntal &amp; Co., noted
that the market had ``hidden expectations'' of more dramatic data.
He noted that further data due out next week, particuarly the
merchandise trade numbers for June, will ``create (additional)
trading opportunities,'' given the market's ``love affair with
numbers.''
   Statements coming out of the Paris meeting of the Group of Seven
industrialized nations also gave the dollar a boost. Comments that
the finance ministers are satisfied with the U.S. currency's current
level prompted traders to speculate that an even higher dollar might
be tolerated.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 139.50 Japanese yen, up 0.45 yen
from late Thursday. Later in London, the dollar traded higher at
140.40 yen. In New York, the dollar closed at 140.85 yen, up from
Thursday's 139.45 yen.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.6125 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.6240 late Thursday. In New
York, one pound cost $1.6050, less expensive than Thursday's $1.6205.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.9125 West German marks, up from
1.8885; 1.6515 Swiss francs, up from 1.6300; 6.4890 French francs,
up from 6.4085; 1,385.00 Italian lire, up from 1,369.50, and 1.1917
Canadian dollars, down from 1.1930.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.9030 West German marks, up from 1.8815; 1.6455 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6190; 6.4575 French francs, up from 6.3870; 2.1400
Dutch guilders, up from 2.1155; 1,378.50 Italian lire, up from
1,362.25, and 1.1916 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1922.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $370.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Thursday's $375.75. In Zurich, gold fell to close
at a bid of $370.75, compared with $375.75 late Thursday. Earlier in
Hong Kong, gold closed at $377.39 bid, down from $377.87 on Thursday.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market, where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $5.25 a troy ounce, compared with
Thursday's $5.20. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery closed at $5.207 a troy ounce, up from Thursday's
settlement of $5.195.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
