<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   07-14 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market ran its July record to nine
gains in nine sessions with an afternoon advance Friday as traders
sorted through a series of new statistics on the state of the
economy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 16.50 to a new
post-crash high of 2,554.82, extending its gain for the week to
66.96 points.
   Since the end of June the average has jumped 114.76 points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 5 to 4 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
819 up, 659 down and 518 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 183.48 million
shares, up from 153.80 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in those
stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market,
totaled 214.58 million shares.
   Several reports from the government Friday morning lent support
to the widespread view that the pace of economic activity was
continuing to slow, fulfilling a primary goal of the Federal
Reserve's credit policy.
   The Fed reported a 0.2 percent drop in industrial production for
June, and a decline in capacity utilization at the nation's
factories, utilities and mines.
   Separately, the Labor Department said its producer price index of
finished goods dropped 0.1 percent last month. That number came in
below advance estimates calling for an increase of between 0.1 and
0.3 percent.
   However, the producer price index, excluding its sometimes
volatile food and energy components, was up 0.7 percent. That left
market participants without a conclusive signal of slackening
inflationary pressures, analysts said.
   Time Inc. fell 4} to 145\ and Warner Communications, the most
active Big Board issue, rose 2 to 64\.
   A judge in Delaware ruled against a bid by Paramount
Communications to block Time's planned acquisition of Warner, but
also barred Time from proceeding with its offer for 10 days pending
appeals.
   Alcoa, which received approval from directors to buy back as many
as 10 million of its shares, climbed 1{ to 68[.
   Other gainers among the blue chips included General Motors, up 1{
at 43{; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, up [ at 36]; Exxon, up | at
45|; General Electric, up \ at 54|, and Procter &amp; Gamble, up 1[ at
116{.
   Honeywell, up sharply in recent sessions on takeover speculation,
fell back 5 to 81 in the absence of any news to back up the
conjecture.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $12.17 billion, or 0.37
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained
.75 to 185.06.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 2.20 to 378.70, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was up 1.89 at 331.84.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market picked
up 1.01 to 448.90. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 368.12, up .48.
</TEXT>
