<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 2057EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-GasConference     07-14 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gas Conference,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pickens Says Best Energy Policy Is No Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas oil magnate T. Boone Pickens said Friday
the best thing Congress can do to promote the U.S. natural gas
industry is to keep its hands off.
   ``Energy policy to some is for Congress to give a tariff on
imported oil. This I am against _ that is not an energy policy,''
Pickens told a conference on natural gas.
   ``My message to our leaders in Washington is this: Thanks for
decontrol of natural gas. Now leave the industry alone. We can take
care of ourselves,'' he said.
   Pickens spoke at a two-day symposium on natural gas at the
University of Southern California that ended Friday. The conference
drew legislators, environmentalists, scientists and energy industry
experts.
   Pickens, founder and chief executive officer of Mesa Petroleum
Co., said demand for gas is lagging far behind available supply,
making it a bargain alternative to oil-based fuels.
   ``That's good news for energy security and the environment.
That's not good news for the producers _ like me,'' he said.
   Pickens said the price of natural gas would have to double from
current levels to be as costly as oil. But oversupply has put a stop
to exploratory drilling, he said.
   Mesa, based in Amarillo, Texas, bolstered its natural gas
investment before the petroleum market began to sour in 1986. Since
1985, Mesa has doubled its natural gas reserve base to an estimated
2.85 trillion cubic feet, Pickens said.
   Texas Railroad Commissioner John Sharp said California's market
potential could pull the Texas petroleum industry out of a slump.
   He said projects in California could bring Texas more than $3
billion in sales revenue in the next five years.
   ``We're in a downturn because of the oil crash, but we believe
natural gas is going to become our golden goose,'' Sharp said.
   Sharp said he, California Assembly Speaker Willie L. Brown, Jr.
and Rep. Joseph Kennedy, D-Mass., had agreed to form a panel to
consult with state legislators nationwide to draft a national clean
air plan relying on natural gas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
