<DOCNO> AP890714-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1806EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MortgageRates 1stLd-Writethru   07-14 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mortgage Rates, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0150,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fixed-Rate Mortgages Hit 2-year Low; VA Lowers Rate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with VA lowering rate. Also moving on general news
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fixed-rate mortgages dropped to the lowest
point in more than two years this week and in response the Veterans
Affairs Department said Friday it is lowering the interest rate cap
for VA-backed mortgages to 9.5 percent.
   Fixed-rate, 30-year mortgages averaged 9.82 percent this week,
down from 10.03 percent last week, according to the Federal Home
Loan Mortgage Corp., known as Freddie Mac.
   The government-created company, which finances the housing market
by purchasing mortgages, said it was the lowest weekly average since
the week ending April 10, 1987.
   One-year, adjustable-rate mortgages fell to 8.73 percent this
week, down from 8.85 percent a week earlier.
   Freddie Mac averages do not include special add-on fees known as
points.
   The VA said it was making the change in its rate, which will take
effect Monday, to reflect the recent interest rate decline in
financial markets. As a service to veterans, the VA insures
low-down-payment mortgages offered by private lenders and it sets a
maximum rate to ensure that veterans are not paying more than rates
on privately insured mortgages.
   The change brings the VA rate to the lowest level in 16 months.
The last change in the rate occurred June 5, when it went dropped to
10 percent from 10.5 percent, where it had been fixed since Dec. 19.
   ``This is certainly good news for the veteran who plans to
purchase a home in the months ahead,'' VA Secretary Edward J.
Derwinski said in a statement. ``For many veterans, it means they
may be able to buy homes that were beyond their means previously.''
   Also effective Monday, the VA will decrease other maximum rates
by half a percentage point, including: graduated payment mortgages,
to 9.75 percent; home improvement loans, to 12 percent, and mobile
lot and home loans, to 11.5 percent.
   Economist Lyle Gramley of the Mortgage Bankers Association
predicted that fixed-rate mortgages would fall by another quarter to
half percentage point by the end of the year.
   ``That's not a large decline, but every little bit helps the
housing market,'' he said.
   Housing has been one of the softest sectors in the economy this
year because the Federal Reserve Board, until recently, has been
nudging interest rates higher to curb inflation pressures. Since
early June, the Fed has reversed course, pushing short-term rates
down by a half a percentage point.
   Gramley said he expected a further loosening in short-term rates
from the Fed of a quarter to a half percentage point by the end of
the month, but that would not necessarily translate into a drop in
adjustable-rate mortgages.
   ``More and more, the S&amp;Ls that were offering extremely attractive
first-year teaser rates are no longer doing so because the federal
presence in that industry is discouraging that,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which does include
points in its averages, said Friday that fixed-rate mortgages
averaged 11.00 percent in early June, down from 11.49 percent in
early May. It was the lowest since the rates averaged 10.87 percent
in December.
   The most popular type of adjustable-rate mortgage, the type with
caps on how high the rate can rise, averaged 10.05 percent in early
June, down from 10.28 percent in May. It was the first drop since
October.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
