<DOCNO> AP890714-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1807EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp 1stLd-Writethru   07-14 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0284,0724</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold Prices Fall On Signs Of Slowing Economy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBs 3rd graf to CORRECT gold price to $372.20 sted $3.772;
Picks up 4th graf pvs, Analysts attributed...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold futures prices tumbled more than $6 an ounce Friday on New
York's Commmodity Exchange on expectations that investment demand
for the metal will fall following government reports indicating an
economic slowdown.
   On other markets, orange juice futures plunged; grains and
soybeans were higher; energy futures were mixed; and livestock and
meat futures were mixed.
   Gold settled $6.10 to $6.40 lower with the contract for delivery
in August at $372.20 a troy ounce. Silver was 0.8 cent to 1.5 cents
higher with July at $5.207 a troy ounce.
   Analysts attributed gold's retreat mainly to the Labor
Department's report of a 0.1 percent decline in wholesale prices in
June. The market had been expecting the report to show an increase
of 0.1 percent to 0.3 percent.
   The Commerce Department's report of a 0.4 percent drop in retail
sales last month _ making for the first back-to-back drop in more
than two years _ was also discouraging to gold traders.
   But the Federal Reserve's report of slowing industrial production
and factory use sent a mixed message to the inflation-sensitive gold
market, suggesting both a reduction in inflationary pressures _
which is bearish for gold _ and the possibility that the Fed will
continue to ease up on interest rates, which is bullish for gold.
   ``The economic reports were not all that bearish,'' said Fred
Demler, metals economist with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New
York.
   Demler pointed out that gold prices had risen by about $20 an
ounce since early June and said that when the wholesale-prices
report came out Friday morning, ``traders saw it as an opportunity
to take profits.''
   Frozen concentrated orange juice futures fell the permitted
5-cents-a-pound daily limit on the New York Cotton Exchange and the
soon-to-expire July contract, which has no limit, plunged 6.3 cents
to settle at $1.7135 a pound.
   Analysts linked the sharp drop to rumors that a large Florida
processor planned to cut prices due to a large Brazilian orange crop.
   Grain and soybean futures prices finished moderately higher on
the Chicago Board of Trade on bullish weather forecasts and
indications of Soviet purchases of South American soybean meal.
   Soybean traders shifted their attention back to supply-and-demand
factors after focusing for two days on wrangling between the
exchange and a large Italian company over the exchange's demand that
traders reduce their holdings in the July soybean contract.
   Soybean prices had fallen in early trading Friday following a
federal court ruling Thursday evening that upheld the exchange's
order.
   Two subsidiaries of the Italian agribusiness firm Ferruzzi
Finanziara SpA had sought a court order blocking the directive,
which Ferruzzi claimed was aimed at weakening its market position.
   Wheat settled 1 cent to 4{ cents higher with July at $3.95\ a
bushel; corn was { cent to 3{ cents higher with July at $2.59} a
bushel; oats were 2\ cents higher across the board with July at
$1.50{ a bushel; soybeans were 6 cents to 13{ cents higher with July
at $7.03{ a bushel.
   Energy futures finished lower in a light, lackluster session on
the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 12 cents lower to 14
cents higher with August at $20.32 a barrel; heating oil was .11
cent lower to .06 cent higher with August at 49.33 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .02 cent to .62 cent lower with August at
56.84 cents a gallon.
   Cattle futures finished narrowly mixed on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange as late profit-taking erased earlier gains linked to
stronger cash markets. Pork futures were mostly higher, boosted by
strong cash markets.
   Live cattle settled .17 cent lower to .50 cent higher with August
at 71.95 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .35 cent lower to .15
cent higher with August at 82.95 cents a pound; hogs were .08 cent
lower to .58 cent higher with July at 47.50 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .25 cent lower to .50 cent higher with July at
29.37 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
