<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 2110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PentagonProbe 1stLd-Writethru   07-14 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru,0731</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Plead Guilty in Pentagon Procurement Fraud Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to restore dropped word ``from,'' and subs 13th
graf, There was, with Unisys comment. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired Navy engineer Friday admitted
taking $475,000 in bribes from two major defense contractors as he
and four other people pleaded guilty in the widening Pentagon
procurement fraud probe.
   Garland L. Tomlin Jr., 59, admitted taking $400,000 from Sperry
Corp. and $75,000 from Honeywell Inc. in exchange for confidential
bid information about a multimillion-dollar contract to maintain the
electronic components of Navy weapons.
   The money was paid between 1982 and 1984 into a bank account that
Tomlin kept in the Bahamas in the name of a dummy corporation he set
up to receive the funds. Tomlin later transferred $400,000 to a
Swiss bank, according to court papers filed in U.S. District Court.
   Another former Navy engineer, Jerry L. Manning, 52, pleaded
guilty to a bribery conspiracy charge, admitting that he gave a
defense consultant bid information about a $20 million Navy
electronics contract.
   In addition, two defense consultants and a former marketing
manager for Unisys Corp., the successor to Sperry Corp., pleaded
guilty to separate charges relating to a scheme to conceal illegal
campaign contributions to several congressmen, including Rep Les
Aspin, D-Wisc., chairman of the House Armed Services Committee.
   There was no indication that Aspin or any of the other
congressmen who received donations knew the contributions were
illegally funneled to them by Sperry through defense consultants.
   All five defendants agreed to cooperate with the Justice
Department's continuing investigation of Pentagon procurement fraud
that has been nicknamed ``Operation Ill Wind.''
   Tomlin, who was a program engineer at the Navy's Space and Naval
Warfare Systems Command until his retirement in 1985, is the third
former Pentagon official to admit taking bribes.
   He pleaded guilty to conspiracy, receiving bribes and tax
evasion, charges that are punishable by a maximum sentence of 25
years and a $130,000 fine.
   Evidence that two major contractors paid Tomlin $475,000 in
bribes ``shows a disturbing pattern'' in the nation's defense
industry, U.S. Attorney Henry E. Hudson told reporters outside the
U.S. Courthouse here.
   Hudson acknowledged that investigators were unaware of Tomlin
until a former Unisys Corp. official and a consultant for the
company pleaded guilty last March and began cooperating with the
probe.
   ``We do not have information that enables us to comment at this
time.'' said Honeywell spokeswoman Sylvia Burgos Wander.
   ``There isn't anybody that would be involved in that thing that
hasn't been thrown out the door or disciplined,'' said Peter Hynes,
a spokesman for Unisys, which was formed in 1986 when Burroughs
Corp. acquired Sperry.
   According to court papers, Tomlin, who now lives near Orlando,
Fla., demanded $500,000 from Sperry Corp. in return for his
influence in helping the company obtain lucrative contracts for
computerized maintenance of electronic weapons components.
   The court papers revealed that the bribery arrangement was
approved by an unidentified high-ranking official of Sperry Corp.
and was also known to an executive at the company's Clearwater,
Fla., electronics plant.
   The Clearwater executive told Charles F. Gardner, then a Sperry
vice president in charge of the company's Surveillance and Fire
Control Systems Division in Great Neck, N.Y., that Tomlin was ready
to retire and ``wanted a nest egg.''
   Gardner, who pleaded guilty to an unrelated bribery charge in
March, obtained approval of the arrangement to pay Tomlin from his
superior.
   Former Unisys marketing manager Dennis Mitchell, 42, pleaded
guilty to participating in a scheme to pay $4,000 in illegal
corporate campaign contributions to Aspin and other House members.
   Mitchell, who worked with Gardner, admitted directing private
consultants to make the contributions as individuals with money they
were paid by Unisys.
   Unisys consultants Joseph S. Zuba, 67, of Mechanicsburg, Pa., and
Gerard J. Scarano, 74, admitted participating in the scheme to
conceal the illegal donations.
   Contributions were also made to Reps. Bob Roe, D-N.J., Bill
Young, D-Fla., George Hochbrueckner, D-N.Y. as well as former Rep.
Robert Badham, R-Calif. and the late Rep. Bill Chappell, D-Fla.,
according to court papers.
   U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton scheduled sentencings for the
five defendants for Sept. 29.
</TEXT>
