<DOCNO> AP890714-0285 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1821EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     07-14 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices sagged and long-term interest rates
rose in volatile trading Friday as the government reported economic
data that weren't weak enough to entice the credit markets.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond fell 13-32 point, or about
$4 per $1,000 face amount. Its yield, which moves in the opposite
direction from its price, climbed to 8.08 percent from 8.03 percent
late Thursday.
   Initially, evidence of economic weakness furnished by government
reports inspired buying enthusiasm in the bond market but the rally
soon faded.
   In two separate reports, the government said retail sales fell
0.4 percent in June and the Producer Price Index dipped by 0.1
percent, the first decline in this inflation measure in 18 months.
   Also, the Federal Reserve said U.S. industrial production fell
0.2 percent last month while U.S. factories, mines and utilities
used less of their operating capacity.
   Normally the credit market would welcome signs that a slowdown in
economic activity is being accompanied by a moderation in inflation.
   But Maria F. Ramirez, an economist at Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc., said the market had built up hopes ahead of the numbers and
pushed up bond prices to very high levels. When the reports merely
confirmed widely held views, traders decided to sell and collect
profits.
   ``It's not that the market is falling apart, it's retrenching a
little bit from very expensive levels,'' she said.
   Steven A. Wood, an economist, with BankAmerica Capital Markets
Group in San Francisco, said the rally fizzled as traders cashed in
profits on the belief the recent rally would go no further.
   He also said the new figures were not weak enough to convince the
Fed to lower interest rates further.
   ``At the least the next official move is going to be several
weeks off at the earliest,'' Wood said.
   In addition, he said the market was slowed by news that a
House-Senate conference committee neared an agreement on a thrift
bailout bill that would add $50 billion in financing to the U.S.
Treasury market over three years. With a greater supply in the
market, bond prices would likely drop.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
governments fell 1-16 point, intermediate maturities were 3-32 point
to \ point lower and long-term issues were down 5-16 point to 13-32
point, according to Telerate Inc., the financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, fell 1.96 to 1,189.14.
   In corporate trading, industrials slipped. Moody's Investment
Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return on a
portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or
longer, fell 0.17 to 329.87.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds closed at 94}, down [. The average yield to
maturity rose to 7.18 percent from 7.17 percent late Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to 8.08 percent as the
discount gained 6 basis points to 7.82 percent. Yields on six-month
bills rose to 8.01 percent as the discount rose 8 basis points to
7.61 percent. Yields on one-year bills climbed to 7.85 percent as
the discount gained 3 points to 7.33 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 93-16 percent, down from 95-16 percent late
Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
