<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 2129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SteelTalks     07-14 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steel Talks,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inland Ratifies Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the United Steelworkers union
overwhelmingly ratified a four-year contract offer that improves
wages and fringe benefits at Inland Steel Industries Inc. and
National Steel Corp., according to ballot tabulations Friday.
   At National, union members voted by an overwhelming 87 percent to
accept an offer nearly identical to one they had rejected by 61
percent in June despite a recommendation to ratify from their
negotiators.
   ``A no vote would have meant a debilitating strike that would
have destroyed National's productivity and profits for the entire
year,'' said Richard P. Coffee, vice president and chief company
negotiator.
   National's 50-month contract provides immediate $500 signing
bonuses, $500 advances on profit-sharing payments and base wage
increases of 31 cents per hour. Wage increases totalling $1.50 will
follow.
   At Inland, the vote was 7,909 to 586 to ratify base wage
increases of $1.50, a $500 signing bonus, inflation recognition
payments, an extra week of vacation and pensions of at least $1,000
per month for 30-year veterans.
   ``The sacrifices, dedication and hard work of our members have
helped turn this company around, which is why we were determined to
get a contract second to none,'' said Jack Parton, director of USW
District 31 and the union's chief negotiator with the nation's
sixth-largest steelmaker.
   ``We helped mix and bake the pie. Now we're getting our slice.
What could be more American than that?'' he said in a printed
statement.
   The new agreement takes effect Aug. 1 and expires July 31, 1983,
for 11,500 USW members at Inland's major plant at East Chicago, its
Minorca Mine at Virginia, Minn., and the Inland Lime and Stone Co.
at Gulliver, Mich.
   National employs about 7,000 union members at Ecorse, Mich.,
Granite City, Ill, and Portage, Ind.
   Officials of the USW and Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corp.,
meanwhile, said they have asked a federal bankruptcy judge to
approve hourly wage increases of 50 cents for union members at the
financially troubled company.
   Judge Warren Bentz scheduled a July 27 hearing on the issue.
   The request does not represent the opening of negotiations on a
new contract. Rather, it reflects production records that have been
set since the current pact was settled in October 1985. The
agreement does not expire until Wheeling-Pittsburgh emerges from
Chapter 11 reorganization.
</TEXT>
