<DOCNO> AP890714-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 2012EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern     07-14 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seeks $100 Million For Reorganization Expenses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines on Friday requested to use $100
million from a court-monitored escrow account toward its rebuilding
program, and union leaders said it was a sign the carrier is
struggling in the 4-month-old strike.
   A spokesman for the Miami-based carrier contends it was well
documented that Eastern could use some profits from the sale of
planes and other assets in its reorganization into a smaller company.
   Eastern filed papers in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in New York seeking
to free the $100 million to pay off expenses.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said he does not know when a
ruling may be issued.
   ``It was known from the beginning that we could use some of the
proceeds from our asset transactions for rebuilding,'' said Matell.
``I don't see why anyone is shocked by this.''
   But the Air Line Pilots Association on Friday said Eastern's
request for the funds suggests cash-flow problems in operating a
smaller carrier.
   ``Eastern's request is evidence that the company's reorganization
plan is seriously flawed,'' the ALPA statement said.
   Matell said Eastern is planning to sell $1.8 billion in assets,
including a proposed $206.5 million sale of 16 planes, two Canadian
routes and 13 gates at Philadelphia International Airport to Midway
Airlines. In June, Eastern sold its profitable Northeast shuttle
service to billionaire Donald Trump for $365 million.
   Eastern, which has tried to lure back passengers with reduced
fares, has announced plans to double its present flight schedule by
August, and build up to about 800 daily flights by the end of the
year.
   Eastern flew 1,040 flights per day before Machinists, flight
attendants and pilots walked off the job March 4. The airline sought
bankruptcy-court protection March 9.
   ALPA also reported that creditors committee attorney Joe Zweibel
said negotiations with Eastern are ``certainly going to be colored''
because of the request. Zweibel could not be reached for comment
Friday.
   Also Friday, ALPA released letters from two congressmen seeking
further information on the Eastern bankruptcy proceedings.
   U.S. Rep. Joe Kolter, D-Pa., has requested more information on a
study by bankruptcy court special examiner David Shapiro on
Eastern's relationship with sister carrier Continental, also owned
by Texas Air Corp. U.S. Rep. Douglas Bosco, D-Calif., requested
Shapiro's evaluation of the union-backed bid for Eastern by Chicago
options trader Joseph Ritchie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
