<FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 2127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Southmark-Bankruptcy 1stLd-Writethru   07-14 0765</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Southmark-Bankruptcy, 1st Ld-Writethru,0791</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Real Estate Firm Seeks Bankruptcy Refuge Because of Crushing
Debts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 7 grafs background at end.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southmark Corp., a large real estate company
plagued by indebtedness stemming partly from its reliance on
junk-bond financing, filed Friday for federal bankruptcy protection
from creditors.
   The troubled company had been attempting to avoid bankruptcy by
restructuring its property and financial holdings, but a $1 billion
first- quarter loss placed it in technical default on the junk
bonds. Creditors had begun taking steps to force the company into
bankruptcy.
   The Chapter 11 bankruptcy filing is one of the largest ever by a
company that used junk bonds as part of its financial strategy.
   Revco D.S. Inc., a national drugstore chain that relied on junk
bonds in a debt-financed takeover, sought Chapter 11 bankruptcy a
year ago after failing to make an interest payment on about $700
million in junk bonds.
   These bonds, commonly used by companies to bankroll expansion and
acquisitions, are considered low-investment grade securities. They
pay high rates of interest to compensate bondholders for the higher
risk of buying them.
   Southmark has about 32,000 employees and 13,000 shareholders.
Formerly known as Citizens and Southern Realty Investors, the
company buys, improves and sells real estate assets, manages
apartments, nursing homes, shopping centers and office buildings,
and owns San Jacinto Savings and Loan, the ninth-largest S&amp;L in
Texas.
   ``Southmark's previously disclosed forecasts show it cannot
continue to pay its interest and principal amortization obligations
beyond Nov. 1, 1989,'' Chairman Arthur G. Weiss said in announcing
the bankruptcy filing. ``It would be unfair to large portions of the
company's constituencies to continue to pay the debt service in the
interim, given all the circumstances.
   ``Accordingly, the board of directors has decided to discontinue
its policy of paying all debt service as it comes due.''
   Wall Street securities strategists that follow Southmark had been
predicting bankruptcy was a strong possibility and warned clients to
avoid the company's stock.
   ``We see scant appeal to the individual investor in these
shares,'' Mark Robertson, an analyst for the Value Line Investment
Survey in New York, wrote in a June report about thecompany's
deteriorating financial condition.
   Weiss said Southmark will continue to operate while reorganizing,
but could not predict when the company would emerge from bankruptcy.
   ``We chose reorganization through the court in light of our
responsibilities to all of Southmark's key constitutiencies _
creditors, stockholders and bondholders, employees, customers and
business partners, and vendors and suppliers.''
   As part of the filing, Southmark received agreement from the
Federal Home Loan Bank Board that as long as the company can meet
regulatory capital requirements at San Jacinto Savings and Loan, the
government will not seek to shut down the $3.5 billion-asset thrift.
   Weiss has said before he hopes to base Southmark's resurgence on
still-solvent San Jacinto.
   The filing in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Atlanta, where the company
is incorporated, lists assets of $1.05 billion and liabilities of
$1.4 billion, including $1.05 billion in unsecured debt sold through
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., a leading issuer and marketer of junk
bonds.
   Under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code, a company is
protected from creditors while it devises a way to pay its debts and
reorganize its business.
   Southmark, which began as a real estate investment trust
operation of Georgia's Citizens &amp; Southern Corp., used the junk
bonds to finance its rapid growth into a $8 billion-asset company
with holdings from campgrounds to insurance companies and a range of
real estate enterprises.
   However the company, which eventually moved to Dallas, has been
strapped by liquidity problems, as it became victimized by the
Southwest's real estate collapse and was left holding huge numbers
of non-performing assets.
   The liquidity problems eventually led to the ouster in January of
Chairman Gene E. Phillips and Vice Chairman William S. Friedman, who
were blamed for the situation.
   The board replaced with two with Weiss, a thrift executive from
Georgia. In the months since, the company has sold off about $170
million in assets to improve its cash position.
   ``We have improved liquidity through asset sales,'' Weiss said
Friday, adding that the company had $85 million on hand to pay
operating expenses.
   ``We will continue our program to sell selected assets,'' he
said, leaving the company with a core of real estate and thrift
operations. ``Without undue pressure from creditors, we can seek
maximum value for these assets.''
   The company said it would continue to seek buyers for its
insurance, recreational land, health care and gaming interests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
